<HEAD>Tobacco Companies Seek Another Mistrial Following Key Ruling</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DANIEL J. WAKIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEWARK, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Three tobacco companies in a cigarette liability suit will ask again for a mistrial following a judge's opinion that narrowed the claims against them, lawyers said Monday Lawyers for <ORGANIZATION> Philip </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Morris </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Liggett </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Group </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Lorillard </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> will file papers this week for a mistrial in <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> District Judge <PERSON> H. </PERSON> <PERSON> Lee </PERSON> <PERSON> Sarokin </PERSON>'s ruling last Thursday, said <PERSON> Steven </PERSON> <PERSON> C. </PERSON> <PERSON> Parrish </PERSON>, a lawyer for <PERSON> Morris </PERSON> and <ORGANIZATION> Lorillard </ORGANIZATION>. The companies have sought at least four mistrials since court proceedings began Feb. 1 and twice have sought to have <PERSON> Sarokin </PERSON> removed from the case. All those efforts were unsuccessful. <PERSON> Sarokin </PERSON> last week dismissed charges brought by <PERSON> Antonio </PERSON> <PERSON> Cipollone </PERSON> on behalf of his wife, <PERSON> Rose </PERSON>, who died of lung cancer at age 58 in 1984 after four decades of smoking the defendants' cigarettes. <PERSON> Cipollone </PERSON> had charged that the companies caused his wife's death by failing to market a safer product or do enough research on smoking. Although the judge ruled there was not enough evidence to support the claims, he decided that the evidence could lead to a finding that the companies engaged in conspiracy to cover up the dangers of smoking. The companies say the jury could not decide fairly on the remaining contentions because so much evidence on the safer cigarette and research issues has been introduced. <PERSON> Sarokin </PERSON> also let stand allegations that <ORGANIZATION> Liggett </ORGANIZATION> failed to warn Mrs. <PERSON> Cipollone </PERSON> about the dangers of cigarettes, but threw out the charge against <PERSON> Morris </PERSON> and <ORGANIZATION> Lorillard </ORGANIZATION> because she did not smoke their cigarettes after 1966, when <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> mandated warnings on cigarette packs.
