<HEAD>Construction Workers Begin Hunger Strike</HEAD>
<BYLINE>BY ELOY O. AGUILAR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANAGUA, Nicaragua (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Twenty-seven union members began a fast Monday as part of the two-month-old strike by thousands of construction workers demanding that the government grant wage increases and better working conditions. About 4,500 construction workers belonging to four opposition labor groups have been on strike since Feb. 25. The 27 hunger strikers began their fast at the General Workers Confederation headquarters in <LOCATION> Managua </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Carlos </PERSON> <PERSON> Nunez </PERSON>, president of the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Assembly </ORGANIZATION> and the Sandinista government's representative in talks with domestic opposition groups, called plans for the hunger strike `` a political publicity show.'' The construction workers went on strike after the leftist government decreed new wage scales and raised prices for basic staples on Feb. 14 as part of reforms intended to combat inflation, which reached 1,500 percent last year. Government officials have called the strike illegal, and Labor Minister <PERSON> Benedicto </PERSON> <PERSON> Meneses </PERSON> said only 600 workers have walked off their jobs. Monday night, the <ORGANIZATION> Labor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION> said negotiations with the strikers had been suspended. A statement said the unions were seeking `` to return to former payment systems that were eliminated precisely because they ran against the logic of the economic reform measures.'' It called on the strikers to return to work `` with the guarantee they wo n't be the object of any reprisals.'' The strike was called by the <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Independent </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Workers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Confederation </ORGANIZATION>, the Autonomous Workers Central of <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION>, the <ORGANIZATION> Confederation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trade </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Union </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Unity </ORGANIZATION> and the <ORGANIZATION> Labor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Action </ORGANIZATION> and Unity Central. They claim a membership of 100,000. There was no immediate response from the government to President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>'s message to <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> Monday in which he threatened to expand the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> embargo against <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION>. But on Sunday, President <PERSON> Daniel </PERSON> <PERSON> Ortega </PERSON> said that if the embargo continued, the Sandinistas would prohibit further shipments from the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> of equipment and other assistance to Nicaraguan organizations. The embargo had been set to expire April 30. It permits <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> aid and independent donations of supplies to `` democratic organizations,'' including newsprint and equipment for the opposition newspaper <ORGANIZATION> La </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Prensa </ORGANIZATION>.
