<HEAD>Jury Gets Song Copyright Case</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARLENE AIG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WHITE PLAINS, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A lawyer for rock singer <PERSON> Mick </PERSON> <PERSON> Jagger </PERSON> said Monday that there was only the `` barest, scintilla of evidence'' that <PERSON> Jagger </PERSON> ever heard a song he is accused of pirating in his 1985 hit `` Just Another Night.'' A federal court jury got the case Monday and deliberated 3 -LCB- hours before retiring for the evening. The jury listened to several tapes and reviewed <PERSON> Jagger </PERSON>'s travel schedule for early 1983, when reggae musician <PERSON> Patrick </PERSON> <PERSON> Alley </PERSON>'s song was broadcast in the <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> area. Testimony showed <PERSON> Jagger </PERSON> was in the area for five days in January and February of that year. Alley is suing <PERSON> Jagger </PERSON>, maintaining that <PERSON> Jagger </PERSON> infringed on his copyright of a song with the same name. Two alternate jurors, who were dismissed at start of deliberations, said it seemed to them that <PERSON> Jagger </PERSON> had developed his song independently. <PERSON> Peter </PERSON> <PERSON> Parcher </PERSON>, one of <PERSON> Jagger </PERSON>'s lawyers, said the only similarity between <PERSON> Jagger </PERSON>'s song and <PERSON> Alley </PERSON>'s 1979 song were the title and the theme of a man spending one more night with a woman, which is `` certainly not original.'' <PERSON> Parcher </PERSON> said there was only the `` barest, barest, scintilla of evidence'' that <PERSON> Jagger </PERSON> ever heard <PERSON> Alley </PERSON>'s song and added that his client had `` no motive to steal <PERSON> Patrick </PERSON> <PERSON> Alley </PERSON>'s song.'' <PERSON> Alley </PERSON>'s attorney, <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON> <PERSON> Farley </PERSON>, said <PERSON> Alley </PERSON> and <PERSON> Jagger </PERSON> had several mutual friends and acquaintances, and said the songs' similar choruses were `` the certain spark that made the songs memorable. If the jury decides <PERSON> Jagger </PERSON> infringed upon <PERSON> Alley </PERSON>'s copyright, damages would be decided in a second trial unless a settlement were reached. <PERSON> Alley </PERSON>'s lawyers say <PERSON> Jagger </PERSON> netted as much as $ 6 million from the song.
