<HEAD>Moderate Earthquake Shakes Gulf of Alaska</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A moderate earthquake occurred Monday in the <LOCATION> Gulf </LOCATION> <LOCATION> of </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Alaska </LOCATION>, the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Geological </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Survey </ORGANIZATION> reported. The tremor was centered about 350 miles southeast of <LOCATION> Anchorage </LOCATION> and occurred at 5:48 p.m. local time -LRB- 9:48 p.m EDT. -RRB- <ORGANIZATION> USGS </ORGANIZATION> earthquake monitors in <LOCATION> Golden </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Colo. </LOCATION>, said they recorded the tremor at a preliminary magnitude of 5.6 on the <PERSON> Richter </PERSON> scale. It was reported felt strongly in <LOCATION> Yakataga </LOCATION>. There was no immediate word of any damage or injuries. The Richter scale is an open-ended gauge of energy released by an earthquake as measured by ground motion recorded on a seismograph. Every increase of one number means that the ground motion is 10 times greater. A quake with a magnitude of 5 can cause considerable damage in a populated area.
