party, picking up 4th graf ``This place...''</NOTE>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto Staffing</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BILL STIEG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Elaine </PERSON>'s, whose clubby confines have provided refuge for a generation of creative minds and famous faces, celebrated its first quarter-century Monday with a celebrity bash. <PERSON> Elaine </PERSON> <PERSON> Kaufman </PERSON>, the rotund proprietress who rewards loyalty and fame with choice tables, expected her `` nice, neighborhood restaurant'' to be filled with people whose names have filled gossip columns for years. For the party, the checked-cloth-covered tables were removed, the ceiling was filled with balloons, and rotating spotlights were set up outside. A crowd of onlookers watched as celebrities filed by: <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Segal </PERSON>, <PERSON> Sidney </PERSON> <PERSON> Lumet </PERSON>, <PERSON> Pat </PERSON> <PERSON> Kennedy </PERSON> <PERSON> Lawford </PERSON>, <PERSON> Peter </PERSON> <PERSON> Maas </PERSON>, <PERSON> Eli </PERSON> <PERSON> Wallach </PERSON>, <PERSON> Iman </PERSON>, <PERSON> Connie </PERSON> <PERSON> Chung </PERSON>, <PERSON> Raquel </PERSON> <PERSON> Welch </PERSON>, <PERSON> Billy </PERSON> <PERSON> Dee </PERSON> <PERSON> Williams </PERSON>, <PERSON> Cheryl </PERSON> <PERSON> Tiegs </PERSON>, <PERSON> Halston </PERSON>, <PERSON> Terry </PERSON> <PERSON> Southern </PERSON>, <PERSON> Jerzy </PERSON> <PERSON> Kosinski </PERSON>. `` The Eighth Avenue subway at rush hour is a picnic compared to this,'' said <PERSON> Jackie </PERSON> <PERSON> Mason </PERSON> in the jam-packed interior. `` These people are used to being treated like kings here. Tonight they are treated like cockroaches.'' And this was early by <PERSON> Elaine </PERSON>'s standards: 10 p.m. `` This place is a living <ORGANIZATION> People </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> magazine </ORGANIZATION>,'' said bartender <PERSON> Brian </PERSON> <PERSON> McDonald </PERSON>. But a glitzy night of revelry is hardly what the regulars think of when they think of <PERSON> Elaine </PERSON>'s. A comfortable tavern chockablock with posters, photos and book covers donated by its celebrated clientele, <PERSON> Elaine </PERSON>'s has evolved from a writer's and artists' hangout to a required stop in the city's see-and-be-seen circuit. Saturday night was typical: <PERSON> Woody </PERSON> <PERSON> Allen </PERSON>, <PERSON> Albert </PERSON> <PERSON> Finney </PERSON> and <PERSON> Paloma </PERSON> <PERSON> Picasso </PERSON>, among others. <PERSON> Prince </PERSON> was there a couple of weeks ago. <PERSON> Allen </PERSON> opened his cinematic valentine to <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>, `` <LOCATION> Manhattan </LOCATION>,'' with a scene set in <PERSON> Elaine </PERSON>'s. He's a regular, <PERSON> Elaine </PERSON> said, because `` He loves to people-watch. It's comfortable, nobody bothers him, we make him what he wants.'' The food, critics love to point out, is undistinguished. It's the restaurant `` where you get the least for your money,'' according to the Zagat Restaurant Survey And its reputation, deserved or not, is that service can be rude and inattentive if you've never made the best-seller list. Even writer <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Plimpton </PERSON>, among the most loyal of regulars, said, `` I'm afraid you do n't get treated very well if you do n't have a pencil in your top pocket.'' Nevertheless, it usually fills up by 9 p.m. with stars, stargazers, yuppies and just neighborhood folks. Those at the bar can nurse $ 3.50 beers and watch the scene. In a city where formality sometimes chokes the fun out of a meal, <PERSON> Elaine </PERSON>'s is a relaxing, familiar retreat, its regulars say. `` It offers an ambience of camaraderie that is centered on <PERSON> Elaine </PERSON> herself _ she's the den mother there,'' said author <PERSON> Gay </PERSON> <PERSON> Talese </PERSON>, adding: `` It's like a boarding house, you've got the round table, and you do n't need a reservation, if you're a friend of hers.'' If you're not, you'll sit farther back. Detractors and celebrity-watchers alike make too big a deal out of the place, <PERSON> Elaine </PERSON> said. `` I think a lot of people just come in to have dinner,'' she said. `` And you have a good time. A good bottle of wine, a nice plate of pasta _ I mean, that's life.'' When she plunked down $ 10,000 for the bar in 1963, she already knew some show folk, writers and artists from her days as a waitress and cafe manager in <LOCATION> Greenwich </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Village </LOCATION>. `` Actually, what I did was just bring the Village uptown,'' she said. `` Then, it was barely going, a rather sleepy place up there,'' <PERSON> Plimpton </PERSON> recalled. `` Friends got their friends to go. It was just one room, very quiet, and we would play darts. `` <PERSON> Elaine </PERSON> made sure it was a very informal, non-frantic atmosphere. Now it's a bit different, and more expensive.'' Overall, however, it's much the same as it was 25 years ago, said <PERSON> Elaine </PERSON>. Regulars can count on a good table, and count on her being there. `` I'm not changing it all the time,'' she said. `` I'm not going with the current trend.''
