<SECOND>PM-Ficus Outbreak,0352</SECOND>
<HEAD>Ficus Trees Growing Wild In South Florida</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The ficus tree, long considered sterile, now has a way to reproduce on its own, and scientists in <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION> are bracing for an explosion of the lush, iron-rooted titan of the tropics. The ficus benjamina, or weeping fig, may be a finicky house plant, but it grows very large very fast in hospitable climates. Its dense crown snuff out plants below, and its notorious roots can muscle through pavement to strangle other large trees and choke pipes. Ficus had been held in check by their inability to reproduce _ until now. Tiny insects from <LOCATION> India </LOCATION> and tropical regions have found their way to <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION> and are allowing the trees to pollinate the wild seeds, which are spread by birds and animals that eat the small berries. A single tree can produce millions of seeds a year. `` You get the idea it's just a rain of these things coming down all the time,'' said <PERSON> Doyle </PERSON> <PERSON> McKey </PERSON>, tropical biologist at the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Miami </ORGANIZATION>, where ficus have been seen sprouting on stone walls and sidewalk cracks. Until such insects as the female fig wasp came to <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION>, ficus could only be reproduced in plant nurseries from other cuttings. That meant the spread of ficus was limited to where property owners planted them. Most of the wild seedlings spotted so far are small, but the growth has been widespread. They have been seen dotting lawns and forests throughout <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION> and north to the <LOCATION> Tampa </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bay </LOCATION> area. `` I think we're going to see our landscape change,'' said <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Knight </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON>, a researcher at the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agriculture </ORGANIZATION>'s subtropical research station in <LOCATION> Coral </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Gables </LOCATION> It's too soon to tell whether they'll be mostly a suburban nuisance or begin to crowd out native vegetation in unspoiled areas, scientists say. `` They might become a pest in our nature preserves and hammocks,'' <PERSON> McKey </PERSON> said recently. `` Otherwise, the habitat is going to be in <LOCATION> suburbia </LOCATION> in our landscapes, where everything else is unnatural.''
</TEXT>
