<HEAD>Cuba Accepting Church To Certain Extent</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Also in Monday AMs report.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By TINA SUSMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HAVANA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The visit last week of <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> Cardinal <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> O'Connor </PERSON> to <LOCATION> Cuba </LOCATION> marked the latest in a series of moves indicating greater government acceptance of religion in this communist nation. Thousands of worshipers filled cathedrals in <LOCATION> Havana </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Santiago </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Cuba </LOCATION>, for Masses celebrated by the Roman Catholic cardinal during his four-day visit. One woman, <PERSON> Ruby </PERSON> <PERSON> Jane </PERSON> <PERSON> Padron </PERSON>, said her husband, <PERSON> Alberto </PERSON>, had been imprisoned 22 years simply for being a practicing <ORGANIZATION> Catholic </ORGANIZATION>. But when asked if she was afraid to be at the <LOCATION> Mass </LOCATION> in <LOCATION> Havana </LOCATION>, she said: `` Nervous? No, we are not nervous here. No, that was in the past. It's different now. The hands of the communists are easier _ not so harsh.'' <LOCATION> Cuban </LOCATION> leader <PERSON> Fidel </PERSON> <PERSON> Castro </PERSON> met with <PERSON> O'Connor </PERSON> on Wednesday night and, according to the cardinal, agreed to grant more visas for foreign nuns to come to <LOCATION> Cuba </LOCATION>. Last month, <LOCATION> Cuba </LOCATION> authorized 19 foreign priests and an expatriate Cuban clergyman to work in <LOCATION> Cuba </LOCATION>, along with the 210 priests already in the communist nation. Last year, the government allowed importation of 30,000 Bibles. And in 1986, the leadership called on citizens to respect the beliefs of churchgoers. <LOCATION> Cuba </LOCATION> now has an office of religious affairs, and <PERSON> Castro </PERSON> has made no secret of the fact that he would welcome a visit by the pope. There apparently is more than one reason for this relaxation. The number of Roman Catholics has decreased to an acceptable level, by government standards. When <PERSON> Castro </PERSON> siezed power in 1959 about 85 percent of Cubans were Roman Catholics. Now Roman Catholics make up an estimated 41 percent of <LOCATION> Cuba </LOCATION>'s 10.2 million people. In addition, the government has realized that it's possible to be loyal both to the church and to the revolution. `` Theoretically it is possible, and in reality it also is,'' Education Minister <PERSON> Jose </PERSON> <PERSON> Ramon </PERSON> <PERSON> Fernandez </PERSON> told reporters while touring <LOCATION> Havana </LOCATION>'s historical colonial section with <PERSON> O'Connor </PERSON>. Even <PERSON> O'Connor </PERSON> told reporters, `` All of us in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> would be revolutionaries, I guess. We are the product of a revolution. I've never thought of myself as a bad Catholic for that reason.'' <LOCATION> Cuba </LOCATION>'s treatment of religion began changing around 1985 after the publication of the book `` Fidel and Religion,'' by the Rev. <PERSON> Carlos </PERSON> <PERSON> Alberto </PERSON> <PERSON> Christo </PERSON>, a Brazilian priest. <PERSON> Castro </PERSON> told <PERSON> Christo </PERSON> he never opposed the <ORGANIZATION> Catholic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Chuch </ORGANIZATION> as an institution _ only those `` militant Catholics ... from the rich class that supported the counterrevolution.'' He described as `` models for Communists'' the <ORGANIZATION> Catholic </ORGANIZATION> nuns who work in Cuban hospitals and mental asylums. <PERSON> O'Connor </PERSON> said he drummed the idea of the church's resourcefulness into <PERSON> Castro </PERSON> during their talk, and <PERSON> Castro </PERSON> responded eagerly <PERSON> Castro </PERSON> welcomed the idea of having an American clergyman as a liaison between the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> government and Cuban political prisoners in an attempt to get the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> to accept the prisoners, the cardinal said. The two also discussed the possibility of church assistance in helping <LOCATION> Cuba </LOCATION> obtain medical supplies unavailable on the island nation. Closer church-state relations and especially a papal visit would boost <LOCATION> Cuba </LOCATION>'s image abroad. `` The church could be very very helpful in explaining to the world at large what is legitimate in the revolutionary government here in <LOCATION> Cuba </LOCATION>,'' <PERSON> O'Connor </PERSON> said. Government officials turned out in force to greet <PERSON> O'Connor </PERSON>, and the cardinal indicated the <LOCATION> Vatican </LOCATION> would pay close attention to this in deciding whether <LOCATION> Cuba </LOCATION> should be added to the <PERSON> pope </PERSON>'s future itinerary. The reaction in churches and on the street to <PERSON> O'Connor </PERSON>'s presence gave credence to the cardinal's comment that the faith in <LOCATION> Cuba </LOCATION> is still solid, despite years of restrictions One elderly woman clutching rosary beads rushed up to pastor <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> McCarthy </PERSON>, <PERSON> O'Connor </PERSON>'s secretary, as he walked through the streets of <LOCATION> Old </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Havana </LOCATION> and told him what a wonderful thing the cardinal's visit was. `` No political system, no ideology, is going to be ultimately successful in driving -LRB- the faith -RRB- out,'' <PERSON> O'Connor </PERSON> said. `` Success could be achieved for a period of time, but the seed is there, and it keeps springing back into flower.''
