<HEAD>Italy Re-examining Fascist Past</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Also in Monday AMs report.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By VICTOR L. SIMPSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ROME (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A recent series of books and articles and a sharp political debate have bared some of the darkest and most sensitive moments of <LOCATION> Italy </LOCATION>'s fascist past. The treatment of Jews, the conduct of <LOCATION> Italy </LOCATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> and the plight of Italian soldiers left to choose sides between the <ORGANIZATION> Nazis </ORGANIZATION> and the Allies all have come under scrutiny. Some of the issues are being used as fuel in current political maneuvering, particularly in the struggle between the Communists and the Socialists for dominance of the Italian left. Others have surfaced as <LOCATION> Italy </LOCATION>'s Jewish community prepares to mark the 50th anniversary of the racial laws enacted by <PERSON> Benito </PERSON> <PERSON> Mussolini </PERSON>'s fascist dictatorship, which foreshadowed deportations to Nazi death camps. The controversy involving the alleged complicity in war crimes of President <PERSON> Kurt </PERSON> <PERSON> Waldheim </PERSON> in neighboring <LOCATION> Austria </LOCATION> brought a reminder that Italian as well as Nazi troops were occupying the <LOCATION> Balkans </LOCATION>. The probing has touched some raw nerves. When <PERSON> Renzo </PERSON> <PERSON> De </PERSON> <PERSON> Felice </PERSON>, a leading historian who wrote a highly respected biography of <PERSON> Mussolini </PERSON>, lectured at <ORGANIZATION> Rome </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION>, he was heckled and harassed by leftist students. <PERSON> De </PERSON> <PERSON> Felice </PERSON> recently suggested anti-fascism was mainly serving the <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> and should be abandoned. But other books praise Italians who fought fascism. `` We all looked at ourselves as anti-fascist and on the side of the Allies,'' says <PERSON> Furio </PERSON> <PERSON> Colombo </PERSON>, the president of <ORGANIZATION> Fiat </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> U.S.A. </ORGANIZATION> and a <ORGANIZATION> Columbia </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> lecturer who wrote the preface to the Italian edition of American historian <PERSON> Susan </PERSON> <PERSON> Zuccotti </PERSON>'s book `` The Italians and the Holocaust.'' The book, published here in March by <ORGANIZATION> Mondadori </ORGANIZATION>, gives generally high marks to Italians, noting that <LOCATION> Italy </LOCATION> shares with <LOCATION> Denmark </LOCATION> the merit of the highest percentage of Jews saved. But it also makes the point that Italians bear a share of guilt. More than 8,000 Jews were deported and only about 900 of them survived. `` It should n't be possible any longer to boast of the ` minimum number' of Italian Jews put to death,'' said <LOCATION> Colombo </LOCATION> in his preface. `` Only one Italian Jew persecuted -LRB- and there were thousands -RRB- would already represent a crime serious enough to force a collective rethinking of the past.'' Any confusion about Italians coming to terms with the past can perhaps be attributed in part to the shifting loyalties that evolved as <LOCATION> Italy </LOCATION> became bogged down in World War II, leaving the country in a `` no man's land'' between winners and losers at the end. <PERSON> Mussolini </PERSON> came to power in 1922, launched an invasion of <LOCATION> Ethiopia </LOCATION> in 1936 and took <LOCATION> Italy </LOCATION> into World War II on the side of <ORGANIZATION> Nazi </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Germany </ORGANIZATION> and <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>. He was ousted from power in <LOCATION> Rome </LOCATION> in July 1943 after Allied forces landed in <LOCATION> Sicily </LOCATION>. In September 1943, <LOCATION> Italy </LOCATION> surrendered unconditionally to the Allies. In the meantime, the Germans helped <PERSON> Mussolini </PERSON> escape from prison and established him in a puppet regime in the north. Italian partisans captured <PERSON> Mussolini </PERSON> and his mistress, <PERSON> Clara </PERSON> <PERSON> Petacci </PERSON>, on April 27, 1945, shot them and hung their bodies upside down at a gasoline station near <LOCATION> Milan </LOCATION>. One of the bitterest quarrels to emerge has pitted Communist and <ORGANIZATION> Socialist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> officials over whether <PERSON> Palmiro </PERSON> <PERSON> Togliatti </PERSON>, who led the Communists from 1927 until his death in 1964, had abandoned the party's founder, <PERSON> Antonio </PERSON> <PERSON> Gramsci </PERSON>, to fascist prison. The allegations center over whether <LOCATION> Togliatti </LOCATION>, from his exile in <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION>, had not tried to press the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> to negotiate the freedom of <PERSON> Gramsci </PERSON>, known more as a liberal thinker than the party boss. `` <LOCATION> Togliatti </LOCATION> was neither a saint nor a hero,'' said former Socialist Premier <PERSON> Bettino </PERSON> <PERSON> Craxi </PERSON>, drawing the rage of the Communist leadership. Historian <PERSON> De </PERSON> <PERSON> Felice </PERSON>'s point is that <LOCATION> Italy </LOCATION> is ill-served by a continued use of anti-fascism as a political reference point, as if anti-fascist meant democratic. `` I do n't say you have to forget fascism,'' <PERSON> De </PERSON> <PERSON> Felice </PERSON> said in an interview with The <ORGANIZATION> Associated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION>. `` I say that today, that the use of the label anti-fascism has allowed the Communists to present themselves as the other parties. It has given them a common heritage.'' <PERSON> De </PERSON> <PERSON> Felice </PERSON> also contends that the postwar laws forbidding re-establishment of the <ORGANIZATION> Fascist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> are anachronistic, since there is a neo-fascist party, the Italian <ORGANIZATION> Social </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Movement </ORGANIZATION>, which has consistently gathered around 6 percent of the vote. The historian also told <ORGANIZATION> Milan </ORGANIZATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Corriere </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> della </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Sera </ORGANIZATION> that the `` myth'' of fascism is over, noting that <PERSON> Mussolini </PERSON>'s granddaughter, a budding actress, recently posed topless in an Italian men's magazine Others disagree that it's time to move on. <LOCATION> Colombo </LOCATION>, for example, said that while he may agree with <PERSON> De </PERSON> <PERSON> Felice </PERSON> intellectually `` some signal still has to be given'' about the evils of fascism. The Jewish community of about 40,000 plans major commemorations this fall of the enactment of the racial laws that expelled Jews from government positions and the military and put restrictions on their work, schooling and possession of property. `` It's too soon to say let bygones be bygones,'' said <PERSON> Tullia </PERSON> <PERSON> Zevi </PERSON>, president of the Union of Italian Jewish Communities. Jewish leaders note that until 1938 the Jewish community was fully integrated in Italian society, holding important posts in the military and government and even the Fascist Party. Another a point of controversy is whether <PERSON> Pope </PERSON> <PERSON> Pius </PERSON> <PERSON> XII </PERSON> did all he could to save the Jews. The <PERSON> Zuccotti </PERSON> book praises the efforts of individual priests to protect Italian Jews. The <LOCATION> Vatican </LOCATION>, which has repeatedly defended the efforts of the pope, on April 13 ran excerpts in its daily newspaper from a new book by a German historian contesting allegations against <PERSON> Pius </PERSON> <PERSON> XII </PERSON>. The newspaper, <PERSON> L'Osservatore </PERSON> <PERSON> Romano </PERSON>, called it a `` vibrant and direct response to the denigrators of the pontiff.''
