<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> ABC </ORGANIZATION>'s `` Nightline'' tonight begins a week of shows live from <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>, including a three-hour panel discussion in <LOCATION> Jerusalem </LOCATION> before an audience of 700 Israelis and Palestinians. `` Good Lord only knows'' how the live discussion will turn out, said `` Nightline'' anchor <PERSON> Ted </PERSON> <PERSON> Koppel </PERSON>, who has done shows in previous years from <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>, the <LOCATION> Philippines </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Southeast </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Asia </LOCATION>. `` This just seemed like one of those subjects that is so rich and meaty it really ca n't be covered in an hour or two over here, so we're going to spend a week over there,'' said <PERSON> Koppel </PERSON> before leaving for <LOCATION> Jerusalem </LOCATION> from which most of the shows will be broadcast. Monday night's one-hour broadcast will feature an interview with <LOCATION> Israeli </LOCATION> Defense Minister <PERSON> Yitzak </PERSON> <PERSON> Rabin </PERSON>, as well as other guests not yet lined up as of this weekend. Likewise, guests for the `` town hall meeting'' on Tuesday had not been determined. <PERSON> Koppel </PERSON> said participants would include Israelis and Palestinians, though selection of <LOCATION> Palestinian </LOCATION> representatives was difficult because Israeli government officials will not participate if there's anyone sympathetic to the <ORGANIZATION> Palestine </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Liberation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Organization </ORGANIZATION> involved. The trip was planned last year, <PERSON> Koppel </PERSON> said, before the recent violence on the Israeli-occupied <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bank </LOCATION> prompted new interest in the conflict between <LOCATION> Palestinians </LOCATION> and Israelis. `` What we're trying to do is make it clearer to an American audience what the different positions are and also 