<HEAD>Shultz Leaves Soviet Union</HEAD>
<HEAD>PRECEDE, Moscow</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: UPDATES throughout with Shultz in Tblisi, Kiev; picks up 4th
pvs: Shultz and ...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By BARRY SCHWEID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Diplomatic Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TBLISI, USSR (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Secretary of State <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> P. </PERSON> <PERSON> Shultz </PERSON> attended religious services in the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> on Sunday, extolling the `` spread and acceptance of faith'' in a subtle jab at this nation's institutionalized atheism <PERSON> Shultz </PERSON> flew out of <LOCATION> Tbilisi </LOCATION>, the capital of the southern Soviet republic of <LOCATION> Georgia </LOCATION> in the <LOCATION> Caucasus </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Mountains </LOCATION>, after a day of sightseeing. He headed for <LOCATION> Brussels </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Belgium </LOCATION>, to brief members of the <ORGANIZATION> North </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Atlantic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Treaty </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Organization </ORGANIZATION> on his talks in <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> Thursday and Friday with Soviet leader <PERSON> Mikhail </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> and Soviet Foreign Minister <PERSON> Eduard </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Shevardnadze </PERSON>. Before he left, in <LOCATION> Tblisi </LOCATION> and in <LOCATION> Kiev </LOCATION>, he delivered an overt message on religious freedom, attending the Georgian Orthodox Cathedral here Sunday and <ORGANIZATION> St. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Sophia </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cathedral </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Kiev </LOCATION> on Saturday. Even at a lavish lunch here with dozens of writers, singers and artists, <PERSON> Shultz </PERSON> went out of his way in a toast to say: `` I could feel, in a sense, I was in the presence of the Creator.'' In <LOCATION> Kiev </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Shultz </PERSON> also visited <PERSON> Babi </PERSON> <PERSON> Yar </PERSON>, the Nazi killing ground in World War II, where tens of thousands of Jews and other Ukrainians were slaughtered. `` We have to say to ourselves always, never again,'' <PERSON> Shultz </PERSON> vowed. In <LOCATION> St. </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Sophia </LOCATION>'s, a cathedral that <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> authorities have converted into a museum, <PERSON> Shultz </PERSON> said the majestic building `` just shows you the commitment of and power of religion.'' In an evolving human rights policy, <PERSON> Shultz </PERSON> has kept up <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> pressure on the Soviets to expand Jewish emigration while pressing for more freedom of religious practices for all citizens. <LOCATION> Tblisi </LOCATION>, a relatively relaxed city far from <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION>, has functioning churches and even two jewish synagogues. <PERSON> Shultz </PERSON>, addressing the patriarch, <PERSON> Iliya </PERSON> <PERSON> II </PERSON>, and the congregants who jammed the small cathedral, said he understood their desire for `` progress in belief, in religion.'' `` ` You must be meaning progress in the spread and acceptance of faith because it has an immense continuity,'' <PERSON> Shultz </PERSON> said, `` It could n't be more evident them being here in this church.'' <PERSON> Shultz </PERSON> and <PERSON> Shevardnadze </PERSON> reported little progress in the talks, which focused on a treaty that would halve <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> and Soviet arsenals of strategic nuclear weapons. The goal had been to complete the treaty by May 29 when President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> journeys to <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> for a summit meeting with <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>. But officials have expressed doubt the pact will be ready by then because too many disagreements remain.
