<HEAD>On The Light Side</HEAD>
<DATELINE>KEWANEE, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Oliver </PERSON> <PERSON> Ratliff </PERSON> does n't know what the 12,000-pound acorn-shaped piece of iron is, but he likes it. Workers from <ORGANIZATION> Ratliff </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bros. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> were clearing a site for a restaurant in <LOCATION> Abingdon </LOCATION> when they dug up the massive object buried about a foot underground. His workers hauled it back to <LOCATION> Kewanee </LOCATION>, thinking the iron might be worth several hundred dollars. But <PERSON> Ratliff </PERSON> says the mystery object has brought him so much attention he wo n't scrap it. Now, <LOCATION> Kewanee </LOCATION> is abuzz as folks in this town of 14,500 try to figure out what it is. `` At first we were worried it was a bomb,'' said <PERSON> Ratliff </PERSON>, 68, who has unearthed many strange things in his 46 years in the construction business. <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION> bomb specialists examined the find Tuesday and determined it was n't a bomb. But that was all they could say. `` Everyone in town is plotting and scheming to explain what this thing is,'' said <PERSON> Steve </PERSON> <PERSON> Bialowbreski </PERSON>, a truck dispatcher at <PERSON> Ratliff </PERSON>'s. `` There is no way it's a wrecking ball because it's too heavy and there's no way to hook on to it.'' <PERSON> Ratliff </PERSON> ran his hand along the rusted exterior of the object as it sat Friday in the rear of his company's yard. `` Whatever it is, it sure was made nice,'' he said. Some <PERSON> Ratliff </PERSON> workers think the 3-by-5-foot hunk of iron is an old bank safe. Retiree <PERSON> Jim </PERSON> <PERSON> Cinnamon </PERSON> speculated that the thing was a weight used to anchor something huge _ a blimp or a crane; farmer <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Betts </PERSON> theorized it's the base for a flagpole. <PERSON> Ratliff </PERSON>