<HEAD>Gorbachev Has Work Cut Out Improving Soviet Economy</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TIM AHERN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Soviet leader <PERSON> Mikhail </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> is facing serious obstacles in his effort to overhaul the troubled, inefficient Soviet economy and things are n't likely to improve anytime soon, according to <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> intelligence agencies. `` <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>'s ambitious program to create a modern, more dynamic Soviet economy ran into trouble in 1987,'' says a joint study by the <ORGANIZATION> Central </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Intelligence </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agency </ORGANIZATION> and the <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Intelligence </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agency </ORGANIZATION>. `` The short-term outlook for <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>'s economic program is not good,'' concluded the study, which was released Sunday by the congressional <ORGANIZATION> Joint </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Economic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION>. `` The real loser in 1987 appeared to be the consumer, who _ now three years into <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>'s economic program _ has seen almost no increase in his standard of living,'' the study said. The main problems last year were poor weather and resistance to change in the huge, slow-moving Soviet bureaucracy, said the report. As a result, the Soviet gross national product grew only 0.5 percent last year, compared with a 3.9 percent increase in 1986, which was the first full year of <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>'s term. The gross national product is the total value of all goods and services produced and is a key measure of an economy. By contrast, the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> GNP grew by 2.9 percent in both 1986 and 1987, but the American economy is much larger and exact comparisons are difficult to make. Sen. <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Proxmire </PERSON>, D-Wis., chairman of the <ORGANIZATION> Joint </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Economic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION>, said the study shows `` the Soviet economy did not pause last year, it stumbled This does not mean that the reform program is necessarily doomed or that <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> will be ousted.'' `` It is still too soon to pass judgment on the reforms or on <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>'s leadership,'' <PERSON> Proxmire </PERSON> said. The study predicted that unless <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> can turn things around, he faces trouble. `` Tension within society and the leadership will increase,'' it said. `` Bureaucrats will become increasingly frustrated by loss of privileges and status and by demands that they show greater initiative. Military leaders are likely to become more and more uneasy if benefits from the industrial modernization fail to materialize. `` Soviet citizens will need to see some improvement in living standards if the regime is to achieve necessary gains in worker productivity and avoid widespread discontent,'' the study said. `` Failure to head off these tensions would, at a minimum, make it more difficult to pursue his economic program vigorously and could ultimately call into question his strong political position at home,'' the study said. The study was presented April 13. The <ORGANIZATION> Joint </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Economic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> released a declassified version. When <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> took over in March 1985, the study noted, he inherited an aging, backward, extremely inefficient economy. He made reform a top priority. Last year's problems were caused by a combination of factors, the study said. `` Familiar problems with poor weather and transportation bottlenecks were compounded by the disruptions caused by the introduction of economic reforms,'' it said. Agricultural output fell because of bad weather. Industrial quality control measures also `` proved to be particularly disruptive, especially early in the year.'' Thus, industry only grew 1.5 percent and the civilian machine-building sector did n't grow at all
</TEXT>
