<HEAD>Biggest Opponent Of West Virginia's Governor Is His Self-Created
Image</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto CN2</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By A.V. GALLAGHER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHARLESTON, W.Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Gov. <PERSON> Arch </PERSON> <PERSON> Moore </PERSON> is finding that perhaps his toughest opponent in his re-election bid is the image he helped create for himself. The almost mythical <PERSON> Moore </PERSON> benefited from an influx of federal funds and a healthy economy as he opened highways, constructed buildings and created jobs during his first two terms from 1969 to 1977. But he has been criticized during his third term as skippering a rudderless ship awash in financial problems that the captain can not or will not control. <PERSON> Moore </PERSON>, 65, faces his first serious political challenge in May 10's <ORGANIZATION> GOP </ORGANIZATION> primary in which he is seeking an unprecedented fourth term. His opponent, <LOCATION> Morgantown </LOCATION> businessman <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Raese </PERSON>, is an aggressive campaigner who has capitalized on the state's woes. `` Everybody changes as they mature,'' former state <ORGANIZATION> GOP </ORGANIZATION> Chairman <PERSON> Kent </PERSON> <PERSON> Strange </PERSON> <PERSON> Hall </PERSON> said of <PERSON> Moore </PERSON>. `` I think the real changes are the circumstances and conditions in which he's operating. `` Number one, he does n't have the money that was available either through federal funding or the state's economy. And secondly, he does n't have the team of department heads and advisers he had in the first eight years.'' <PERSON> Moore </PERSON>'s administrative abilities have drawn the most fire. Even administration officials concede that when <PERSON> Moore </PERSON> was returned to office in 1984, people expected a miracle turnaround that <PERSON> Moore </PERSON> has been unable to produce. The governor can point to a record of hard work, a gradual reduction in the unemployment rate and increased industrial development, but the days of major announcements have ended. A spokesman for the state <ORGANIZATION> Manufacturers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION>, for instance, says the state has lost 36 major plants between 1979 and 1986, idling 4,450 workers, and said 28,000 manufacturing jobs were lost in the plants that remain open. <PERSON> Moore </PERSON>'s first two terms were marked by a burgeoning economy. Federal money poured into the state, and <PERSON> Moore </PERSON> took the credit. He seemed to be everywhere at once, opening 225 miles of <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Virginia </LOCATION>'s 515 miles of interstate highway, overseeing construction of the state Science and Cultural Center on the Capitol grounds, and luring new businesses. The myth of the all-knowing, all-seeing leader is one that he helped cultivate in a state where registered Democrats outnumber Republicans 2-1. Even a 1976 federal extortion indictment did not slow him. On the day he was indicted, <PERSON> Moore </PERSON> called a news conference to announce he would seek a third consecutive term, although the state constitution appeared to prohibit it. <PERSON> Moore </PERSON> was acquitted, but the state <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> barred his re-election bid. He left what he said was a $ 234 million budget surplus, a booming interstate highway building program and reasonably strong coal, steel and glass industries. <PERSON> Moore </PERSON> opened a law practice and ran unsuccessfully for the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> in 1978 and governor in 1980. When <PERSON> Moore </PERSON> again entered the governor's office for an unprecedented third term in 1985, he found the state in much different shape. The unemployment rate hit 18 percent the year before as the state's economy hit rock-bottom. The state faced a $ 250 million debt in the unemployment compensation fund that had been run up by Democratic Gov. <PERSON> Jay </PERSON> <PERSON> Rockefeller </PERSON>. The Legislature had enacted huge tax increases. And federal funding for highway construction and other projects dwindled. <PERSON> Moore </PERSON> asked the Legislature for a myriad of economic tools to attract business, and later claimed success. He says he has attracted more than $ 1 billion in development money during each of the past two years, and that the unemployment rate dropped below 11 percent in 1987. Critics, however, scoffed at his economic announcements, saying thousands have fled seeking jobs elsewhere. A <ORGANIZATION> West </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Virginia </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> study found the state lost 52,600 of its 1.9 million residents since 1980. Raese, a newspaper publisher and coal and limestone company owner, calls himself a conservative, pro-business candidate. He says <PERSON> Moore </PERSON> has failed to adjust spending to the state's dwindling tax income. `` Arch <PERSON> Moore </PERSON> is just a credit card governor,'' <PERSON> Raese </PERSON> said during a recent interview. `` He's marching to an old liberal tune of the late 1950s and early 1960s.'' According to a poll released today, <PERSON> Raese </PERSON> holds a substantial lead over <PERSON> Moore </PERSON> among Republicans and independents, 54 percent to 30 percent. Sixty-nine percent of the Republicans surveyed rated <PERSON> Moore </PERSON>'s performance as governor as poor or fair. The poll, conducted by The <ORGANIZATION> Associated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION>, the <ORGANIZATION> Charleston </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Daily </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mail </ORGANIZATION> and WSAZ-TV, had a margin of error of 4.4 percentage points.
