<FIRST>r w PM-FairHousing     04-25 0675</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Fair Housing,650</SECOND>
<HEAD>Administration Softening Position on Fair Housing</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID BRISCOE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration is softening its opposition to Democrat-sponsored fair housing legislation but still opposes provisions it says would deny the right to trial by jury and be unfair to elderly people, according to a Housing and Urban Development official. Another administration objection _ that a new ban of discrimination against the handicapped could force landlords to accept drug addicts or alcoholics _ was addressed in two amendments passed last week. The bill, expected to be voted on Tuesday in the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Judiciary </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION>, would toughen enforcement of the Fair Housing Act of 1968 and expand it to ban discrimination against handicapped people and families with children in rental or sale of living space. A similar bill has been introduced in the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION>. The administration had introduced its own fair housing legislation and favors an expansion of the act which now bans discrimination on the bases of sex, ethnic origin or religion. But it is wary of the version now being discussed in the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Judiciary </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION>, believing it may be unconstitutional and unfair to some landlords, tenants and home buyers, <ORGANIZATION> HUD </ORGANIZATION> general counsel <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Dorsey </PERSON> said in an interview Friday. The committee last week rejected changes that would have met some administration objections, but it tentatively approved one excluding abusers of controlled substances from being classified as handicapped. Another amendment would allow landlords or sellers to reject people `` whose tenancy would constitute a direct threat to the health or safety of other individuals.'' <PERSON> Dorsey </PERSON> said there is broad agreement that discrimination against the handicapped should be added to the law. But he had said in a letter to the <ORGANIZATION> Judiciary </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> last week that the Democratic version `` does not clearly allow those who provide housing to exclude individuals with current impairments, such as current drug abuse, that pose a threat to property or safety of others.'' Major objections to the bill have come from the <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> which opposes the setting up of an administrative law judge system to handle discrimination cases, rather than having them go to a regular jury. <PERSON> Dorsey </PERSON> said that despite strong objections to parts of the proposed bill, the administration is taking a softer stand than it has in the past. But he said it has not altered its major objections to the Democratic proposals. `` We are not saying anything about a veto at this point at all,'' he said. President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> has submitted four bills to amend fair housing laws _ in 1983, 1985, 1986 and this year. <PERSON> Dorsey </PERSON> said the current Democratic bill is `` not the one that we would prefer.'' But he indicated the administration wants fair housing laws expanded before <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> leaves office. <PERSON> Dorsey </PERSON> said the administration supports the idea that discrimination cases can be brought for single incidents rather than requiring that a pattern of discrimination be proven, which is required under the 1968 law. But he said the administrative law judge plan does not pass `` constitutional muster.'' <PERSON> Dorsey </PERSON> noted that the provision banning discrimination on the basis of `` familial status'' is designed to protect families with children. But he said in the letter, `` This provision intended to ensure fairness may well have substantial unfair effects'' on older Americans and people without children. The bill allows retirement communities or buildings where all the tenants are over 62 to ban children, but singles communities that also have younger people in them would have to accept families with children. <PERSON> Ralph </PERSON> <PERSON> G. </PERSON> <PERSON> Neas </PERSON>, executive director of the <ORGANIZATION> Leadership </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Conference </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> on </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Civil </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rights </ORGANIZATION>, which endorses the Democratic bill, said that despite administration opposition, he expects bipartisan support for the final measure. `` This administration, led by the <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION>, has compiled the worst civil rights record of any administration in half a century,'' <PERSON> Neas </PERSON> said in a telephone interview. But he said the <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> has failed in all previous efforts to limit civil rights and `` we believe once again a strong bipartisan consensus will reject this one.''
