<HEAD>US Warns Environment Endangered by Big International Loans</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CARL HARTMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Over $ 3 billion worth of loans planned by intergovernment banks to raise the standard of living in 20 countries are also likely to damage natural resources and the environment, the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> government says. The <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> is the biggest contributor to the banks, which are a major source of aid to poor countries. By law, a list of loans considered dangerous by the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agency </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Development </ORGANIZATION> will be distributed to other donors such as <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> and the leading countries of western <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>. The <ORGANIZATION> Associated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION> obtained an advance copy. AID is particularly concerned about projects that dam up big rivers in the tropics, that build roads into undeveloped parts of the world and that try to develop rural areas. One of the biggest loans on the list would provide $ 420 million from the <ORGANIZATION> World </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> for a dam on the <LOCATION> Narmada </LOCATION> <LOCATION> River </LOCATION> in central <LOCATION> India </LOCATION>, second only to the <LOCATION> Ganges </LOCATION> in sacredness to Hindus. It will displace 120,000 people, irrigate about 720,000 acres of land and generate 1,000 megawatts of electricity. The agency says the project could also increase the risk of earthquakes, of waterlogging the soil and of transmitting water-borne diseases including malaria and cholera. As many as 96,000 acres will be cleared of forest and submerged. `` We continue to have concerns about this project and will pursue them again with -LRB- World -RRB- Bank management as one of our top priorities,'' the agency says. <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> has asked for such `` early warning'' reports to be made every six months. `` We do not consider the list all inclusive,'' the agency explains. It adds that the object is to encourage better planning of new loan projects with the environment in mind. Six of the loans would go to <LOCATION> Indonesia </LOCATION>, including one from the <ORGANIZATION> World </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> for $ 120 million to help a government effort that has moved over 1.2 million families out of the overpopulated islands of Java and <LOCATION> Bali </LOCATION>. The <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> agency says it is worried about insufficient help to people being moved, displacement of those who already live near the new settlements, danger to water supply and to wildlife. Another controversial project also involves the <ORGANIZATION> World </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION>, and its continued support for a major overhaul of <LOCATION> Brazil </LOCATION>'s electric power system. It involves a loan of $ 500 million. The agency says it is concerned about the impact on <LOCATION> Brazil </LOCATION>'s Indian populations and the region's `` sensitive ecosystem. British and West German officials joined the Americans in talking to the bank's management in January. They were told that the loan had been delayed until September or October, mostly for economic reasons. The potential value of the 31 loans could be much higher than $ 3 billion. No estimates were available for five of them. Others are for major projects on which the banks have already made loans and may make more in the future.
