<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> Secretary <PERSON> Frank </PERSON> <PERSON> C. </PERSON> <PERSON> Carlucci </PERSON> says predictions that the Star Wars missile defense system wo n't work `` are like saying 10 years before we had helicopters that helicopters were doomed to failure.'' <PERSON> Carlucci </PERSON> on Sunday defended the administration program to create a hi-tech space shield against Soviet missiles, saying a panel of non-government experts believes the system is `` fundamentally sound.'' He disputed a report in Sunday's edition of <ORGANIZATION> The </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Washington </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Post </ORGANIZATION> that quoted an unpublished congressional study as saying the system would `` suffer a catastrophic failure'' if it were used against a multiple missile attack from the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>. `` That's about `` like saying 10 years before we had helicopters that helicopters were doomed to failure,'' <PERSON> Carlucci </PERSON> said in an interview on <ORGANIZATION> ABC-TV </ORGANIZATION>'s `` This Week with <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Brinkley </PERSON>.'' The study was conducted by the <ORGANIZATION> Office </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Technology </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Assessment </ORGANIZATION>, a non-partisan scientific arm of <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Carlucci </PERSON> said he had a panel of non-government technicians and engineers evaluate <ORGANIZATION> Star </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Wars </ORGANIZATION>, and it concluded that `` the program is fundamentally sound and that we can build a militarily effective SDI -LRB- strategic defense initiative -RRB- program, and that is the goal.'' <PERSON> Carlucci </PERSON> said the <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> has been studying the congressional report, which he described as long and complex, but he said there has been no official comment on it. He said SDI is `` a program that we are currently designing. It has not even entered the developmental stage, much less the deployment stage.'' Meanwhile, the <ORGANIZATION> Post </ORGANIZATION> reported in Monday's editions that a high-level Pentagon panel has recommended to <PERSON> Carlucci </PERSON> that he sharply cut the proposed initial SDI deployment from a system of space-based weaponry to a less costly and much less effective system of ground-based rockets. Quoting unidentified senior <ORGANIZATION> Pentagon </ORGANIZATION> officials, the newspaper said the panel directed by <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Everett </PERSON>, chairman of the <ORGANIZATION> Pentagon </ORGANIZATION>'s senior scientific advisory group, has told <PERSON> Carlucci </PERSON> that such a ground-based defense is worth pursuing as an initial step. Last September, then-Defense Secretary <PERSON> Caspar </PERSON> <PERSON> W. </PERSON> <PERSON> Weinberger </PERSON> approved the acceleration of six SDI programs, the first decision to push Star Wars technologies from pure research toward development. The six projects then entered what is known as a `` demonstration and validation'' phase, in which various components needed for a working system would be tested. No decision has been made on which of the six would be the first deployed. The six programs, which had been recommended by the <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Acquisition </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION>, the <ORGANIZATION> Pentagon </ORGANIZATION>'s highest internal review panel, include: _ The ground-based surveillance and tracking system, a missile that could be fired into space to obtain tracking information on missiles approaching the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> _ The space-based surveillance and tracking system, a satellite system that would be deployed in space to identify and track enemy missiles _ The boost surveillance and tracking system, another type of orbiting satellite system that would provide an alert if enemy missiles were launched _ The re-entry vehicle interception system, small missiles that could be fired from the ground to intercept and destroy enemy missiles during the middle and latter stages of their flight _ The space-based interception system, small `` kinetic kill'' rockets on an orbiting platform in space The rockets could be fired at enemy missiles shortly after launch and would destroy them through a direct collision. _ And the battle management-command, control and communications system, the `` brains'' of any Star Wars defense This would consist of a series of high-powered computers that would be programmed to select targets and direct weapons against them. In the interview Sunday, <PERSON> Carlucci </PERSON> said the Post story on the report by the <ORGANIZATION> Office </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Technology </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Assessment </ORGANIZATION> `` took selected quotes out of that report'' and drew conclusions from them. `` What you're reading from is some kind of a leaked document,'' he said. The <ORGANIZATION> Post </ORGANIZATION> said it had obtained the report's `` summary chapter.'' The newspaper said the report shows that detailed computer instructions needed to destroy thousands of warheads streaking towards the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> probably can not `` be produced in the foreseeable future.'' The overall conclusion of the report is that, despite five years and $ 12 billion worth of scientific research, `` many questions remain about the feasibility of meeting SDI goals,'' which include the ability to ward off a Soviet missile attack and eventually eliminate the threat posed by Soviet missiles.
