<HEAD>Labor Party: Voters Will Have Final Say On Peace Pact</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KARIN LAUB</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The left-of-center <ORGANIZATION> Labor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> adopted a campaign platform saying <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> will never completely withdraw from the occupied territories and that voters will be asked to approve any <LOCATION> Middle </LOCATION> <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> peace settlement. The platform for November's election appeared to be more hard-line than the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> peace initiative initially backed by <PERSON> Shimon </PERSON> <PERSON> Peres </PERSON>, the head of the <ORGANIZATION> Labor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> and the foreign minister in <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>'s coalition government. The platform adopted Sunday apparently was aimed winning over voters on the right who might consider the party too `` dovish.'' Defense Minister <PERSON> Yitzhak </PERSON> <PERSON> Rabin </PERSON>, meanwhile, told the <ORGANIZATION> Cabinet </ORGANIZATION> on Sunday that 1,700 Palestinians, more than one-third of the 4,900 arrested since protests began Dec. 8, were being held without trial for up to six months. <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> media said <PERSON> Rabin </PERSON> also criticized the <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION> during the Cabinet meeting, saying it was hampering army efforts to deport more Palestinian agitators. <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> has deported 20 Palestinians to <LOCATION> Lebanon </LOCATION> since Dec. 8 and ordered the expulsion of at least four others. Also Sunday, the army lifted a four-day ban that had prevented Arabs in the occupied lands from traveling to <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>. The army also permitted the delivery of gasoline to the occupied areas for the first time in more than a month. No major clashes were reported between Arabs and <LOCATION> Israeli </LOCATION> soldiers in the occupied lands on Sunday. The <ORGANIZATION> Labor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> platform promised voters a final say, either through elections or a referendum, on any <LOCATION> Middle </LOCATION> <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> peace settlement, said <ORGANIZATION> Labor </ORGANIZATION> spokeswoman <PERSON> Michal </PERSON> <PERSON> Cohen </PERSON>. The platform, written by <PERSON> Peres </PERSON>, also says <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> will never withdraw completely from the <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bank </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Gaza </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Strip </LOCATION> it captured in the 1967 <LOCATION> Middle </LOCATION> <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> war, Ms. <PERSON> Cohen </PERSON> told The <ORGANIZATION> Associated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION>. It calls on <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> to seek direct negotiations with a <LOCATION> Jordanian-Palestinian </LOCATION> delegation, to be preceded by an international peace conference with strictly ceremonial functions. The <ORGANIZATION> Palestine </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Liberation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Organization </ORGANIZATION> would not participate in the talks. A negotiated interim agreement on limited self-rule for the 1.5 million Palestinians in the occupied lands would remain in effect for up to five years. The document also specifies that a final settlement should allow no <LOCATION> Palestinian </LOCATION> state in the <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bank </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Gaza </LOCATION>, preserve all Jewish settlements there and maintain <LOCATION> Jerusalem </LOCATION> as the united capital of <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>. It says areas with a high percentage of <PERSON> Arab </PERSON> residents may be turned over to Palestinian-Jordanian control. These specifics in the platform go beyond the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> peace initiative, which do not dictate any such terms. The section on settlements remaining intact presumably would conflict with the views of the American government, which has consistently urged limiting Jewish settlements in the occupied territories. <PERSON> Peres </PERSON>' call for giving <LOCATION> Israeli </LOCATION> voters a final say on any peace plan has not been stated before. The <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> peace initiative also has never directly said that any international peace conference would be strictly ceremonial in function. Prime Minister <PERSON> Yitzhak </PERSON> <PERSON> Shamir </PERSON> head of the right-wing <ORGANIZATION> Likud </ORGANIZATION> bloc said on Sunday that <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> would `` never part with the <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bank </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Gaza </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Strip </LOCATION>.'' In a speech to the central committee of his <ORGANIZATION> Herut </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>, <PERSON> Shamir </PERSON> also suggested that gradual and limited <LOCATION> Palestinian </LOCATION> self-rule was as far as he was willing to go. Labor and <ORGANIZATION> Likud </ORGANIZATION> are in the fourth year of a fragile coalition. <PERSON> Peres </PERSON> and <PERSON> Shamir </PERSON> traded jobs in October 1987. Also Sunday, the <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION> asked the <ORGANIZATION> Finance </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION> for an additional $ 162 million to cover the cost of combating the Arab uprising, said spokesman <PERSON> Eitan </PERSON> <PERSON> Haber </PERSON>. He would not elaborate, and it was not immediately clear if that sum represented all the money the ministry has spent in connection with the uprising since Dec. 8, or only a part of it. Last month, the <ORGANIZATION> Economics </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION> said the uprising has cost <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> $ 312 million in lost production, lost exports and added security costs. <PERSON> Rabin </PERSON> also said 165 Palestinians have been killed in the uprising, including 147 by the army. According to <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> figures, the Palestinian death toll has reached 173. An <LOCATION> Israeli </LOCATION> soldier and Jewish settler also have died.
