<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION> share prices rose across the board today and the <ORGANIZATION> Tokyo </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stock </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> closed at a record high while the dollar stayed stable throughout the day. The Nikkei index of 225 selected issues in the <ORGANIZATION> Tokyo </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stock </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> gained 155.08 points from Saturday's closing to end the day at 27,213.45, the highest level for the market's main index. On the <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION> foreign exchange market, the dollar closed at 125 yen, up 0.35 yen from Friday's close of 124.65 yen. It had opened the day at 125.05 yen. `` Share prices, including large-capital issues such as steels, are faring well'' as investors were buoyed by the strength of the Japanese economy, said <PERSON> Masahiro </PERSON> <PERSON> Umemori </PERSON> of <ORGANIZATION> Nomura </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Securities </ORGANIZATION>. He said some investors were awaiting first-quarter figures on the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> gross national product, scheduled to be announced in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> Tuesday. A foreign exchange dealer at a Japanese commercial bank said morning trading on the dollar was very slow because investors were waiting for the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> GNP figures. Speaking on condition of ananymity, he said slow trading was expected throughout the week as <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> enters a major holiday season next week.
