<HEAD>National Front Soars, Communists Slide In Election</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-France-Election, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JEFFREY ULBRICH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The first round of the presidential election was a historic moment for two political parties. The far-right <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Front </ORGANIZATION> achieved unprecedented support, and the <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> tumbled to an all-time low. Perhaps most important for the future of <LOCATION> France </LOCATION> was the 14.5 percent won by <PERSON> Jean-Marie </PERSON> <PERSON> Le </PERSON> <PERSON> Pen </PERSON>, president of the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Front </ORGANIZATION>. The party has emerged as a significant new force in French politiics with its strident anti-immigrant, `` French first'' campaign. `` Nothing ever again will be done in <LOCATION> France </LOCATION> without the voters of the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Front </ORGANIZATION>,'' exulted <PERSON> Le </PERSON> <PERSON> Pen </PERSON>, 59, after the results became clear in Sunday's election. He said there has been a `` radical transformation of the national -LRB- political -RRB- landscape.'' Premier <PERSON> Jacques </PERSON> <PERSON> Chirac </PERSON>, who will face <ORGANIZATION> Socialist </ORGANIZATION> President <PERSON> Francois </PERSON> <PERSON> Mitterrand </PERSON> in the May 8 runoff, won only 19.9 percent of the vote and desperately needs <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Front </ORGANIZATION> support if he is to have any chance of overtaking the president, who scored 33.9 percent. <PERSON> Chirac </PERSON> has vowed he will not do a deal with <PERSON> Le </PERSON> <PERSON> Pen </PERSON> for his backing, but he may have no choice but to do so despite the nearly universal condemnation it will bring him. <PERSON> Le </PERSON> <PERSON> Pen </PERSON> says his instructions to his voters will depend on what <PERSON> Chirac </PERSON> says and does in the coming week. While <PERSON> Le </PERSON> <PERSON> Pen </PERSON>'s performance was a surprise, well above the 10 percent to 12 percent he had been accorded in pre-election opinion polls, the 6.8 percent won by <PERSON> Andre </PERSON> <PERSON> Lajoinie </PERSON>, the official <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> candidate, was predictable and confirmed the steady decline that began in 1981. The stodgy, tightly structured <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> has been losing members for a decade, essentially because it has failed to adapt its language to a changing French society which is better educated, more sophisticated and less doctrinaire. The Communists were hampered by the candidacy of <PERSON> Pierre </PERSON> <PERSON> Juquin </PERSON>, leader of a splinter reformist movement who won 2.1 percent. The poor showing of the official <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> candidate could lead to further internal party dissension of the sort that led to the rebellion by <PERSON> Juquin </PERSON> and others over the past four years. The <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>, which once was the major force on the French left accounting for more than a quarter of the vote, began to fall significantly with the 1981 presidential election when party Secretary General <PERSON> Georges </PERSON> <PERSON> Marchais </PERSON> won only 15.3 percent of the vote. That fell to 11.3 percent in the 1984 election for the <ORGANIZATION> European </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Parliament </ORGANIZATION> and 9.8 percent in the 1986 National Assembly election. Sunday's score was the lowest registered by the <ORGANIZATION> French </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> in a national election since the party was founded in 1920. The previous low was 8.4 percent in the 1932 legislative vote. In the 1974 presidential election, <PERSON> Le </PERSON> <PERSON> Pen </PERSON> won a minuscule 0.7 percent. In 1981, he was not even able to gather the 500 signatures of elected officials necessary to get on the ballot. But in 1984, the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Front </ORGANIZATION>, thoroughly vilified by all of the traditional parties, nearly equaled the Communists in the European vote with 11 percent and matched them in the 1986 legislatives with 9.8. <PERSON> Bruno </PERSON> <PERSON> Megret </PERSON>, <PERSON> Le </PERSON> <PERSON> Pen </PERSON>'s campaign manager, called 1988 `` a major turning point in the political history of our country.'' <PERSON> Francois </PERSON> <PERSON> Bachelot </PERSON>, a <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Front </ORGANIZATION> deputy in <ORGANIZATION> Parliament </ORGANIZATION>, said the score was `` not just the most remarkable event of the first round of the presidential elections, it is the essential political event of the post-war period.'' The combined vote of <PERSON> Chirac </PERSON>, head of the conservative Rally for the Republic party, and former Premier <PERSON> Raymond </PERSON> <PERSON> Barre </PERSON>, supported by the center-right <ORGANIZATION> Union </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> French </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Democracy </ORGANIZATION>, totaled less than 37 percent, a serious setback for the traditional rightist parties. Though <PERSON> Chirac </PERSON> rejects making overtures to the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Front </ORGANIZATION>, he boldly addressed <PERSON> Le </PERSON> <PERSON> Pen </PERSON>'s favorite themes in a short television appearance after the election was over. He appealed to `` all those who want security to be assured, and delinquence, criminality and terrorism to be fought with all necessary firmness, our national identifity to be preserved and clandestine immigration also to be fought ...'' Political analysts generally agreed that <PERSON> Le </PERSON> <PERSON> Pen </PERSON>'s newfound support was based as much on a widespread dissatisfaction with traditional parties as his anti-immigration and law-and-order stands. `` I am a little ashamed for <LOCATION> France </LOCATION> that a man like <PERSON> Le </PERSON> <PERSON> Pen </PERSON> ... has won 4 million votes,'' said <PERSON> Marchais </PERSON>. `` That poses a problem for me and that poses a problem for my country. He has taken votes from the working-class electorate.'' He added that <LOCATION> France </LOCATION> had `` no reason to be proud'' of a man whose policy is `` founded on racism.'' <PERSON> Lajoinie </PERSON> stressed that he `` waged my campaign not to be elected, but to affirm demands for new policies.'' He added: `` In that context is is obvious that the real influence of the <ORGANIZATION> French </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> goes very far beyond the results that we registered today.''
