<FIRST>r i PM-Chernobyl-Fears     04-25 0712</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Chernobyl-Fears,0739</SECOND>
<HEAD>Chernobyl Returning To Normal But Fear of Nuclear Power Persists</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Chernobyl-Conditions, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ANDREW KATELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> Kiev </LOCATION> residents who get a mysterious ache or pain are apt to grasp for the easy explanation _ radiation from <LOCATION> Chernobyl </LOCATION>. Such is one of the lingering scars of the world's worst nuclear accident: a fear of what long-term health problems will result from the explosion and fire two years ago at the <LOCATION> Chernobyl </LOCATION> nuclear plant, 80 miles north of <LOCATION> Kiev </LOCATION>, the Ukrainian capital. A <LOCATION> Kiev </LOCATION> resident, speaking during a <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> visit on condition of anonymity, said some people blame everything from headaches to toothaches on radiation from <LOCATION> Chernobyl </LOCATION>. This is despite the government's repeated assurances that radiation levels in the region are normal and safe. Doctors in accident-affected regions are spending most of their time `` combating radiophobia,'' the government newspaper <ORGANIZATION> Izvestia </ORGANIZATION> reported in February. A Soviet pediatrician said last August that more than 2,000 healthy children were born to mothers who lived around <LOCATION> Chernobyl </LOCATION> during the April 26, 1986 disaster, which killed 31 people and spewed a cloud of radioactivity worldwide. But an <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> doctor who treated some <LOCATION> Chernobyl </LOCATION> victims, <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Gale </PERSON>, wrote April 1 in Pravda that the accident's long-term effects can not be predicted. He guessed that problems could include birth defects, genetic deviations and an additional 6,000 cancer victims in the next 50 to 70 years. Although a Pravda report on Sunday criticized nepotism, drunkenness and sloppy repairs at the plant, other reports marking the disaster's second anniversary portray life returning to normal. They say Chernobyl's reactors are generating electricity again and people are living nearby in once dangerously radioactive areas. But the fear of nuclear power remains. Taking advantage of Soviet leader <PERSON> Mikhail </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>'s campaign for `` glasnost,'' or more openness on some issues, nuclear power opponents have been speaking out and in some cases halting construction of new nuclear plants `` Who will say that each of these atomic power stations, built or planned, does not conceal another potential Chernobyl?'' Ukrainian writer <PERSON> Oles </PERSON> <PERSON> Honchar </PERSON> asked at a conference last October. The government's answer: `` One can say now with confidence that even a recurrence of the errors which were made in Chernobyl would not lead to such a disaster,'' Nuclear Power Minister <PERSON> Nikolai </PERSON> <PERSON> Lukonin </PERSON> told the Soviet news agency <ORGANIZATION> Tass </ORGANIZATION> last week. Officials say the public's fears are unjustified. Plans call for doubling by 1990 the amount of electricity generated by nuclear plants from the 1985 level of 28 million kilowatts. Part of the increased production is from the Chernobyl plant itself. But the resumed production reportedly is not without its costs. <PERSON> V. </PERSON> <PERSON> Lukyanenko </PERSON>, the <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> head in <LOCATION> Slavutich </LOCATION>, a new town for plant workers 35 miles from <LOCATION> Chernobyl </LOCATION>, said last December that sloppy work, poor discipline and safety violations at the plant contributed to 36 accidents over a 10-month period, three of them fatal. <PERSON> Yuri </PERSON> <PERSON> K. </PERSON> <PERSON> Semyonov </PERSON>, deputy head of the Chernobyl clean-up commission, denied at a news conference last week that any major accident had occurred at the plant since the 1986 explosion. Last July, three officials in charge of the plant during the accident were convicted of gross negligence and sentenced to 10 years in a labor camp. The government blamed the accident on human error in shutting down safety systems to conduct unauthorized experiments. In January, the ruling Politburo put the accident's cost at $ 13.8 billion. Another price paid was in people's shaken faith in the government's ability to harness nuclear energy safely. The newspaper <ORGANIZATION> Komsomolskaya </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Pravda </ORGANIZATION> said nuclear plants once lent prestige to a city, `` but that was before Chernobyl.'' Popular opposition has prevented building two nuclear plants near the Ukrainian city of <LOCATION> Odessa </LOCATION> and the <LOCATION> Byelorussian </LOCATION> capital of <LOCATION> Minsk </LOCATION>. Construction of a nuclear plant in the Russian city of <LOCATION> Krasnodar </LOCATION> was halted because residents complained it was in an earthquake-prone area and too close to a nature preserve. Public complaints appear to have been at least partly behind the government's May 1987 decision to stop building two additional reactors at <LOCATION> Chernobyl </LOCATION>. Thirty Ukrainian scientists, writing Jan. 21 in the newspaper <ORGANIZATION> Literaturnaya </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ukraina </ORGANIZATION>, criticized on ecological grounds the government's plans to add reactors to three other plants. They accused the government of ignoring the `` bitter lessons of Chernobyl.''
