<DATELINE>WALTHAM, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A group of <ORGANIZATION> Brandeis </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> students has turned the addition of pork and shellfish to the student menu into a debate on the institution's Jewish origins. About 55 students demonstrated Sunday against the menu items that go against kosher dietary laws. Protesters said shellfish and pork symbolized a desire by <ORGANIZATION> Brandeis </ORGANIZATION> officials to pull away from the Jewish identity of the 40-year-old university. The protesters in turn faced a counter-demonstration by students who said the anti-pork faction was exhibiting a hostility toward non-Jews that has damaged <ORGANIZATION> Brandeis </ORGANIZATION>' reputation in the past. `` <LOCATION> Brandeis </LOCATION> and the administration is backing away from its Jewish pride,'' said protest organizer <PERSON> Stuart </PERSON> <PERSON> Kolisky </PERSON>. <PERSON> Claudia </PERSON> <PERSON> Salomon </PERSON> agreed, saying `` <ORGANIZATION> Brandeis </ORGANIZATION> needs to retain that Jewish quality. It should be a diverse community, but it should know that it has a Jewish character.'' <PERSON> Michelle </PERSON> <PERSON> Tankin </PERSON>, who also is Jewish, engaged several of the protesters in a heated argument. `` What you're trying to do is apply laws to people who are n't kosher,'' she said. Student <PERSON> Adam </PERSON> <PERSON> Whitehead </PERSON> held a small sign with the message: `` Do n't discriminate against freedom to choose.'' <ORGANIZATION> Brandeis </ORGANIZATION> is officially non-sectarian, but about 60 percent of the 2,800 undergraduate enrollment is Jewish. The university has long offered non-kosher foods, such as dishes that mix dairy products and meat. The university's board has no plans to change the pork and shellfish policy, said <PERSON> Sallie </PERSON> <PERSON> Riggs </PERSON>, spokeswoman for <LOCATION> Brandeis </LOCATION>. `` Many of the comments that were made are either one-sided or half the truth,'' <PERSO