<HEAD>Chirac Faces Old Foe In Second Run For Presidency</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-France-Election, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JEFFREY ULBRICH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Premier <PERSON> Jacques </PERSON> <PERSON> Chirac </PERSON>, an energetic leader and a tireless campaigner, will need to draw on those traits as he fights what is expected to be an uphill battle in next month's runoff presidential election. The neo-Gaullist, who has been head of the government for two years, finished second in the first round of the election on Sunday, receiving 20 percent of the vote compared to 34 percent for President <PERSON> Francois </PERSON> <PERSON> Mitterrand </PERSON>. When <PERSON> Chirac </PERSON> faces <PERSON> Mitterrand </PERSON> in the May 8 runoff, the conservative premier will be challenging the president who appointed him. One poll released Sunday predicted <PERSON> Mitterrand </PERSON> will win the runoff with 55 percent of the vote. By finishing second Sunday, <PERSON> Chirac </PERSON> improved on his first presidential run seven years ago. He lost out in the first round in 1981, finishing third behind former President <PERSON> Valery </PERSON> <PERSON> Giscard </PERSON> d'Estaing and <PERSON> Mitterrand </PERSON>. <PERSON> Chirac </PERSON> became premier in March 1986 when the conservatives ousted the Socialists from control of the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Assembly </ORGANIZATION> in legislative elections. He then formed the new Cabinet and was formally named premier by <PERSON> Mitterrand </PERSON>. <PERSON> Chirac </PERSON>'s conservative Rally for the Republic is the largest party in the center-right government coalition. The energetic premier has at various times been compared to a bulldozer, a computer and a robot. While <PERSON> Chirac </PERSON>'s immense energy and ability to make tough decisions rapidly is considered a key asset, critics consider it a liability. There are those who feel he is too impulsive to be president. <PERSON> Chirac </PERSON> is simple in his tastes and acknowledges he likes Western movies, detective novels, gin rummy and a good glass of beer. He is the champion of a liberalized free-market economy. <PERSON> Chirac </PERSON> was born Nov. 29, 1932, in <LOCATION> Paris </LOCATION>. He was educated in the capital, except during World War II period, and spent most of his holidays at the family's country home in the south-central <LOCATION> Correze </LOCATION> region. After graduating from the <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Political </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Studies </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Paris </LOCATION>, he fought as a lieutenant in the Algerian War. He completed his studies at the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> School </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION>, whose graduates are destined for the top ranks of the civil service. A frequent visitor to the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Chirac </PERSON> hitchiked around <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> as a youth, working for a time as a fountain clerk at a <PERSON> Howard </PERSON> <PERSON> Johnson </PERSON> restaurant. He was a protege of the late President <PERSON> Georges </PERSON> <PERSON> Pompidou </PERSON>, who referred to him as `` my bulldozer.'' <PERSON> Chirac </PERSON> won his first election in 1967 _ a seat in the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Assembly </ORGANIZATION> from the <LOCATION> Correze </LOCATION> district. He became a secretary of state in the <ORGANIZATION> Finance </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION>, then moved on to be minister for relations with <ORGANIZATION> Parliament </ORGANIZATION>, agriculture minister and interior minister. In 1974, at the age of 41, he became premier for the first time under Giscard d'Estaing. <PERSON> Chirac </PERSON> resigned after two years, complaining of a lack of authority and disagreement over economic policy. In 1977 he was elected mayor of <LOCATION> Paris </LOCATION>, a post he continues to hold. Instead of supporting Giscard d'Estaing in the runoff against <PERSON> Mitterrand </PERSON> in the 1981 election, <PERSON> Chirac </PERSON> told his supporters to vote their conscience, a move believed to have contributed to Giscard d'Estaing's defeat and a source of bitterness between the centrists and conservatives.
