<HEAD>'60's Protesters: Past and Present</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KILEY ARMSTRONG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The old issues were blurred with ambivalence for some of the'60's revolutionaries who grappled with their past during a reunion at <ORGANIZATION> Columbia </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION>. The adrenaline surge they remembered from the former struggle has been tempered by wistfulness, perhaps, because the dream did n't last `` It did n't just die; it was profoundly defeated,'' said <PERSON> Tom </PERSON> <PERSON> Hurwitz </PERSON>. a freelance cinematographer who thought a majority's greed overcame a minority's ideals. `` You become an anachronism _ and a very bitter one _ if you're not careful,'' said <PERSON> Bettina </PERSON> <PERSON> Berch </PERSON>, who was among the hundreds of former protesters who last weekend marked the 20th anniversary of a weeklong student uprising that shut down the Ivy League campus `` One of the things that makes me sad is that people who are younger than us picked up on the drugs and forgot most of the rest of what we were saying,'' said <PERSON> Ann </PERSON> <PERSON> Hunter </PERSON>, 40. `` Drugs were our biggest mistake.'' During panel discussions, a party and an indoor picnic, they recalled how about 1,000 people, mostly students, barricaded themselves inside five buildings the week of April 23, 1968. The protest drew international attention to the issues of racism, the Vietnam War and the status quo in general. `` This has plunged some of us into a lot of memories that one still feels ambivalent about,'' said <PERSON> Berch </PERSON>. After college, <PERSON> Berch </PERSON> clung to her anti-establishment leanings. She said she was `` kicked out of academia'' in a tenure fight after seven years of teaching at <ORGANIZATION> Barnard </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> College </ORGANIZATION> and is now writing a book. `` In their own terms, we were an aberration, a time when they lost control,'' she said. `` We became very difficult creatures.'' Some people refused to discuss their feelings, saying the reunion