<HEAD>Separatists Defiant After Four Days Of Violence In New Caledonia</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-France-Election, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NOUMEA, New Caledonia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Police were ordered to return gunfire with gunfire as they sought to end four days of violent clashes with <ORGANIZATION> Melanesian </ORGANIZATION> separatists in which 27 policemen were kidnapped and four killed. The violence disrupted elections in this <LOCATION> French </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Pacific </LOCATION> island territory in which residents voted for regional candidates and for a slate of nine candidates running in the first round of <LOCATION> France </LOCATION>'s presidential contest French Minister for Overseas Territories <PERSON> Bernard </PERSON> <PERSON> Pons </PERSON> arrived in this archipelago late Sunday and instructed gendarmes to `` respond to arms with arms.'' <PERSON> Leopold </PERSON> <PERSON> Joredie </PERSON>, a leader of the <ORGANIZATION> Kanak </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Socialist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Liberation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Front </ORGANIZATION>, today said the separatists would continue their `` mobilization.'' <PERSON> Pons </PERSON>' instructions were `` a declaration of colonial war,'' he added. The verbal confrontation followed four days of violence between police and pro-independence Melanesians that began with the storming of a police station Friday on the island of <LOCATION> Ouvea </LOCATION>, 90 miles northeast of the capital of <LOCATION> Noumea </LOCATION>. Twenty-seven gendarmes were taken hostage in the attack and three of their colleagues were hacked to death with machetes. A fourth gendarme injured in the attack died on Sunday in a <LOCATION> Sydney </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Australia </LOCATION>. Three Melanesians were injured. The kidnappers demanded the regional elections be canceled and that police reinforcements be removed from the island. They also demanded that negotiators be sent from <LOCATION> Paris </LOCATION> to discuss independence for the island. `` We do not negotiate with terrorists and criminals,'' <PERSON> Pons </PERSON> said. `` These terrorists will be treated as terrorists.'' At dawn today, 11 of the hostages were freed, <LOCATION> French </LOCATION> Defense Minster <PERSON> Andre </PERSON> <PERSON> Giraud </PERSON> announced in <LOCATION> Paris </LOCATION>. About 300 police continued combing a forest in northern <LOCATION> Ouvea </LOCATION> for the remaining 16 hostages. A <ORGANIZATION> Kanak </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Socialist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Liberation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Front </ORGANIZATION> statement issued in <LOCATION> Paris </LOCATION> said the traditional tribal chiefs requested the release `` to avert reprisals against their tribe and the population'' by the French army. `` <LOCATION> France </LOCATION>'s policy in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Caledonia </LOCATION> today is worthy of a banana republic,'' the statement said. Later today, a teen-age <PERSON> Melanesian </PERSON> was fatally shot in a clash between police and militant separatists, the privately-owned radio station TUW reported. It said the youth died after French gendarmes and Kanaks opened fire as the police were leaving their post in the eastern town of <LOCATION> Canala </LOCATION>. On Sunday, an officer was shot in the stomach while guarding a polling station in <LOCATION> Canala </LOCATION>, on the island's east coast. Barricades were set up by the separatists to disrupt polling, ballots were burned, telephone lines were cut and police used tear gas to disperse crowds of protesters on several islands. Thirty-eight of 139 polling stations were closed because of gunfire and explosions which punctuated the elections as voters cast double ballots in presidential and regional elections. Officials said turnout in the voting, boycotted by militants seeking independence, was 56.3 percent. Conservative Premier <PERSON> Jacques </PERSON> <PERSON> Chirac </PERSON>, who finished second behind incumbent President <PERSON> Francois </PERSON> <PERSON> Mitterrand </PERSON> with 19.9 percent of the vote in <LOCATION> France </LOCATION>, scored an overwhelming victory among those casting ballots in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Caledonia </LOCATION>, taking nearly 74.6 percent of the vote. <PERSON> Chirac </PERSON> will face <PERSON> Mitterrand </PERSON> in a runoff election on May 8. In voting for 48 legislative seats, the pro-French Rally for the Republic in <LOCATION> Caledonia </LOCATION>, the territorial branch of <PERSON> Chirac </PERSON>'s neo-Gaullist Rally for the <ORGANIZATION> Republic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>, won 35 and the extreme-right <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Front </ORGANIZATION> won eight Two small, right-wing parties won three seats, while dissident separatists won two. Those holding the 48 seats also will assist in four regional councils. <PERSON> Joredie </PERSON> said actions to disrupt Sunday's elections were a `` first step.'' `` The second step is the second round. We must establish a force sufficient to open discussions with the new government'' toward independence, he said. `` There are people here who are ready to fight to the end,'' he said by telephone. The new territorial assembly was created by <PERSON> Chirac </PERSON>'s government over the objections of militant native Melanesians, known as Kanaks, who make up 43 percent of the island group's population of 145,000. Thirty-six percent of the residents are Europeans, while the rest are mainly Asian or Tahitian. Many of the Melanesians are demanding independence for <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Caledonia </LOCATION>. Police in <LOCATION> Noumea </LOCATION> said six gendarmes were injured Sunday in <LOCATION> Canala </LOCATION> by `` thrown explosives.'' They were taken to a hospital in <LOCATION> Noumea </LOCATION>, where one was listed in serious condition.
