<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Martin J. O'Dea</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Martin </PERSON> <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> O'Dea </PERSON>, who climbed from a job as office messenger to president of the <ORGANIZATION> Hibernia </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION>, died Friday after a long illness. He was 76. <PERSON> O'Dea </PERSON>, who began his banking career in 1928, was named vice-president and manager of <ORGANIZATION> Hibernia </ORGANIZATION>'s downtown <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Francisco </LOCATION> branch in 1956. In 1963 he was elected director and in 1968 was named president. He was past president of the <ORGANIZATION> Serra </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Club </ORGANIZATION> of <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Francisco </LOCATION>.
