<HEAD>Dollar Steady In Calm Trading, Gold Slightly Higher</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The dollar was steady in calm European trading today. Gold prices rose slightly. The dollar is likely to trade quietly in the coming days and may move a bit higher until midweek, several dealers said. But a <LOCATION> Frankfurt </LOCATION> dealer said he expects a downturn for the dollar close to the end of the week since there are no substantial factors supporting the currency. In <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION>, where the business day ends as <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>'s begins, the dollar rose 0.35 yen to a closing 125.00 yen. Later, in <LOCATION> London </LOCATION>, it fell back to 124.55 yen. Financial markets in <LOCATION> Italy </LOCATION> were closed for a national holiday. Other dollar rates at midmorning, compared with late Friday's rates: _ 1.6745 West German marks, up from 1.6730 _ 1.3835 Swiss francs, down from 1.3840 _ 5.6865 French francs, unchanged _ 1.87775 Dutch guilders, up from 1.8770 _ 1.2320 Canadian dollars, down from 1.2324 _ 1,244.50 lire, unchanged In <LOCATION> London </LOCATION>, it cost $ 1.8815 to buy one pound, Gold opened in <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> at a bid price of $ 448.85 a troy ounce, down from late Friday's $ 449. But at midmorning today, the city's five major bullion dealers fixed a higher recommended price of $ 449.75 In <LOCATION> Zurich </LOCATION>, the bid price was $ 449.25, up from $ 449 late Friday. Earlier, in <LOCATION> Hong </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Kong </LOCATION>, gold fell to $ 451.13 from Saturday's $ 451.58 Silver was quoted in <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> today at a bid price of $ 6.41 a troy ounce, down from Friday's $ 6.46.
