<HEAD>Mitterrand To Face Chirac In Bid For Second Term</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Leads with 5 grafs to UPDATE with party endorsing of Chirac,
exit polls; Pickup 5th graf pvs, `However, Barre ...</NOTE>
<HEAD>LaserPhotos NY6,7</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HARRY DUNPHY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Conservative Premier <PERSON> Jacques </PERSON> <PERSON> Chirac </PERSON> today received the backing of the centrist <ORGANIZATION> Union </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> French </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Democracy </ORGANIZATION> in his uphill battle to defeat Socialist President <PERSON> Francois </PERSON> <PERSON> Mitterrand </PERSON> in the presidential runoff May 8. <PERSON> Chirac </PERSON>, a 55-year-old neo-Gaullist, finished a distant second in first-round voting Sunday to <PERSON> Mitterrand </PERSON>, who is seeking a second seven-year term. <PERSON> Chirac </PERSON> picked up the support of the centrist party's leader, 64-year-old <PERSON> Raymond </PERSON> <PERSON> Barre </PERSON>, Sunday night shortly after polls closed. <PERSON> Barre </PERSON>, a former premier, finished third in the voting. The Union for <ORGANIZATION> French </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Democracy </ORGANIZATION> formally endorsed <PERSON> Chirac </PERSON> today, but it was not known how many of its supporters would vote for <PERSON> Chirac </PERSON>. Exit polls showed many members of the centrist party might support <PERSON> Mitterrand </PERSON> in the runoff. `` I support him in his fight,'' said <PERSON> Barre </PERSON> of <PERSON> Chirac </PERSON>. `` And I ask all those who voted for me to vote for him in the second round.'' However, <PERSON> Barre </PERSON> did not write <PERSON> Chirac </PERSON> a blank check. `` I count on him to defend the objectives to which we are particularly attached, an open and tolerant society that rejects xenophobia, racism and extremism,'' <PERSON> Barre </PERSON> said. His comments were aimed at the candidate of the extreme right, <PERSON> Jean-Marie </PERSON> <PERSON> Le </PERSON> <PERSON> Pen </PERSON>, who finished just behind <PERSON> Barre </PERSON> and whose endorsement could be key to a Chirac victory. <PERSON> Le </PERSON> <PERSON> Pen </PERSON>, president of the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Front </ORGANIZATION>, won 14.5 percent of the vote _ well above predictions. His campaign speeches included calls for deporting immigrants and quarantining victims of acquired immune deficiency syndrome. A cartoon in the leftist daily Liberation today showed <PERSON> Le </PERSON> <PERSON> Pen </PERSON>, dressed as a stormtrooper, standing inside <PERSON> Chirac </PERSON>'s open mouth and saying, `` From now on, nothing in this country gets done without me.'' In an editorial, <ORGANIZATION> Liberation </ORGANIZATION> editor <PERSON> Serge </PERSON> <PERSON> July </PERSON> wrote: `` Two years under <PERSON> Mitterrand </PERSON> have multiplied discontent with <PERSON> Chirac </PERSON>. <PERSON> Le </PERSON> <PERSON> Pen </PERSON> has systematically welcomed this, once again making <LOCATION> France </LOCATION> an ` exceptional' democracy, the only one in the Western world where the economic and political crisis has engendered an extremist electorate.'' <PERSON> Le </PERSON> <PERSON> Pen </PERSON>, 59, said he will tell his supporters at a rally on Sunday how to vote on May 8. An editorial in the conservative daily <ORGANIZATION> Le </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Figaro </ORGANIZATION> today said the task of attracting <PERSON> Le </PERSON> <PERSON> Pen </PERSON> followers without alienating <PERSON> Barre </PERSON>'s constituents was difficult but not impossible `` The right has no reason to call this a lost cause as long as <PERSON> Chirac </PERSON> can rally around him all the men and women in this country who do n't want <PERSON> Mitterrand </PERSON>'s re-election,'' <PERSON> Le </PERSON> <PERSON> Figaro </PERSON> said. With 98 percent of the vote counted on Sunday, the 71-year-old <PERSON> Mitterrand </PERSON> had 33.9 percent, ahead of <PERSON> Chirac </PERSON>, who with 19.9 percent did not do as well as expected. <PERSON> Barre </PERSON> was third with 16.6 percent. A telephone poll conducted by state-run Antenne 2 television after the results were announced showed that <PERSON> Mitterrand </PERSON> would defeat <PERSON> Chirac </PERSON> in the runoff, winning 55 percent of the vote. In a brief statement, <PERSON> Mitterrand </PERSON> said on Sunday: `` Now the choice is simple. To all of you who serve <LOCATION> France </LOCATION>, we have great tasks before us. Let us rally together, neglecting no effort to win May 8.'' The <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>, once a significant political force, slumped to its lowest score in party history, with <PERSON> Andre </PERSON> <PERSON> Lajoinie </PERSON> getting 6.8 percent. Rounding out the nine-candidate field were <PERSON> Antoine </PERSON> <PERSON> Waechter </PERSON>, an ecologist with 3.8 percent; <PERSON> Pierre </PERSON> <PERSON> Juquin </PERSON>, leader of a splinter <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> reformist group, 2.1 percent; <ORGANIZATION> Arlette </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Laguiller </ORGANIZATION>, head of the <ORGANIZATION> Trotskyist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Worker </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Strggle </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Movement </ORGANIZATION> 2 percent; and <PERSON> Pierre </PERSON> <PERSON> Boussel </PERSON> leader of another Trotskyist group 0.4 percent. Turnout by <LOCATION> France </LOCATION>'s 38 milion voters was more than 82 percent. The choice facing French voters May 8 is more over what kind of president they want rather than the positions of the two candidates. This is <PERSON> Mitterrand </PERSON>'s fourth presidential race. He was defeated by Gen. <PERSON> Charles </PERSON> <PERSON> de </PERSON> <PERSON> Gaulle </PERSON> in 1965 and by <PERSON> Valery </PERSON> <PERSON> Giscard </PERSON> d'Estaing in 1974 before winning in 1981. <PERSON> Chirac </PERSON>, a smiling, energetic campaigner, heads the neo-Gaullist Rally for the Republic Party. He has run the government since the right won the legislative elections in 1986 in what the French call `` cohabitation'' with a leftist president. The president is the chief of state. The premier, elected by the legislature, is the head of government. Sunday's vote marked the first time a president and premier have opposed one another in a presidential election. Discussion in the next few days is likely to focus on a date and format for a televised Mitterrand-Chirac debate. <PERSON> Mitterrand </PERSON> has suggested Thursday. <PERSON> Chirac </PERSON> wants a date in the final week of the campaign. A debate is vastly more important to <PERSON> Chirac </PERSON>, who hopes it will help him make up ground against the president. On the issues, both candidates support an open economy and want to improve <LOCATION> France </LOCATION>'s education system, spending more on technical training and research. On foreign and defense policies, both speak of the need for <LOCATION> France </LOCATION> to become more involved in <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>'s defenses.
