<HEAD>12,000 Union Members Vote on Caterpillar No-Strike Proposal</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PEORIA, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Ratification of a limited no-strike clause will mean more jobs for <ORGANIZATION> Caterpillar </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>'s parts subsidiary, union and company officials say. Voting over several days by some 12,000 members of <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Auto </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Workers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Caterpillar </ORGANIZATION> locals nationwide was capped Sunday with ballots in <LOCATION> Peoria </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Decatur </LOCATION>, where union officials reported large majorities favoring the no-strike agreement. A final official vote tally still must be transmitted from the union to the company, <PERSON> Gil </PERSON> <PERSON> Nolde </PERSON>, a company spokesman, said late Sunday. The agreement extends indefinitely the contract with <ORGANIZATION> Caterpillar </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Logistic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Services </ORGANIZATION>, a parts-distribution subsidiary that covers about 1,000 employees. Most of the workers are based in <LOCATION> Morton </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ill. </LOCATION>, with some in <LOCATION> Delavan </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ill. </LOCATION>, and <LOCATION> Memphis </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Tenn. </LOCATION>. Caterpillar officials, based in <LOCATION> Peoria </LOCATION>, said they needed the no-strike clause to attract major contracts for CLS The subsidiary was formed in January 1987 to provide warehousing and distribution services for parts and equipment for companies around the world. CLS President <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Baldwin </PERSON> said recently the company is ready to bid on or sign three such contracts in 1988, including one with the <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION>. He said the contracts could translate into thousands of new jobs. Union officials had feared that without approval of the limited no-strike clause, the company might move the jobs to non-union facilities. Under the agreement, CLS parts-distribution workers will remain on the job even if the <ORGANIZATION> UAW </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Caterpillar </ORGANIZATION> do n't reach a master contract agreement by Sept. 30, and even if manufacturing workers decide to strike. The parts-distribution workers would not be allowed to strike until after a new central bargaining agreement is reached. They then would have 60 days to negotiate a new local contract and could strike at the end of that period. `` We are pleased with the vote,'' <PERSON> Jerry </PERSON> <PERSON> Flaherty </PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION> Caterpillar </ORGANIZATION> vice president of employee and labor relations, said in a statement late Sunday. `` We can now talk to potential customers about continuing, reliable CAT Logistics service from facilities with <ORGANIZATION> UAW </ORGANIZATION> employees. It means more jobs, and that's good news.'' In <LOCATION> Peoria </LOCATION>, the agreement won 62 percent of the votes cast from <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Auto </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Workers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Local </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> 974 </ORGANIZATION>, with 837 in favor of it and 519 against, said <PERSON> Tony </PERSON> <PERSON> Green </PERSON>, the local's president. The vote covered plants in <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Peoria </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Mapleton </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Mossville </LOCATION>. In <LOCATION> Decatur </LOCATION>, Local 751 members who participated gave the agreement an 82 percent vote of approval, said Local President <PERSON> Larry </PERSON> <PERSON> Solomon </PERSON>. He refused to say how many of his 2,000 members voted, or to give the actual vote totals. `` I think the general sentiment is that if it could mean jobs, we've got to try it,'' <PERSON> Solomon </PERSON> said. Union members in <LOCATION> Memphis </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Tenn. </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Denver </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Colo. </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Dallas </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Pa. </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Davenport </PERSON>, <LOCATION> Iowa </LOCATION>, and <LOCATION> Aurora </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ill. </LOCATION>, already had ratified the agreement.
