<HEAD>Gas Price Average Jumps More Than 2 Cents in Two Weeks</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The average price of gasoline nationwide jumped 2.67 cents to nearly a dollar a gallon in the past two weeks in what is seen as a precursor to even higher prices during the summertime peak driving season. `` We have a dramatic leap in the retail price of gasoline across the nation,'' <PERSON> Trilby </PERSON> <PERSON> Lundberg </PERSON> said Sunday after compiling results of the <ORGANIZATION> Lundberg </ORGANIZATION> Survey of prices at 12,000 gas stations in every state. The latest two-week survey ended April 22. The average price of 98.84 cents includes all grades and sales categories as well as taxes. `` The greatest increases were found in the <LOCATION> Midwest </LOCATION>; the smallest in the <LOCATION> Rocky </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Mountains </LOCATION> region,'' Ms. <PERSON> Lundberg </PERSON> said. Prices per gallon at self-service pumps were: regular unleaded, 89.90 cents; premium unleaded, 104.45 cents; regular leaded, 86.86 cents. At full-serve pumps, prices were: regular unleaded, 118.74 cents; premium unleaded 128.81 cents; regular leaded, 114.14 cents. `` There's a mixed bag of indicators for future trends because, although wholesale prices to all types of retailers are still on the rise, our spot price surveys show great variation with drops and hikes in the main trading centers,'' Ms. <PERSON> Lundberg </PERSON> said. Crude oil prices, meanwhile, are holding and `` a good guesstimate might be that if they continue to hold, gasoline prices to motorists could continue to rise moderately in coming months in response to summer demand,'' she said. Ms. <PERSON> Lundberg </PERSON> noted that most price change usually occurs at self-service pumps but the latest survey showed activity at full-serve pumps. `` This is a real push upward because the wholesale buying price increases that the retailers paid in the past couple of weeks were burdens they had to pass on, and they did,'' she said.
