<SECOND>PM-Poland-Strike,0544</SECOND>
<HEAD>Transit Workers Strike In Western Polish City</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN DANISZEWSKI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Bus and tram drivers in the western city of <LOCATION> Bydgoszcz </LOCATION> went on strike today, forcing thousands of people to walk to work and testing <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION>'s determination to limit wage increases in the face of steep price rises. Workers seeking higher pay listed 10 demands in their unauthorized job action. Negotiations were taking place with a deputy mayor and a deputy provicial governor at a streetcar depot in the city, said a spokeswoman at the official transport workers union office. The drivers want wages to match those earned in other cities, as well as some management changes, she said. Officials said it appeared there would be no early end to the walkout. Solidarity Chairman <PERSON> Lech </PERSON> <PERSON> Walesa </PERSON> said he was planning to travel from his home in <LOCATION> Gdansk </LOCATION> to <LOCATION> Bydgoszcz </LOCATION> to offer support. Prices in <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION> have gone up 42 percent since the beginning of the year, the result of planned increases mandated by a government economic reform program. The increases prompted nationwide pressure for pay raises among workers. Government figures said wages rose on average 45 percent by April 1. Polish leader Gen. <PERSON> Wojciech </PERSON> <PERSON> Jaruzelski </PERSON>, alarmed by the trend, last month warned enterprise managers they could be fired if they were too generous with their payrolls, thereby fueling inflation. Government spokesman <PERSON> Jerzy </PERSON> <PERSON> Urban </PERSON> said the unauthorized walkout at the <ORGANIZATION> Provincial </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Transportation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Enterprise </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Bydgoszcz </LOCATION> began today at 6 a.m. `` The first shift refused to work,'' Urban said in a telephone interview. `` I ca n't say it is the biggest strike -LRB- in recent years -RRB-. I ca n't even call it a strike. They did n't declare a strike and it has no organized form.'' Second-shift workers also refused to begin work at 2 p.m., said a spokeswoman at <LOCATION> Bydgoszcz </LOCATION> transit headquarters. A parked bus blocked the gates of the main depot but there were few other outward signs of discord, said a Solidarity activist in the city, <PERSON> Ryszard </PERSON> <PERSON> Helak </PERSON>. Urban said the demands included a $ 15 a month salary raise, plus a eight cent increase in the 38-cent-an-hour wage. The union spokeswoman, who would not give her name, said the transit system employs about 2,800 workers. Urban said 229 buses and 60 trams were idled in the city of 375,000 people, located 150 miles northwest of <LOCATION> Warsaw </LOCATION>. `` It looks like it will take a long time to resolve it,'' said <PERSON> Halina </PERSON> <PERSON> Jarminowska </PERSON>, a spokeswoman for the <LOCATION> Bydgoszcz </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Voivoidship </LOCATION>, the provincial government. `` People had to walk to work this morning,'' she said. `` Factories which have buses drove people from the night shift home and then took those coming for the morning shift. Those working in offices, youths going to school, had to walk.'' <PERSON> Helak </PERSON> said Solidarity did not organize the strike. <PERSON> Walesa </PERSON> on Sunday said large-scale strikes might be needed to spur reform in <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION>. The spokeswoman at the official union office in <LOCATION> Bydgoszcz </LOCATION>, one of the unions put together by the government after Solidarity was banned in the 1981 martial law crackdown, said the strike took her organization `` by surprise.'' `` It was an initiative of the drivers,'' she said.
