 <ORGANIZATION> Chinese </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> chief <PERSON> Zhao </PERSON> <PERSON> Ziyang </PERSON> said today that <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> will deal forcefully with separatist movements, such as the one in <LOCATION> Tibet </LOCATION>, and that such movements are doomed to failure. `` Nowadays, a very small number of people are attempting to split our motherland,'' <PERSON> Zhao </PERSON> said at a conference of 4,000 people representing <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>'s 56 nationalities. `` It is not difficult to see that they are not representing the interests of our people, and they are only the agents of some anti-Chinese foreign forces. Their vain attempt of splitting <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> can not possibly be realized.'' <PERSON> Zhao </PERSON> did not mention <LOCATION> Tibet </LOCATION> by name but it was clear that he was referring to the faraway province. The Tibetan capital of <LOCATION> Lhasa </LOCATION> erupted in pro-independence riots last fall and again in March. The bloody protests were led by <ORGANIZATION> Buddhist </ORGANIZATION> monks loyal to the exiled spiritual leader the <PERSON> Dalai </PERSON> <PERSON> Lama </PERSON>. Tibetan authorities have allowed almost no foreign journalists into <LOCATION> Tibet </LOCATION> and released few details of action taken against rioters. Sources in <LOCATION> Lhasa </LOCATION> have reported hundreds of arrests following the March disturbance. Chinese officials say five people died in the March riots. Unconfirmed reports have put the death toll as high as 24. <PERSON> Zhao </PERSON> said <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> must carry out a two-pronged policy to promote the interests of minority nationalities and `` forcefully oppose and deal with any separatist efforts.'' His comments were carried by the official <ORGANIZATION> Xinhua </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> News </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agency </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Zhao </PERSON> told the gathering that discrimination against minority ethnic groups is a problem everywhere in the world except <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>. He claimed <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> has banned discrimination against minorities, protects them by law and grants them privileges not available to <PERSON> Han </PERSON> <PERSON> Chinese </PERSON>, who comprise 92 percent of <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>'s 1 billion people. Chinese minorities, which include 55 ethnic groups, were often the victims of persecution during the first three decades of Communist rule in <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>, when the government tried to eliminate religious worship and local languages and customs. In the past decade <LOCATION> Beijing </LOCATION> has tried to redress some of the wrongs of the past and now encourages minorities, many who live in sparsely populated, strategic areas of western <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>, to retain their traditions. <PERSON> Zhao </PERSON> is the author of a plan to give priority to economic development of coastal <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>. There has been concern that <PERSON> Zhao </PERSON>'s plan would further widen the income gap between the coast, which is mostly Han Chinese, and the interior where many minorities live in pockets of poverty. <PERSON> Zhao </PERSON> urged minorities to use foreign capital, science and technology to develop their economies and compete in national and international markets.
