<HEAD>Justices Will Consider Prisoners' Rights Case</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES H. RUBIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> today agreed to consider giving federal prison wardens more power to decide what publications inmates may read. The court said it will review a ruling that limits the authority of officials to censor reading material behind prison bars. One of the prisoners in the case is <PERSON> Jack </PERSON> <PERSON> Henry </PERSON> <PERSON> Abbott </PERSON>, a convicted murderer and bank robber who achieved notoriety after he was befriended by <PERSON> Norman </PERSON> <PERSON> Mailer </PERSON> and other prominent writers and editors. Six weeks after <PERSON> Abbott </PERSON> was freed in a work-release program in 1981, he stabbed to death an aspiring actor outside of a <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION> restaurant where the victim was working as a waiter. <PERSON> Abbott </PERSON>'s book on prison life, `` In the Belly of the <LOCATION> Beast </LOCATION>,'' was critically acclaimed <PERSON> Abbott </PERSON> is among prisoners who challenged federal regulations restricting publications that may be sent to inmates. The <LOCATION> U.S </LOCATION>. <ORGANIZATION> Circuit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Appeals </ORGANIZATION> here ruled last July that the rules go too far in giving wardens control over what publications inmates may subscribe to or receive. The appeals court ordered further trial court hearings, where officials will have to prove that 46 publications should be banned because they threaten security, order or rehabilitation. The free-expression rights of inmates require that officials shoulder the burden of proof when they seek to ban publications, the appeals court said. Among the publications officials tried to ban were, for example, an issue of The Call, a left-wing newspaper that included an article charging `` inhumane treatment ... by racist guards'' in federal prisons. Officials at a federal penitentiary in <LOCATION> Atlanta </LOCATION> said the article `` is considered not to be in the best interest of discipline, good order and security.'' But the appeals court said that is an insufficient reason to ban the publication. The officials failed to prove `` the material encouraged conduct which would constitute, or otherwise was likely to produce, a breach of security or order or an impairment of rehabilitation.'' The same limits on official power should apply to sexually explicit material, the appeals court said. Also, the appeals court said censoring parts of a publication is less restrictive than banning the newspaper or magazine entirely. `` Rejecting an entire publication where a part is objectionable is inconsistent with the First Amendment,'' the appeals court said. The Constitution's First Amendment ensures freedom of speech. The <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration urged the <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> to restore fully the prison regulations. `` While a warden may have a legitimate fear that a particular publication will cause problems, he will rarely be able to prove a likelihood of violence or disorder as a result of the admission of a publication,'' <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> lawyers said. They cited uprisings last year by inmates from <LOCATION> Cuba </LOCATION> in two <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> prisons as evidence `` that information from the outside can, in some circumstances, have grave consequences within a prison.'' The government also argued that the number of publications excluded is small. Between Sept. 1, 1986 and Aug. 31, 1987 some 1,728 publications were withheld out of 1.8 million sent to federal inmates, the government's appeal said. The groups challenging the prison regulations are the Prisoners' Union, <ORGANIZATION> Weekly </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Guardian </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Associates </ORGANIZATION> and the <ORGANIZATION> Revolutionary </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Socialist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> League </ORGANIZATION> The case is <PERSON> Meese </PERSON> vs. <PERSON> Abbott </PERSON>, 87-1344.
