<HEAD>Court Lets Stand Ruling on Property Owners' Rights in Wyoming Case</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> today let stand a ruling that property owners' rights are not violated when they are required to remove structures that could interfere with low-flying planes. The court, citing the lack of a `` substantial federal question,'' rejected an appeal by a <LOCATION> Cheyenne </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Wyo. </LOCATION>, man fined $ 200 a day for refusing to trim a 48-foot cottowood tree on his property. <PERSON> Terry </PERSON> <PERSON> Rogers </PERSON>, the tree owner, said a <LOCATION> Cheyenne </LOCATION> ordinance imposing a height limit on structures near the local airport is unconstitutional because it takes property without just compensation. His tree, at 48 feet, would have to be cut to 25 or 30 feet to comply with the ordinance. <PERSON> Rogers </PERSON> said that would kill the tree, costing him $ 2,064. After he lost an earlier challenge to the ordinance's constitutionality, <PERSON> Rogers </PERSON> was found guilty of violating city law and fined $ 200 a day beginning Nov. 20, 1986 Court documents did not indicate the total fine assessed against <ORGANIZATION> Rogers </ORGANIZATION>. The <ORGANIZATION> Wyoming </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> last December upheld the fine, rejecting claims that the air space above <ORGANIZATION> Rogers </ORGANIZATION>' property belonged to him. The state court also rejected <PERSON> Rogers </PERSON>' argument that because the tree was in place prior to enactment of the ordinance he was entitled to keep it. The state court said the local law `` allows for the continuance of a non-conforming use. It does not allow the expansion of a pre-existing non-conforming use.'' `` In other words,'' the state court said, `` a violation occurred if the tree was allowed to grow higher than it stood in October 1974 when the ordinance was adopted.'' The tree has grown some 18 feet since the fall of 1974, the state court said. The justices in 1986 rejected a related appeal by <PERSON> Rogers </PERSON>. The case is <ORGANIZATION> Rogers </ORGANIZATION> vs. <LOCATION> Cheyenne </LOCATION>, 87-1462.
