<HEAD>Court Turns Away Missouri Sex Discrimination Case</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES H. RUBIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> today turned away a case in which <LOCATION> Missouri </LOCATION> officials were found guilty of sex discrimination by not hiring enough women as highway maintenance workers. The court, without comment, rejected an appeal by state officials who said lower courts improperly weighed the evidence. The justices also refused to hear an appeal by women who said remedies ordered by the lower courts were inadequate. The 8th U.S. <ORGANIZATION> Circuit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Appeals </ORGANIZATION> last September said there was adequate evidence for a federal jury to find that the <LOCATION> Missouri </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Highway </LOCATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Transportation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> discriminated against women in the state's eighth district. The verdict was based partly on anecdotal evidence and partly on statistics that showed the number of women maintenance workers in the district was a small fraction of the women in the regional work force. The appeals court said that from Jan. 1, 1975, through May 31, 1980, the state hired eight women as maintenance workers and 89 men for those jobs. During that period women comprised up to 48 percent of the work force, the appeals court noted. <LOCATION> Missouri </LOCATION> officials interpreted the statistics differently. They said only 312 women applied for maintenance work compared to 3,566 men during that period. The state said it hired 2.6 percent of the female applicants and 2.5 percent of the men who applied. But the 8th Circuit court said the equal hiring rate did not prove the state was innocent of bias. A judge and jury `` were free to weigh the inference of non-discrimination arising from the hiring rate against the inference of discrimination arising from the anecdotal and statistical evidence,'' the appeals court said. It added the evidence was sufficient to support a verdict that the state `` engaged in a pattern or practice of discrimination against women.'' The appeals court upheld a ruling that some 150 women may share in back pay to be awarded by the state. The group is made up of women who were qualified to be hired as maintenance workers if the state had not discriminated on the basis of sex. But the appeals court overturned a portion of a federal judge's ruling that <LOCATION> Missouri </LOCATION> hire from 37 percent to 48 percent women for future maintenance worker openings The 8th Circuit court ordered the hiring goal `` replaced by a generalized injunction prohibitng further discrimination'' against women. The appeals court also refused to order the state to hire four women who were among the first to charge the state with discrimination, and it declined to extend its ruling beyond the eighth district to make it statewide. The <ORGANIZATION> Mountain </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> States </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Legal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Foundation </ORGANIZATION>, a conservative group, and officials from <LOCATION> Wisconsin </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Wyoming </LOCATION> said the finding of discrimination against <LOCATION> Missouri </LOCATION> could have far-reaching consequences. They said the charges were based on questionable statistical evidence. The eligible work force consisted of all working women between ages 18 and 70 who had driver's licenses and an eighth grade education, they noted. `` This labor pool is too broad because it failed to consider only those individuals willing and able to do the work in question,'' they said. The cases are <ORGANIZATION> Missouri </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Highway </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> vs. <PERSON> Catlett </PERSON>, 87-1415, and <PERSON> Catlett </PERSON> vs. <ORGANIZATION> Missouri </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Highway </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION>, 87-1416.
