<HEAD>Danish Train Derails, Killing 7, Injuring 67</HEAD>
<DATELINE>COPENHAGEN, Denmark (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A passenger train today raced through a station where it was supposed to stop and then derailed. Danish television said seven people were killed and 67 injured. `` There are several overturned cars, partly on top of each other,'' Assistant Police Commissioner <PERSON> Palle </PERSON> <PERSON> Hasselgren </PERSON> told Danish radio. The radio reported the train, traveling from <LOCATION> Fredricia </LOCATION> to <LOCATION> Copenhagen </LOCATION>, derailed as it was to return to the main track from a side rail which was used because of repair work. The train was not scheduled to stop for passengers at the small rural station at <LOCATION> Soroe </LOCATION>, but was supposed to halt because of the track change. Instead it went through the station at high speed, the radio said. The engine and the two first cars flew off the track, causing the following five cars to overturn, the report said. The derailment occurred about 50 miles southwest of <LOCATION> Copenhagen </LOCATION>. The express train, with a capacity of 300 people, was nearly full. However, a group of children on their way to school got off at the station before <PERSON> Soroe </PERSON>, the radio said. Many passengers were businessmen from <LOCATION> Funen </LOCATION> island on their way to the Danish capital. Police helicopters and air force planes were called in to help evacuate casualties. The dead were not immediately identified. Their nationalities were not known.
