<HEAD>Pace Slow As Town Evacuated as Part of Drill</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JILL WILSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>INSTITUTE, W.Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Only a handful of people left their homes and jobs today when local officials conducted their first evacuation drill in this `` Chemical Valley'' community, the site of the nation's only methyl isocyanate plant. Sirens sounded to signal the evacuation at about 9:25 a.m. and brought little immediate response. About one hour later, only some 30 people had arrived at an emergency shelter set up in nearby <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Charleston </LOCATION>. Volunteers participating in the drill, which was designed to simulate a leak in a railroad tanker at the plant, said they believed the operation was going well. But at least one resident said `` mayhem'' would result if a real emergency occurred. Institute is the site of a <ORGANIZATION> Rhone-Poulenc </ORGANIZATION> chemical plant that formerly was owned by <ORGANIZATION> Union </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Carbide </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp </ORGANIZATION>. The plant produces methyl isocyanate, the chemical that leaked from a Union Carbide plant in <LOCATION> Bhopal </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> India </LOCATION>, in 1984, killing more than 2,000 people. Less than a year later, a leak of another chemical at the Institute plant sent 135 people to the hospital, prompting the call by some community leaders for an organized evacuation plan in case of a major leak. <PERSON> Barbara </PERSON> <PERSON> Oden </PERSON>, assistant vice president of academic affairs at <ORGANIZATION> West </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Virginia </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> College </ORGANIZATION>, next to the plant, was in Institute during the 1985 leak and said today's drill was `` useful'' even if people did n't participate. `` We really did n't know what to do -LRB- then -RRB-. At least now we have some idea,'' she said. `` People normally do n't take things seriously. They do n't think it can really happen.'' Local officials responded to the problem of evacuating the town of 1,500 by building a one-lane emergency road out of town to help residents flee, but the gate to that road is kept locked except when needed. Today was the first time it was used. `` I can envision cars all over the track. It's just a little trail. It would be mayhem. It will be a mess,'' said <PERSON> Barbara </PERSON> <PERSON> Clark </PERSON>, a health and physical education instructor at the state college. Today's evacuation was conducted under special circumstances. <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Virginia </LOCATION> State called off classes this morning, so there were no students to evacuate from academic buildings. The town also was evacuated in stages so the roads leading out of town would n't be too crowded. `` When this was prepared, people did n't take it seriously,'' said <PERSON> Lois </PERSON> <PERSON> Thurston </PERSON>, a custodian at <ORGANIZATION> West </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Virginia </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> College </ORGANIZATION>. `` I'm sure if the students were here, they would n't know what was going on.''
