<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Sen. <PERSON> Frank </PERSON> <PERSON> Lautenberg </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-N.J. </LOCATION>, announced his bid for a second term today, while veteran Democratic Rep. <PERSON> Butler </PERSON> <PERSON> Derrick </PERSON> of <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Carolina </LOCATION> said he'll seek an eighth term in November. In prepared remarks to announce his candidacy, <PERSON> Lautenberg </PERSON> did not mention Republican senatorial candidate <PERSON> Pete </PERSON> <PERSON> Dawkins </PERSON>, a <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Point </LOCATION> hero who recently moved to <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Jersey </LOCATION> and announced Feb. 29 he would seek <PERSON> Lautenberg </PERSON>'s seat. <PERSON> Lautenberg </PERSON> told reporters at <ORGANIZATION> Liberty </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Park </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Jersey </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.J. </LOCATION>, that he expects to debate <PERSON> Dawkins </PERSON> during the campaign. But he said he would not attack the <ORGANIZATION> GOP </ORGANIZATION> candidate, and that it would be up to voters to decide if <PERSON> Dawkins </PERSON> should answer for moving into the state to run to office. <PERSON> Lautenberg </PERSON> also said he must work on getting <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Jersey </LOCATION> voters to better recognize his name. `` I think it's fair to say people know my work better than they know me. I guess I have n't been as good a communicator as I've been a worker,'' he said. <PERSON> Lautenberg </PERSON>, 63, has run for office just once. The <LOCATION> Montclair </LOCATION> multimillionaire, who made his fortune with the <ORGANIZATION> Automatic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Data </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Processing </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, upset well-known Rep. <PERSON> Millicent </PERSON> <PERSON> Fenwick </PERSON> to gain the si