<HEAD>British Airways To Begin First of Smoking Ban Trials Tuesday</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MAGGIE JACKSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> British </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airways </ORGANIZATION> will ban smoking on one of its busiest domestic routes for a month beginning Tuesday in the first of a series of smoke-free flights. The airline will forbid an estimated 2,500 passengers from lighting up on its 12 daily one-hour shuttle flights between <LOCATION> London </LOCATION>'s <LOCATION> Heathrow </LOCATION> airport and <LOCATION> Glasgow </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Scotland </LOCATION>. On June 6, some <ORGANIZATION> British </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airways </ORGANIZATION> flights to the continent will become smoke-free for a month, and in November some <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION> and New York-bound flights join the experiment. Several small British carriers have banned smoking on domestic and international flights, but <ORGANIZATION> British </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airways </ORGANIZATION> is the largest to try it. The company's only domestic competitor, British <ORGANIZATION> Midland </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airways </ORGANIZATION>, said it had no plans to ban smoking. Unlike the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, where the government forced airlines to ban smoking on all domestic flights shorter than two hours, <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION> has no national laws concerning smoking. About 34 percent of British adults smoke cigarettes. British Airways officials said they took action because research showed that if smoking were banned, the number of customers who would fly more often was four times the number who would switch airlines. `` In recent years demand for non-smoking areas on our aircraft have grown and grown. Today on most routes smokers are very much in the minority,'' said <PERSON> Jim </PERSON> <PERSON> Harris </PERSON>, marketing director for the airline. `` We have steadily increased non-smoking areas to reflect this trend. ... Now we want a full trial of customer reaction to see if we can extend the idea still further.'' Airline spokesman <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Blunt </PERSON> said the carrier will decide whether to continue the bans after studying surveys and other passenger response. <PERSON> Stephen </PERSON> <PERSON> Eyres </PERSON>, director of a pro-smoking group, criticized the idea as discriminatory, dangerous and unnecessary. `` Our view is that so long as non-smokers' wishes are respected with definite no-smoking areas, there also ought to be areas where smokers can light up and not be treated like social lepers,'' he said. He said the bans would lead to safety risks from people smoking in toilets, and said that it was unnecessary because cabin air is changed every three minutes. Opposition lawmaker <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Foulkes </PERSON> said Monday he would introduce a bill in <ORGANIZATION> Parliament </ORGANIZATION> Tuesday to ban smoking in the workplace, saying `` some people regard it as torture to have to work in a smoke-filled workplace.'' But opposition legislation rarely passes the legislative body, and a government spokesman said that government planned no national laws banning smoking on airlines or in public places. `` It's like drinking, it's a question of choice. It's a part of society's freedoms,'' said <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> Hayward </PERSON> of the <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Health </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Social </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Services </ORGANIZATION>. `` At this moment this government has no intention to inhibit this generally accepted freedom.''
