<FIRST>r p BC-UTAHAt-A-Glance     04-25 0237</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-UTAH At-A-Glance,</SECOND>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Here, at a glance, are the methods for picking delegates from <LOCATION> Utah </LOCATION> to attend the 1988 Democratic and Republican national conventions this summer.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>DEMOCRATS</HEAD>
<TEXT>
 Method: Caucus Date: Monday, April 25 Presidential filing deadline: None. Pledged delegates: 23 Super delegates: 4 TOTAL: 27 Delegates allocated: Monday, April 25 Selection of delegates: Saturday, June 18 <ORGANIZATION> Utah </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Democrats </ORGANIZATION> use a three-step system of caucuses and conventions to pick pledged national convention delegates. All of the state's 23 pledged national convention delegates will be allocated among presidential candidates in proportion to presidential preferences expressed by write-in ballot at Democratic mass meetings to be held around the state on April 25.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>REPUBLICANS</HEAD>
<TEXT>
 Method: Caucus Date: Monday, April 25 Presidential filing deadline: None. Delegates: 26 Delegates allocated: Saturday, June 11 Selection of delegates: Saturday, June 11 <ORGANIZATION> Utah </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Republicans </ORGANIZATION> choose their national convention delegates through a process of meetings and conventions, beginning with neighborhood `` mass meetings'' on April 25. These mass meetings will choose delegates to county conventions, and in 17 counties will pick delegates to the state convention. In the remaining 12 counties in <LOCATION> Utah </LOCATION>, delegates to the state convention will be chosen by the county conventions. Delegates in this process are not bound from one level to the next and candidates for national convention delegate need not declare their presidential preference. All national convention delegates will be chosen at that state convention.
</TEXT>
