hat the nation does not appear to have reached the collective state of mind neded to defeat the drug problem. Drugs pour into <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> because there is a market for them, he said, and the battle needs to be waged against the users. Accomplices in crime are young couples who think it's all right to use drugs casually on the weekend, abstainers who look away when others use drugs, sports heroes who set a bad example by using drugs, college presidents who know drugs are on campus but fail to act, civil libertarians who tie up the courts with technicalities and sophistry and television and movie producers who glorify drugs, <PERSON> Bauer </PERSON> said. `` Unless we find the political will to penalize the users as well as the dealers,'' the drug problem will remain, he said. The nation can not buy or blast its way drug free with financial programs and the military, he said. <PERSON> Rangel </PERSON>, pressed by <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Orleans </LOCATION> Mayor <PERSON> Sidney </PERSON> <PERSON> Barthelemy </PERSON>, said he plans to introduce a measure to direct federal anti-drug funds directly to large cities, rather than through federal and state bureaucracies. In addition, <PERSON> Rangel </PERSON> called for increased participation of all federal agencies in anti-drug battles. To begin with, he said, the <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> should call a summit of nations from <LOCATION> Latin </LOCATION> <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> to find ways to cooperate in the drug war. A plan must be developed to work with people. `` You ca n't take a farmer who is making $ 10,000 on coca leaves and tell him to go back to his former crop that made $ 500,'' <PERSON> Rangel </PERSON> said. In addition to involving the <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION>, <PERSON> Rangel </PERSON> questioned the reluctance of the <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> <ORGA