<HEAD>Najib Offers To Withdraw Troops From Pakistani Border Areas</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto KAB2</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By EARLEEN FISHER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KABUL, Afghanistan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 President <PERSON> Najib </PERSON> on Monday offered to withdraw Afghan troops from their posts near the Pakistani border if anti-communist guerrillas and <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION> agree to do the same. `` We are ready to create a non-military line'' between <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Najib </PERSON> said at the opening of celebrations marking the 10th anniversary of the Afghan revolution that installed a Soviet-backed government. <PERSON> Najib </PERSON> told an assembly of three small parties loyal to his government that such a withdrawal would allow the estimated 3 million Afghan refugees in <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION> to return home. However, the proposal appeared to be little more than a face-saving acknowledgement of the difficulties the Afghan army is having against onslaughts by anti-communist guerrillas, based in <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION> and supplied with <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Chinese </LOCATION> weapons. Soviet troops entered <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION> in 1979 to help quell an uprising by a guerrilla front. The <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> has agreed to start withdrawing its estimated 115,000 troops from <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION> on May 15 under a U.N.-mediated agreement signed April 14 in <LOCATION> Geneva </LOCATION> by the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION>. The <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> and several other countries have been aiding the Afghan guerrillas via <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION>. The <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> arms the Afghan military forces. Each superpower has reserved the right to continue its assistance as long as the other one does. The guerrillas, who were not direct party to the <LOCATION> Geneva </LOCATION> accord, have vowed to continue fighting until <PERSON> Najib </PERSON>'s government is overthrown. On Sunday, <PERSON> Najib </PERSON> confirmed a guerrilla claim that the Afghan army had been pushed out of <LOCATION> Barikot </LOCATION>, a key post on the Pakistani frontier. Barikot, 150 miles northeast of <LOCATION> Kabul </LOCATION>, controls a major road leading into <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION> from <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION>. The guerrillas said the victory opened a new, direct supply route for weapons into <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION>. The guerrillas said Monday they have taken control of three other strategic towns in recent weeks: <LOCATION> Ghorband </LOCATION>, 50 miles north of <LOCATION> Kabul </LOCATION>, and <PERSON> Maarouf </PERSON> and <PERSON> Darwazgai </PERSON>, both in the south about 30 miles from the Pakistani bordar. Western sources, speaking on condition of anonymity, said the guerrillas captured Ghorband in late March. There was no immediate word on the other two claims. The guerrillas also said <PERSON> Najib </PERSON>'s government is negotating with Moslem guerillas for the release of a provincial governor captured by insurgents earlier this month. The insurgents are holding the governor of northern <LOCATION> Kunduz </LOCATION> province, the chief of police and two senior Afghan army officers. The governor and the two other officials were not identified. Brig. <PERSON> Abdullah </PERSON> <PERSON> Haq </PERSON> <PERSON> Ulomi </PERSON> said the Afghan army would withdraw from the border at `` the points that are needed _ several dozen if necessary.'' Ulomi heads the Afghan <ORGANIZATION> army </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> department </ORGANIZATION> of the <ORGANIZATION> Central </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> the </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> ruling </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> People </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Afghanistan </ORGANIZATION>. A foreign diplomat warned that <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> officials were incorrect to assume that guerrilla victories near the Pakistani border were signs the Soviet-backed government was in trouble. `` We are very surprised by the optimism of <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> officials,'' said the diplomat, who asked not be identified. `` They believe the government of <PERSON> Najib </PERSON> will collapse after the withdrawal of the Soviet troops, but this optimism seems to me and to other Western observers to be very worrying because it is absolutely not true,'' he said. <PERSON> Najib </PERSON>, in his speech at the <ORGANIZATION> Polytechnic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Kabul </LOCATION>, called the Soviet withdrawal `` the significant event of the year.'' He asserted that the Soviet troops have enabled the Afghan army to maintain a military balance with the guerrillas. <PERSON> Najib </PERSON> said his army must maintain this balance and much has to be done to prepare for the return of refugees. About 5 million Afghans _ one-third of the country's population _ have fled since the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> intervention. About 3 milllion are in <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION>, and most of the rest are in <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Najib </PERSON> spoke in <LOCATION> Dari </LOCATION> for one hour to the <ORGANIZATION> Revolutionary </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Organization </ORGANIZATION> of <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION>, the <ORGANIZATION> Peasants </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Organization </ORGANIZATION> of <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION> and the <ORGANIZATION> Toilers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Organization </ORGANIZATION> of <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION>. His remarks were translated by government employees. The 10th anniversary of the revolution is Wednesday, but parades and speeches marking the event will take place Tuesday.
