<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Here, at a glance, are highlights of actions taken Monday by the <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION>. RACIAL DISCRIMINATION The court said it will consider overturning a key civil rights precedent allowing people to sue private citizens accused of racial discrimination. Four dissenting justices accused the court of undermining the trust minority groups have in it. The court, in an extraordinary move, said it will use a <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Carolina </LOCATION> case involving charges of on-the-job racial harassment to consider throwing out a 12-year-old decision. The case is <PERSON> Patterson </PERSON> vs. <ORGANIZATION> McLean </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Credit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Union </ORGANIZATION>, 87-107. PHONE PORN The court let stand a ban on sexually explicit telephone dial-up message services in <LOCATION> Arizona </LOCATION>. The justices, without comment, refused to hear arguments that the ban violates free-speech rights. It was the first dial-a-porn case with which the court was confronted. The case is <ORGANIZATION> Carlin </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Communications </ORGANIZATION> vs. <ORGANIZATION> Mountain </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> States </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Telephone </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; <ORGANIZATION> Telegraph </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, 87-1479. PRISON PUBLICATIONS The court agreed to consider giving federal prison wardens more power to decide what publications inmates may read. The court said it will review a ruling that limits the authority of officials to censor reading material behind prison bars. The case is <PERSON> Meese </PERSON> vs. <PERSON> Abbott </PERSON>, 87-1344. AGNEW The court turned away an appeal by former Vice President <PERSON> Spiro </PERSON> <PERSON> T. </PERSON> <PERSON> Agnew </PERSON> in a lawsuit alleging he was cheated out of more than $ 2 million for arranging a deal between a defense contractor and the Argentine government. The justices, without comment, refused to order the setting aside of more than $ 340,000 in a special fund <PERSON> Agnew </PERSON> and another businessman would receive if they win the lawsuit. The case is <PERSON> Agnew </PERSON> vs. Alicanto, 87-1464. AIR SPACE The court let stand a ruling that property owners' rights are not violated when they are required to remove structures that could interfere with low-flying planes. The court, citing the lack of a `` substantial federal question,'' rejected an appeal by a <LOCATION> Cheyenne </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Wyo. </LOCATION>, man fined $ 200 a day for refusing to trim a 48-foot cottonwood tree on his property. The case is <ORGANIZATION> Rogers </ORGANIZATION> vs. <LOCATION> Cheyenne </LOCATION>, 87-1462. SEX BIAS The court turned away a case in which <LOCATION> Missouri </LOCATION> officials were found guilty of sex discrimination by not hiring enough women as highway maintenance workers. The court, without comment, rejected an appeal by state officials who said lower courts improperly weighed the evidence. The justices also refused to hear an appeal by women who said remedies ordered by the lower courts were inadequate. The cases are <ORGANIZATION> Missouri </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Highway </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> vs. <PERSON> Catlett </PERSON>, 87-1415, and <PERSON> Catlett </PERSON> vs. <ORGANIZATION> Missouri </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Highway </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION>, 87-1416. RELIGIOUS RIGHTS The court turned down an appeal by native Hawaiians who say plans for developing geothermal energy in a volcanic area will violate their religious rights. The court, without comment, let stand a ruling that the proposed development will not interfere unlawfully with access to sacred land by worshippers of the goddess <PERSON> Pele </PERSON>. The case is <PERSON> Dedman </PERSON> vs. <ORGANIZATION> Hawaii </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Land </ORGANIZATION> and Natural Resources, 87-605.
