<BYLINE>By MERRILL HARTSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> is still mulling whether to increase <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> military involvement in the <LOCATION> Persian </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Gulf </LOCATION>, a White House spokesman said today, amid indications of fresh administration concern about the American presence there. Spokesman <PERSON> Marlin </PERSON> <PERSON> Fitzwater </PERSON> said a number of options are still being weighed and that `` no decisions have been made'' on the possible broadening of the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> escort role for neutral ships in the strategic waterway. But <PERSON> Fitzwater </PERSON> contradicted remarks that administration officials had made last Friday, indicating a decision had been made to expand the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> role to allow <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> warships to protect neutral vessels under attack. Officials, who declined to be named publicly, said last week that a more aggressive <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> policy in the gulf had been decided upon. They said such a policy was aimed at deterring Iranian attacks against gulf shipping. The change in policy, they said at the time, was a direct result of the mining of a <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> frigate and Monday's extensive fighting between Iranian and <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> forces. But during his daily <ORGANIZATION> White </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> briefing today, <PERSON> Fitzwater </PERSON> talked of the possibility of returning <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> forces in the gulf to the limited rules of engagement that applied before last Monday, when the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> attacked two Iranian platforms and the two nations' forces subsequently exchanged fire. While the spokesman emphasized that several options remained under study, <PERSON> Fitzwater </PERSON> indicated a concern within the administration about an Americanization of the Iran-Iraq war. `` Right now the rules of engagement are essentially the same as they were last week, reflecting the emergency nature of the situation,'' he said. `` But the question is, where do we move back to? But I ca n't discuss specifics.'' Secretary of State <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> P. </PERSON> <PERSON> Shultz </PERSON>, interviewed from <LOCATION> Brussels </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Belgium </LOCATION>, on <ORGANIZATION> NBC-TV </ORGANIZATION>'s `` Today'' program, also indicated a <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> interest in restraining the role of <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> military involvement in the gulf. `` We will not get tied up in any serious shooting war with the Iranians,'' <PERSON> Shultz </PERSON> said. He added that the final decision is up to <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> _ and that it has n't yet been made. `` As far as our rules of engagement are concerned, what the right ones are for this stage of the game in the gulf are being considered in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, and there is a process of consultation going on and I think it's premature to describe them in any particular way,'' <PERSON> Shultz </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Fitzwater </PERSON> said that `` during the conflict last Monday, the rules -LRB- of engagement -RRB- were changed to accommodate the military situation that was encountered.'' `` You'll recall at that point that our ships were engaging hostile forces in any number of areas, and we now want to move back to our conservative set of rules. And so that decision has to be made about where to move back to,'' he said. `` You see, the rules were changed to accommodate the military aggression that was encountered that day. Once that is no longer the case, we want to move to something that would be more sustainable in the long term.'' Among the options being examined is adding <ORGANIZATION> Coast </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Guard </ORGANIZATION> ships to assist the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> fleet in the <LOCATION> Persian </LO