<SECOND>AM-Scotus-Phone Porn,600</SECOND>
<HEAD>High Court Lets Stand Ruling Against Dial-a-Porn Calls</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Scotus Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DEBORAH MESCE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> on Monday let stand an <LOCATION> Arizona </LOCATION> telephone company's ban on sexually explicit dial-up message services. In the first `` dial-a-porn'' case to reach the high court, the justices without comment declined to hear arguments that <ORGANIZATION> Mountain </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bell </ORGANIZATION>'s refusal to carry sexually explicit message services violates free-speech rights. The court's action came a week after <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> sent to President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> a bill that would ban all dial-a-porn services, which are available to callers through `` 976'' exchanges and <ORGANIZATION> AT </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; T's `` 900'' long-distance lines. State governments also have been working to limit availability of dial-a-porn services, and last week the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Communications </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> fined two <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> dial-a-porn companies $ 600,000 each for allegedly failing to prevent children from hearing their messages. The <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION>'s action `` clearly puts the ball in the phone companies' court,'' said <PERSON> Bradley </PERSON> <PERSON> Keirnes </PERSON>, vice president of <ORGANIZATION> Citizens </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Decency </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Through </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Law </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, a <LOCATION> Phoenix </LOCATION>, Ariz.-based public interest law firm specializing in obscenity law. <PERSON> Keirnes </PERSON> said phone companies now have a green light to `` pull the plug on dial-a-porn'' services without fear of violating the companies' First Amendment rights. Rep. <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON> <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Bliley </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON>, <LOCATION> R-Va </LOCATION>., who spearheaded the move in the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> to approve a dial-a-porn ban, said the court's action bolsters his belief that such a ban will withstand a court test `` It indicates the thinking of the court, which is that this kind of speech is not protected by the First Amendment,'' he said. <ORGANIZATION> Mountain </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bell </ORGANIZATION>, a <ORGANIZATION> US </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> West </ORGANIZATION> company, was pleased with the decision, but the parent company is not considering extending the <LOCATION> Arizona </LOCATION> ban to the 13 other states in its territory, a spokesman said. In <LOCATION> Arizona </LOCATION>, dial-a-porn services `` were particularly harmful to our reputation, so we felt that -LRB- a ban -RRB- was the most appropriate action for <LOCATION> Arizona </LOCATION>. But there are different circumstances in different states,'' said <ORGANIZATION> US </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> West </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> Blair </PERSON> <PERSON> Johnson </PERSON>. In its other states, <LOCATION> US </LOCATION> <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> is offering customers one-time, free blocking of 976 services, establishing a separate prefix for dial-a-porn services and is no longer billing or collecting for these services. `` We think those will be effective and give parents a tool to keep children from gaining access to these types of services,'' <PERSON> Johnson </PERSON> said. <ORGANIZATION> Pacific </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bell </ORGANIZATION> spokeswoman <PERSON> Sandy </PERSON> <PERSON> Hale </PERSON> said her company `` will review our position in light of the <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION>'s action to see if there are direct implications.'' Other Bell companies and <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Telephone </ORGA