 the rules of engagement in the gulf. While <PERSON> Fitzwater </PERSON> stressed that several options remain under study in the gulf, he said `` right now the rules of engagement are essentially the same as they were last week, reflecting the emergency nature of the situation. But the question is, where do we move back to? ... I ca n't discuss specifics.'' <PERSON> Shultz </PERSON> told interviewers that `` as far as our rules of engagement are concerned, what the right ones are for this stage of the game in the gulf are being considered in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, and there is a process of consultation going on, and I think it's premature to describe them in any particular way.'' <PERSON> Fitzwater </PERSON> said the rules of engagement were expanded a week ago `` to accommodate the military situation that was encountered'' after <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> forces bombarded two Iranian oil platforms in reprisal for the mining of the USS <PERSON> Samuel </PERSON> <PERSON> B. </PERSON> <PERSON> Roberts </PERSON> the week before. `` You'll recall at that point that our ships were engaging hostile forces in any number of areas,'' <PERSON> Fitzwater </PERSON> said. `` And we now want to move back to our conservative set of rules. And so that decision has to be made about where to move back to. ... `` The rules were changed to accommodate the military aggression that was encountered that day,'' he said. `` Once that is no longer the case, we want to move to something that would be more sustainable in the long term.'' The <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> remains officially neutral in the 7 -LCB- - year Iran-Iraq war although it used <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> warships to guard American-flagged Kuwaiti tankers from attacks since last summer
