<HEAD>Shultz Tells Denmark To Meet Responsibilities Under NATO</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT J. WIELAARD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Secretary of State <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> P. </PERSON> <PERSON> Shultz </PERSON> on Monday urged <LOCATION> Denmark </LOCATION> to `` measure up'' to its <ORGANIZATION> NATO </ORGANIZATION> responsibilities and to stop a resolution that would effectively ban allied ships from Danish ports. <PERSON> Shultz </PERSON> met with Danish Foreign Minister <PERSON> Uffe </PERSON> <PERSON> Ellemann-Jensen </PERSON> to restate <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> concerns about a <ORGANIZATION> Danish </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Parliament </ORGANIZATION> motion which demands that visiting warships not carry nuclear arms into Danish harbors. `` It constitutes a real problem,'' <PERSON> Shultz </PERSON> said of the April 14 motion. <LOCATION> Denmark </LOCATION>'s minority center-right government opposed the measure and has called for early elections May 10. `` If you like the benefits -LRB- of <ORGANIZATION> NATO </ORGANIZATION> membership -RRB- ... then you ought to like the responsibilities that go with making that possible,'' <PERSON> Shultz </PERSON> said. He met with <PERSON> Ellemann-Jensen </PERSON> after briefing <ORGANIZATION> NATO </ORGANIZATION> foreign ministers on his talks last week in <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> with Soviet leaders. The talks were held to prepare for the May 29-June 2 summit meeting between President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> and Soviet leader <PERSON> Mikhail </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>. <PERSON> Shultz </PERSON> said prospects for a treaty by then to halve <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> and Soviet strategic nuclear arms were dim. `` It's extremely difficult to get there. There are hard issues to get at. They involve a lot of pick-and-shovel work,'' he said. The issues deal with verification of compliance and counting different arms systems under a Strategic Arms Reduction Treaty, <PERSON> Shultz </PERSON> told reporters at <ORGANIZATION> NATO </ORGANIZATION> headquarters. He said he would continue negotiating after the summit in the last months of the <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration. `` We'll keep at it, we're not going to stop,'' he said, citing `` broad bipartisan support'' for a START accord in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. He denied superpower relations had slumped since last year's signing of a treaty to remove hundreds of medium-range nuclear missiles from <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> Citing <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION>'s decision to withdraw its troops from <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Shultz </PERSON> said, `` I think the picture is one in which we see general progress.'' <PERSON> Ellemann-Jensen </PERSON> said his government was looking to the May 10 elections for an answer to the <ORGANIZATION> NATO </ORGANIZATION> problem. `` We want to get a clear message from our voters that they want <LOCATION> Denmark </LOCATION> to remain a full member of the alliance,'' he said. `` If we get the signal from the voters we are asking for it will be possible to reach a fair solution.'' That means <LOCATION> Denmark </LOCATION> would stick by its current ban on nuclear arms on its soil but would not demand a declaration from visiting ships, he said. <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> and British warships, as a matter of policy, never say if their warships carry nuclear arms. The Danish resolution has led <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION> to suspend visits to <LOCATION> Denmark </LOCATION> by <ORGANIZATION> Royal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> vessels. <PERSON> Ellemann-Jensen </PERSON> said, `` Both the Americans and the British have made it clear many times it would be necessary to discuss the full participation of <LOCATION> Denmark </LOCATION> in military matters if we'' effectively banned allied warships from these two countries. <PERSON> Shultz </PERSON> said the parliamentary resolution, while an internal Danish matter, has NATO-wide implications. <LOCATION> Norway </LOCATION> also formally b