<SECOND>AM-South Africa-Explosions,0332</SECOND>
<HEAD>Two Blacks Convicted Of Murder In 1985 Land Mine Blasts</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Two alleged African National <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> guerrillas were convicted of murder Monday in connection with land mine explosions that killed seven people in 1985. One of the defendants, <PERSON> Mzondileli </PERSON> <PERSON> Nondula </PERSON>, was found guilty of planting a mine that killed two white woman and four white children as they drove in a pickup truck near the <LOCATION> Zimbabwe </LOCATION> border in December 1985. His co-defendant, <PERSON> Mthetheleli </PERSON> <PERSON> Mncube </PERSON>, was convicted of laying a mine that killed a black farm worker in the same area in November 1985. <PERSON> Mncube </PERSON> also was convicted of murdering two white policemen while trying to escape following his arrest in 1986. Both defendants pleaded innocent. Defense lawyers are scheduled to present arguments Tuesday in an effort to avoid death sentences for the pair. Evidence presented during a six-month trial in the northern town of <PERSON> Messina </PERSON> indicated that both men received military training at <ORGANIZATION> ANC </ORGANIZATION> facilities in <LOCATION> Angola </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Tanzania </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Zambia </LOCATION>. The <ORGANIZATION> ANC </ORGANIZATION>, outlawed in <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>, has waged a bombing and sabotage campaign since 1961 aimed at ending white-minority rule. <PERSON> Mncube </PERSON> described himself during the trial as `` an <ORGANIZATION> ANC </ORGANIZATION> soldier,'' but both he and <PERSON> Nondula </PERSON> said they were tortured by police before signing confessions. In a separate development Monday, the state-run <ORGANIZATION> South </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> African </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Broadcasting </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> reported that a black policeman was shot dead by an unknown assailant near <LOCATION> Newcastle </LOCATION> in northern <LOCATION> Natal </LOCATION> province. The broadcast