<HEAD>Lyng Decries EEC Intransigence Over Farm Subsidies Issue</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DON KENDALL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Farm Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> European </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Economic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Community </ORGANIZATION> has to get serious about seeking solutions to `` an increasingly chaotic condition'' in global agricultural trade or risk being blamed by other trading countries, <ORGANIZATION> Agriculture </ORGANIZATION> Secretary <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> E. </PERSON> <PERSON> Lyng </PERSON> said Monday. But the <ORGANIZATION> EEC </ORGANIZATION> `` is unwilling to even define a long-term goal in the reform of the rules of international trade,'' <PERSON> Lyng </PERSON> said. `` They term our proposal to eventually eliminate trade-distorting subsidies as ` unrealistic' or ` too far, too fast.' Yet, they have not stated what alternative they will accept.'' <PERSON> Lyng </PERSON> warned that failure to make progress in the negotiations by the time of the <ORGANIZATION> GATT </ORGANIZATION> midterm review in <LOCATION> Montreal </LOCATION> next December `` will bring into question the change for eventual success'' of the so-called <LOCATION> Uruguay </LOCATION> Round. `` I'm not pessimistic, but I'll have to admit there's not whole lot to be optimistic about at this point,'' <PERSON> Lyng </PERSON> said. He added: `` I think the European Community, unless they show some willingness to even discuss with us -LRB- their long-term objectives -RRB- are going to wake up having the problem of failure of these -LRB- talks -RRB- tossed in their laps. I think that will be unpopular throughout the world. I know it will be, and I suspect they might begin to come around a little bit.'' It has been almost a year and a half since the new <LOCATION> Uruguay </LOCATION> Round of multinational trade talks began under the General Agreement on Tariffs and Trade, or <ORGANIZATION> GATT </ORGANIZATION>. Yet, <PERSON> Lyng </PERSON> said, the major agricultural shippers are expanding export subsidies, rather than reducing them. <PERSON> Lyng </PERSON> said the <ORGANIZATION> EEC </ORGANIZATION>, for example, has just paid a subsidy equal to $ 126 per metric ton to wheat exporters, and continues to pay `` huge subsidies on a host of other commodities,'' including mixed feed, $ 291 per ton; durum wheat, $ 281 per ton; and barley, $ 130 per ton. The <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, he told a meeting of the <ORGANIZATION> Newspaper </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Farm </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Editors </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> America </ORGANIZATION>, is calling for agricultural trade reform at the <LOCATION> Uruguay </LOCATION> Round. Ultimately, under the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> proposal, international trade barriers and subidies would be eliminated over a period of 10 years or so. <PERSON> Lyng </PERSON> said the `` excessive influence of governments in farm product markets leads to a grossly inefficient allocation of resources in developed countries and leave poorer, developing countries in economic shambles.'' The worst offenders are the big nations `` who are unwilling or reluctant to change,'' he said. <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>, with huge trade surpluses from exports of industrial and consumer goods, clings to import barriers on products such as beef, rice and citrus. Other exporting countries, including the 12-nation EEC, say they are not alone in subsidizing agricultural trade and point to the Export Enhancement Program operated by the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agriculture </ORGANIZATION>. Under <ORGANIZATION> EEP </ORGANIZATION>, as it is known, private exporters are given surplus USDA-owned commodities so they can sell grain or other products to selected foreign countries, including the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> and others. Department officials claim <ORGANIZATION> EEP </ORGANIZATION> was necessary to compete with <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>'s subsidized exports.
