<HEAD>New Emigration Documents Worry Soviet Jews</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARK J. PORUBCANSKY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Jews seeking to emigrate are receiving revised invitations from <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> that promise to provide them with visas in <LOCATION> Romania </LOCATION>, activists said Monday. The activists said the change is apparently part of an effort to boost emigration to the Jewish state. But it could make it difficult for Jews to settle anywhere else, they said. Invitations from family members and the Israeli government are the official basis on which Jews are allowed to leave. Visas now come through the <ORGANIZATION> Dutch </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Embassy </ORGANIZATION>, which has handled <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>'s interests since the <ORGANIZATION> Kremlin </ORGANIZATION> broke relations after the 1967 <LOCATION> Middle </LOCATION> <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> war <PERSON> Sergei </PERSON> <PERSON> Mkrtchyan </PERSON> said Monday he knew of about a half a dozen people who did not emigrate because the Soviet visa office said they could go only to <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> with the new invitations. `` They rejected it because they wanted to go to <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>,'' he said in a telephone interview. According to the new invitations, Israeli visas will be issued in <LOCATION> Bucharest </LOCATION>, capital of <LOCATION> Romania </LOCATION>, the only Soviet bloc nation that has formal relations with <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Stolar </PERSON>, an <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> citizen who remains in <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> because his <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> wife is refused permission to leave, said Jews who want to go somewhere other than <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> are worried. `` A lot of people are talking about the problem _ whether it will increase or decrease emigration, whether the Soviets will let more people out or whether fewer people will apply,'' he said. Both he and <PERSON> Mkrtchyan </PERSON> want to go to <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> and are active in a group called `` Poor Relatives,'' for people who are denied permission to leave because a family member will not waive financial obligations imposed by law. They said the new invitations began arriving about three weeks ago and the long-term effect is unclear. In the past, many Soviet Jews left the country through <LOCATION> Vienna </LOCATION>, and traveled from there to <LOCATION> Western </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>, the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> or <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Mkrtchyan </PERSON> said it could be difficult for Jews to go anywhere except <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> from <LOCATION> Bucharest </LOCATION> because of limited connections and because a Jew arriving in <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> automatically becomes an <LOCATION> Israeli </LOCATION> citizen, limiting his ability to settle elsewhere. Jews who emigrate from the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> lose their Soviet citizenship. <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> wants Soviet Jews to settle there and has promoted a direct air link via <LOCATION> Romania </LOCATION>. Among those emigrating through <LOCATION> Bucharest </LOCATION> was <PERSON> Josef </PERSON> <PERSON> Begun </PERSON>, a prominent Soviet Jew who emigrated in January. According to the Union of Councils for Soviet Jews, only 221 of the 986 who emigrated in March went to <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>, and 42 traveled through <LOCATION> Bucharest </LOCATION>. The 986 represented the highest total in 15 months. More than 8,000 Jews were allowed to emigrate in all of 1987, many more than in any of the previous several years but still far below the peak of 51,000 in 1979. More than 2,400 Jews emigrated in the first three months of 1988. Sources said <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> instructed the <ORGANIZATION> Dutch </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Embassy </ORGANIZATION> to continue issuing visas with which Jews can emigrate through <LOCATION> Vienna </LOCATION> or any other transit city, but activists said that may not matter if Soviet authorities insist on emigrants going by way of <LOCATION> Romania </LOCATION>. Requiring Jews to leave through <LOCATION> Bucharest </LOCATION> may increase the number going to <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> by 5 to 10 percent, but the rest want to settle elsewhere, <PERSON> Mkrtchyan </PERSON> said.
