<HEAD>Oregon Newspaper Survey Shows White Resistance to Jackson</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PORTLAND, Ore. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A large number of Oregonians say <PERSON> Jesse </PERSON> <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> can not win the presidential election because he is black, but only a small number say they wo n't vote for him because of his race, according to a newspaper poll. The Sunday Oregonian reported that only 5 percent of the voters surveyed indicated they would not support <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> because he is black. But 30 percent of those surveyed said they doubted that <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> could win a presidential election. <PERSON> Pam </PERSON> <PERSON> Smith </PERSON>, an Oregonian who works for <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> in <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION> as a press aide, said the focus on race hurts <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON>. `` Was there a question of how would Americans accept a Greek?'' she asked, referring to <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION> Gov. <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON>, <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON>'s remaining rival for the Democratic presidential nomination. The poll of 600 registered voters was conducted for the newspaper April 11-16 by <ORGANIZATION> Griggs-Anderson </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Research </ORGANIZATION>. It included Democrats, Republicans and independant voters.
