<BYLINE>By ED BLANCHE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NICOSIA, Cyprus (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> called Monday for the nation's youth to prepare to go quickly to the battlefront. <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION> announced it has successfully tested a new missile capable of reaching deep into Iranian territory. President <PERSON> Ali </PERSON> <PERSON> Khamenei </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION>, speaking on <ORGANIZATION> Tehran </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Radio </ORGANIZATION>, said young Iranians `` should get ready to to be sent to the fronts and to fight against the enemies of the Islamic revolution in a most extensive way.'' `` The young people, especially those who have received training and who are ready, should move forward their allotted time for dispatch and go earlier. Others too should continue their dispatch ... in an accelerated form,'' he said. <ORGANIZATION> Tehran </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Radio </ORGANIZATION> said <PERSON> Khamenei </PERSON> spoke after a meeting of the <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> War </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Effort </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION>. The broadcast was monitored in <LOCATION> Cyprus </LOCATION>. <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> suffered a battlefield setback 10 days ago when <LOCATION> Iraqi </LOCATION> forces recaptured the <LOCATION> Faw </LOCATION> <LOCATION> peninsula </LOCATION> in southern <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION>. It had been seized by Iranian troops in February 1986. The two countries have been at war since September 1980. <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION>'s official news agency, also monitored in <LOCATION> Cyprus </LOCATION>, said a powerful new surface-to-surface missile has been tested successfully. The announcement could serve as a warning to <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> not to respond to the loss of Faw by resuming the deadly missile duel known as the `` war of the cities.'' The last such battle lasted from Feb. 29 to last Thursday, with the capitals of <LOCATION> Baghdad </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Tehran </LOCATION> being frequent targets. Brig. <PERSON> Hussein </PERSON> <PERSON> Kamel </PERSON> <PERSON> Hassan </PERSON>, director of <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION>'s military industries, informed President <PERSON> Saddam </PERSON> <PERSON> Hussein </PERSON> that the new missile named al-Abass has a range of 550 miles, according to the news agency. <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION> has used al-Hussein missiles since last August in the duel with <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION>. It claimed the al-Hussein missiles were domestically produced, but Western military analysts believe they are Soviet-designed SS-1 Scud-B weapons with special rocket boosters to give them a range of up to 400 miles. The agency report gave no details of the new missile. Western analysts said they thought <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION> may have obtained a larger missile that also could be equipped with boosters. There was a lull in action along the 730-mile front. Both sides reported scattered skirmishes and artillery duels.
