<HEAD>Officials Sacrifice Marsh To Defend Other Wetland Areas</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MARTINEZ, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Officials planned Monday to sacrifice a section of wildlife-rich marshland to an oil spill, saying the tactic would save hundreds more acres of wetlands. `` We're trying to keep new areas from becoming oiled,'' said <PERSON> Brian </PERSON> <PERSON> Hunter </PERSON> of the state Department of Fish and Game. `` We're willing to try and capture as much oil as we can in 20 acres of marsh. About 21,000 gallons of thick, unrefined crude gushed Saturday from a storage tank at <ORGANIZATION> Shell </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Oil </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>'s <PERSON> Martinez </PERSON> refinery, 30 miles northeast of <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Francisco </LOCATION>. By Monday morning, a slick stretched for 10 miles in <LOCATION> Suisun </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bay </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Carquinez </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Strait </LOCATION> but was beginning to dissipate in tidal currents. The biggest concentration was confined to an area of marshland and coated at least 100 birds. <ORGANIZATION> Coast </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Guard </ORGANIZATION> spotter planes, six vessels with oil skimmers and 16 vacuum tank-trucks raced to capture oil and save wetland animals. Floating oil booms were laid in the water to keep oil away from wildlife areas. <ORGANIZATION> Coast </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Guard </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> Ken </PERSON> <PERSON> Massey </PERSON> estimated it could take until next week to clean up the spill. <ORGANIZATION> Shell </ORGANIZATION> acknowledged responsibility for the spill, and <PERSON> Massey </PERSON> said the company would have to pay for the costs of the clean-up and damages, which would include new paint for the bottoms of thousands of pleasure boats in area marinas. There was no immediate estimate of the damage. <ORGANIZATION> Shell </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> Bill </PERSON> <PERSON> Sharkey </PERSON> said the spill was the company's worst in 73 years The last at the 850-acre refinery occurred in June 1986 when a tank overflowed 8,000 gallons of oil. By Monday about 100 birds _ including egrets, avocets, cinnamon teals, mallard ducks, grebes, herons and the endangered clapper rail bird _ had been rescued and taken to centers in <LOCATION> Berkeley </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Walnut </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Creek </LOCATION> for cleaning, <PERSON> Hunter </PERSON> said. The spill also threatened many nests. Volunteers also reported a dozen dead muskrats, several oil-coated turtles and a dead heron.
