<HEAD>GAO: Navy Missiles Having Quality Problems</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TIM AHERN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Four of the <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION>'s main non-nuclear missiles still are having quality problems that have delayed delivery or produced some substandard weapons, the <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Accounting </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Office </ORGANIZATION> said Monday. `` All of the missile systems we examined had defects _ that is, they failed in one respect or another to conform with contract specifications,'' said the congressional watchdog agency. The <ORGANIZATION> GAO </ORGANIZATION> reviewed the <LOCATION> Phoenix </LOCATION>, High-Speed Anti-Radiation -LRB- HARM -RRB-, <LOCATION> Harpoon </LOCATION>, and <LOCATION> Sparrow </LOCATION> missiles, four weapons deployed on a variety of <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> ships for use against other ships and planes. The review, done for the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Energy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION> investigations subcommittee, found:
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
 _ Design and workmanship problems on safety and arming devices aboard the <LOCATION> Phoenix </LOCATION> AIM-54C, problems which the <ORGANIZATION> GAO </ORGANIZATION> said have delayed deliveries of more than 500 <LOCATION> Phoenix </LOCATION> missiles The weapon is built by <ORGANIZATION> Hughes </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Aircraft </ORGANIZATION> of <LOCATION> Tucson </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ariz. </LOCATION> _ Pressure transducers for some HARMs may not have been tested before being put into the missiles The transducer is used in activating the weapon's target-seeking device. The chief contractor is <ORGANIZATION> Texas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Instruments </ORGANIZATION>. _ Altimeters for the Harpoon were being accepted under a contract deviation permitting a soldering-related condition which the <ORGANIZATION> GAO </ORGANIZATION> said could affect the weapon's reliability The main contractor is <ORGANIZATION> McDonnell-Douglas </ORGANIZATION>. _ Detonators on some Sparrows were unknowingly built without enough explosive compound to set off the warhead The chief contractor is <ORGANIZATION> Raytheon </ORGANIZATION>. Most of the problems occurred at the level of subcontractors, the <ORGANIZATION> GAO </ORGANIZATION> said. `` One common problem was that changes were made in manufacturing processes which were unknown to the prime contractor, but affected the quality of the product,'' the <ORGANIZATION> GAO </ORGANIZATION> told <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>. Many of the problems related to soldering, but it is unclear how serious the problems are, the <ORGANIZATION> GAO </ORGANIZATION> said. `` Some contractors and government officials believe that certain requirements in the <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION>'s soldering specification are more stringent than necessary to have a reliable missile,'' the report said. `` They cite high reliability rates and the successful use of missiles that deviate from the soldering specifications as evidence that the <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION>'s soldering specifications may be too stringent,'' it said. The <ORGANIZATION> Pentagon </ORGANIZATION>, in a response that was part of the review, said it partially agrees with the <ORGANIZATION> GAO </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Jack </PERSON> <PERSON> Katzen </PERSON>, deputy assistant secretary of <ORGANIZATION> defense </ORGANIZATION> for systems, said the <ORGANIZATION> Pentagon </ORGANIZATION> `` acknowledges that a number of problems have been experienced during the production of <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> missiles.'' But, <PERSON> Katzen </PERSON> added, `` contrary to the <ORGANIZATION> GAO </ORGANIZATION> implication, in no case has the <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> knowingly accepted missiles suspected of containing defects that could affect the performance of the missile. In any case where the defects were determined to affect performance, the contractor was required to take the necessary corrective actions.'' In addition, the <ORGANIZATION> GAO </ORGANIZATION> noted, pilots, ordnance officers, and other <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> officials aboard ships `` were satisfied with the missiles' performance and capabilities and cited no particular problems.
