<HEAD>Britain Announces Approval of Four-Nation Plan To Build Jet
Fighter</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MAUREEN JOHNSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION> on Monday announced its approval of a $ 37.4 billion jet fighter project involving four European nations. <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION> was the first to declare its support of the European Fighter Aircraft. No final decisions have been made by the governments of <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Italy </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Spain </LOCATION>. Defense Secretary <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Younger </PERSON> told Parliament the British decision still depends on agreement by the three other countries. The first of the 800 aircraft are to be in service in 1996. British officials expect the defense ministers of the four countries will approve the project at a meeting in <LOCATION> Hanover </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>, on May 11. Under a preliminary accord signed in September, <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION> each will pay one-third of the cost, <LOCATION> Italy </LOCATION> 21 percent and <LOCATION> Spain </LOCATION> 13 percent. <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION> are to each order 250 of the warplanes, with the first to come into service in 1996. The estimated cost of each jet will be $ 49 million, and some West German critics say that is too much. Younger said the <ORGANIZATION> European </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Fighter </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Aircraft </ORGANIZATION> `` will fulfill a vital defense need in the best and most cost-effective way. It will continue the trend of successful European collaboration in aerospace -LRB- and -RRB- it will ensure that our industry remains in the forefront of this technology to the end of the century and beyond.'' <PERSON> Denzil </PERSON> <PERSON> Davies </PERSON>, the opposition <ORGANIZATION> Labor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>'s defense spokesman, expressed relief that `` on this occasion at least the government has been forced'' to agree to European rather than American technology. In 1986, <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION> scrapped its own surveillance-plane system that had cost millions of dollars and ordered instead Airborne Warning and Control -LRB- AWACs -RRB- aircraft produced by the Seattle-based <ORGANIZATION> Boeing </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co </ORGANIZATION>. The <ORGANIZATION> European </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Fighter </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Aircraft </ORGANIZATION> is among the projects on which the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and its <LOCATION> European </LOCATION> allies are supposed to share information to avoid duplication in developing technology.
