<HEAD>Former Argentine General Ordered To Pay $21 Million In Civil
Rights Case</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BOB EGELKO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A former Argentine general facing extradition has been ordered to pay $ 21 million to a lawyer who was held four years without charges and tortured repeatedly in a prison run by the general's soldiers. The judgment against <PERSON> Carlos </PERSON> <PERSON> Suarez </PERSON> <PERSON> Mason </PERSON>, made public Monday, is the largest known damage award by a <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> District </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> for human rights abuses, said <PERSON> Joanne </PERSON> <PERSON> Hoeper </PERSON>, a lawyer for plaintiff <PERSON> Horacio </PERSON> <PERSON> Martinez-Baca </PERSON>. <PERSON> Suarez </PERSON> <PERSON> Mason </PERSON>, commander of the <ORGANIZATION> First </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corps </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Buenos </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Aires </LOCATION> from 1976 to 1979, during a period of military rule, `` directed a pattern and practice of terror against the general population of <LOCATION> Argentina </LOCATION>,'' said the ruling by <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> District Judge <PERSON> Samuel </PERSON> <PERSON> Conti </PERSON>. <PERSON> Suarez </PERSON> <PERSON> Mason </PERSON>, a fugitive from <LOCATION> Argentina </LOCATION> who is being held without bail during extradition proceedings, never submitted a response to the civil suit, refused to answer pretrial questions and was held in default by <PERSON> Conti </PERSON>. <PERSON> Suarez </PERSON> <PERSON> Mason </PERSON> has insisted he has no money after spending his last $ 100,000 on lawyers for his extradition case. <PERSON> Ray </PERSON> <PERSON> Archuleta </PERSON>, a lawyer who sought to represent <PERSON> Suarez </PERSON> <PERSON> Mason </PERSON> in the civil suit did not return a reporter's calls. <PERSON> Suarez </PERSON> <PERSON> Mason </PERSON>, 64, fled <LOCATION> Argentina </LOCATION> after a civilian government came to power in 1983. He was arrested in January 1987 at his home in <LOCATION> Foster </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION>, south of <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Francisco </LOCATION>, after <LOCATION> Argentina </LOCATION> located him and requested his extradition. Another judge is scheduled to rule Wednesday on <LOCATION> Argentina </LOCATION>'s attempt to extradite him on charges of 43 murders and 24 kidnappings, allegedly committed by soldiers under his command <PERSON> Martinez-Baca </PERSON>'s suit is one of three filed in the <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Francisco </LOCATION> federal court by former Argentinians who say they were tortured, or their relatives killed, by soldiers under <PERSON> Suarez </PERSON> <PERSON> Mason </PERSON>'s supervision <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> courts have allowed civil suits against foreigners in their jurisdiction for violations of internationally recognized human rights, such as torture and summary execution. <PERSON> Martinez-Baca </PERSON>, a labor union lawyer and former local government official in <LOCATION> Mendoza </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Argentina </LOCATION>, said he was arrested in March 1976, six days after a military coup, and tortured several times before his release in April 1980. He said <PERSON> Suarez </PERSON> <PERSON> Mason </PERSON> once intervened personally to block his release. The damages can be collected against any of <PERSON> Suarez </PERSON> <PERSON> Mason </PERSON>'s assets that <PERSON> Martinez-Baca </PERSON> and his lawyers can find Ms. <PERSON> Hoeper </PERSON> said she was skeptical about <PERSON> Suarez </PERSON> <PERSON> Mason </PERSON>'s claim of poverty. `` This is someone who is alleged to have taken many millions of dollars when he was in a position of power in <LOCATION> Argentina </LOCATION>,'' she said. `` He paid his attorneys $ 100,000 in wire transfers from <LOCATION> Argentina </LOCATION> and we're sure there's more where that came from.'' <PERSON> Martinez-Baca </PERSON>, who lives in <LOCATION> Oakland </LOCATION> and works in a law office, said he doubted he would ever collect all the money. He said he would donate half of anything he gets to a fund for victims of human rights abuses in <LOCATION> Argentina </LOCATION>.
