<HEAD>Factory Converting Missile Carriers into Building Cranes</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A factory in <LOCATION> Odessa </LOCATION> is planning to convert platforms used to transport SS-20 missiles into building cranes as the weapons are dismantled under a U.S.-Soviet arms control treaty, <ORGANIZATION> Tass </ORGANIZATION> reported Monday. The official news agency said the first missile platform has arrived at the <ORGANIZATION> Odessa </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Heavy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lifter </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Factory </ORGANIZATION> in the Ukrainian republic. Soviet engineers have designed an 80-ton crane will be mounted on the former missile chassis, <ORGANIZATION> Tass </ORGANIZATION> said. President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> and Soviet leader <PERSON> Mikhail </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> signed a teaty last December to eliminate intermediate-range nuclear missiles. The <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> began pulling its SS-20 missiles out of <LOCATION> Eastern </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> earlier this year, although neither the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> nor the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> has yet ratified the treaty.
