 President <PERSON> Mato </PERSON> <PERSON> Andric </PERSON> of the Yugoslav republic of <LOCATION> Bosnia-Hercegovina </LOCATION> on Monday withdrew his candidacy for a new term in office after being implicated in a major financial scandal, <ORGANIZATION> Tanjug </ORGANIZATION> news agency said. <PERSON> Andric </PERSON> was the only candidate and would have been formally elected at a session of the <ORGANIZATION> Bosnian </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Parliament </ORGANIZATION> on April 27. On Sunday the official Bosnian youth organization criticized <PERSON> Andric </PERSON> for his part in a scandal in which the Bosnian food-processing firm Agrokomerc last year issued uncovered promissory notes worth about $ 1 billion. The scandal is the worst in Yugoslav history and led to the resignation and replacement of other Bosnian officials. The youth organization said it would not support <PERSON> Andric </PERSON> because of several `` economic and political flaws'' that occurred in the republic during his term, including the Agrokomerc scandal.
