<HEAD>AP Correspondents Discuss World Hotspots</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RON STATON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HONOLULU (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Signs of thawing in U.S.-Soviet relations are giving a measure of hope to some people in the strife-torn <LOCATION> Middle </LOCATION> <LOCATION> East </LOCATION>, The <ORGANIZATION> Associated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION>' chief correspondent there said Monday. `` They hope that there is a spinoff there for the <LOCATION> Middle </LOCATION> <LOCATION> East </LOCATION>,'' said <PERSON> Nick </PERSON> <PERSON> Tatro </PERSON>, the <ORGANIZATION> AP </ORGANIZATION>'s chief of bureau in <LOCATION> Jerusalem </LOCATION>. `` We see in the <LOCATION> Middle </LOCATION> <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> a certain loss of hope, a very negative type of atmosphere,'' he said. <PERSON> Tatro </PERSON> and four other <ORGANIZATION> AP </ORGANIZATION> executives and correspondents discussed the situation in their areas in a conversation with <ORGANIZATION> AP </ORGANIZATION> President <PERSON> Louis </PERSON> <PERSON> D. </PERSON> <PERSON> Boccardi </PERSON> during the <ORGANIZATION> AP </ORGANIZATION>'s annual meeting here Monday. Also participating in the discussion, called `` The World's Hotspots: A Firsthand View,'' were <PERSON> Bryna </PERSON> <PERSON> Brennan </PERSON>, correspondent in <LOCATION> Central </LOCATION> <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>; <PERSON> Terence </PERSON> <PERSON> P. </PERSON> <PERSON> Hunt </PERSON>, chief White House correspondent; <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Putzel </PERSON>, chief of bureau, <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION>; and <PERSON> Barry </PERSON> <PERSON> Renfrew </PERSON>, chief of bureau, <LOCATION> Seoul </LOCATION> The failure of Secretary of State <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> P. </PERSON> <PERSON> Shultz </PERSON> and <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> Foreign Secretary <PERSON> Eduard </PERSON> <PERSON> Shevardnadze </PERSON> to find a breakthrough on arms control `` makes it sure that arms control will not be the centerpiece'' of the upcoming summit between President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> and Soviet leader <PERSON> Mikhail </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>, said <PERSON> Putzel </PERSON>. Despite that, <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>'s staff will be looking for a big public relations gain for the president, <PERSON> Hunt </PERSON> said. `` Unless the president stumbles badly, there is always a bounce that comes out of the summit,'' he said. <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> will address the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> people and a group of Soviet students during the May summit and will stress that if <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> is sincere about giving the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> people more freedoms, he should grant them passports to travel freely and ease the restrictions on the literature they can read, <PERSON> Hunt </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Renfrew </PERSON> said <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION> was hoping for success is hosting the summer Olympics. `` They hope the Olympics will launch the country on the path cut out for themselves as a second <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>,'' he said. However, <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION>'s potential for violeance can not be underestimated, he said, and the North could engage in a major provocation and interrupt the Olympics, he said. <PERSON> Brennan </PERSON> said wars in <LOCATION> Guatemala </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> El </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Salvador </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION> were `` essentially civil wars which started as reaction to poverty and land distribution, which was completely unfair.''
