<HEAD>Black Labor Federation Angered By Threatened Wage Freeze</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID CRARY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 This nation's main black labor federation warned Monday of `` anger and confrontation'' if President P.W. <PERSON> Botha </PERSON> fulfills a threat to impose wage controls in the private sector. `` The government underestimates just how sensitive an issue wages is,'' said <PERSON> Frank </PERSON> <PERSON> Meintjies </PERSON>, spokesman for the <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> South </ORGANIZATION> African Trade Unions. `` We completely reject the state president's plans to impose a general wage freeze.'' <PERSON> Meintjies </PERSON> said <PERSON> Botha </PERSON> may feel he can curb wages because black workers have no vote, `` but he will have to deal with other consequences _ the anger and confrontation of millions of workers crucially located at the point of production.'' The government imposed a wage freeze for public employees earlier this year as part of its campaign to curb the current 13.4 percent annual inflation rate. This drew bitter protests from white teachers and railway workers, among others. <PERSON> Botha </PERSON> complained last week in Parliament that the private sector was not holding down salaries and said legislation was being drafted to force wage and price restraints. He said private employers were envisioning wage increases in the range of 15 percent. `` The reaction thus far from the private sector has been disappointing,'' <PERSON> Botha </PERSON> said. `` It is becoming increasingly clear that this quid pro quo will not come about by means of persuasion or voluntary teamwork. Other mechanisms will have to be found.'' Major business organizations expressed concern about <PERSON> Botha </PERSON>'s statement The chairman of a nationwide grocery store chain defended his company's recent decision to grant wage increases of up to 25 percent to the predominantly black work force. `` The bigger increases were confined to the most needy in the lower income groups,'' said <PERSON> Raymond </PERSON> <PERSON> Ackerman </PERSON> of Pick' n Pay. `` If we did not negotiate the recent increases in a responsible fashion ... we would have faced strikes which would have been far more costly in the long run.'' <PERSON> Mentjies </PERSON> said that if the government sought wage restraints, it `` should start by cutting salaries fo government ministers, directors and shareholders.'' `` The working class does not want to pay for the disasters of apartheid's political and economic system,'' <PERSON> Meintjies </PERSON> said. `` Employers will have to decide whether they will be browbeaten or use their clout to oppose the wage freeze.'' The <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> South </ORGANIZATION> African Trade Unions, which claims 750,000 members, was the target of a government decree on Feb. 25 barring it from political activities. The federation, which has taken a militant and active stance against apartheid, is scheduled to hold a national assembly this weekend to discuss the ban. By law and custom, apartheid establishes a racially segregated society in which the 26 million blacks have no vote in national affairs. The 5 million whites control the economy and maintain separate districts, schools and health services.
</TEXT>
