<HEAD>Britain Says It Could Not Land Troops in Non-Nuclear Denmark</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> Secretary <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Younger </PERSON> said Monday that if fellow <ORGANIZATION> NATO </ORGANIZATION> member <LOCATION> Denmark </LOCATION> adopts a policy of forcing visiting ships to say if they are carrying nuclear arms, <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION> will not be able to land troops there. `` If we can not send ships into that situation we clearly would not physically be able to deliver 13,500 British troops of the <LOCATION> U.K </LOCATION>. Mobile Force on site without ships to transport them,'' <PERSON> Younger </PERSON> told a luncheon for foreign correspondents. <LOCATION> Denmark </LOCATION>'s conservative Prime Minister <PERSON> Poul </PERSON> <PERSON> Schlueter </PERSON> has called an election for May 10 in a showdown with left-of-center foes over the nuclear issue and its effect on the <ORGANIZATION> North </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Atlantic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Treaty </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Organization </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Schlueter </PERSON> heads a minority coalition government. He called the election rather than implement a parliamentary vote that could have forced visiting warships to declare if they had nuclear arms. The <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION> both refuse, as a matter of policy, to say if their warships carry nuclear arms. <LOCATION> Denmark </LOCATION> is a key <ORGANIZATION> NATO </ORGANIZATION> country geographically. <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION> is supposed to land reinforcements there as part of the defense strategy of the Western alliance. Privately, British officials have expressed concern that if <LOCATION> Denmark </LOCATION> insists on a nuclear arms declaration, <LOCATION> Norway </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Greece </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Spain </LOCATION>, other <ORGANIZATION> NATO </ORGANIZATION> members with strong anti-nuclear sentiments, might follow suit. <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION> and the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> have already stopped visits to <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Zealand </LOCATION>, a non-NATO member, because it insists that ships disclose the presence of nuclear arms on board. `` We and our <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> allies have a very firm policy that we never confirm or deny that any of our ships has nor has not got nuclear weapons on board,'' said Younger. `` It would be valuable information to the outside world to know either that they have or have not.''
