<HEAD>Appeals Court Reverses Ruling on Documents in Teamsters Case</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CINCINNATI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A federal appeals court Monday threw out a lower court's order requiring government prosecutors to share secret documents with lawyers for indicted Teamsters President <PERSON> Jackie </PERSON> <PERSON> Presser </PERSON>. <PERSON> Presser </PERSON>'s defense has claimed that the government documents would prove his innocence. But a three-judge panel of the 6th U.S. <ORGANIZATION> Circuit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Appeals </ORGANIZATION> unanimously agreed that <PERSON> Presser </PERSON> and two <ORGANIZATION> Teamsters </ORGANIZATION> union co-defendants had no constitutional right of access to the documents, overturning a ruling last year by <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> District Judge <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> White </PERSON> in <LOCATION> Cleveland </LOCATION>. Federal prosecutors argued that they should be permitted to keep the documents confidential until <PERSON> Presser </PERSON> and co-defendants <PERSON> Harold </PERSON> <PERSON> Friedman </PERSON> and <PERSON> Anthony </PERSON> <PERSON> Hughes </PERSON>, fellow officers of <LOCATION> Cleveland </LOCATION>'s Teamsters Local 507, went on trial The trial is scheduled for July 12 in White's court. The three defendants were charged in a May 1986 indictment with arranging a $ 700,000 payroll-padding scheme that put `` ghost employees'' on the payroll of Local 507. <PERSON> Presser </PERSON>, 60, is secretary-treasurer of Local 507 as well as president of the 1.6 million-member <ORGANIZATION> Teamsters </ORGANIZATION> union. The defense has argued that the documents would show that <PERSON> Presser </PERSON> and the other defendants were serving as government informants and that the <ORGANIZATION> FBI </ORGANIZATION> had authorized the payroll-padding scheme. `` In essence, the district court concluded ... that the defense has a constitutional right to know the tactical strengths and weaknesses of the government's case against it,'' appeals Judge <PERSON> Danny </PERSON> <PERSON> Boggs </PERSON> wrote for the 6th Circuit court. `` The <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> has never held that the Constitution creates such a right and we do not believe that it exists,'' <PERSON> Boggs </PERSON> wrote. Defense lawyer <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Climaco </PERSON>, contacted through his <LOCATION> Cleveland </LOCATION> office, said he was unaware of the ruling and declined immediate comment.
