4th graf pvs: As in ...; DELETES 15th graf pvs, ``About 26.2 ... to
conform.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By PHIL BROWN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Voters on Tuesday cast ballots for the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Assembly </ORGANIZATION> in an election the governing <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> was expected to win over a divided opposition. A few hours after the polls opened at 7 a.m. -LRB- 6 p.m. EDT Monday -RRB-, election officials said voting was progressing smoothly in fine spring weather. Police were on full alert. The polls close at 6 p.m. -LRB- 5 a.m. EDT Tuesday -RRB- and most results were expected to be known within hours. About 26.2 million people were registered to vote. At 9 a.m., election officials reported a 9.5 percent voter turnout, compared to 9.3 percent during the same period in the Dec. 16 presidential election. Despite the unexpectedly strong early turnout, election officials predicted the overall voting rate would not be high. Newspapers had predicted a turnout lower than the 89 percent in December balloting and 84 percent in the last parliamentary election in February 1985. The <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> of President <PERSON> Roh </PERSON> <PERSON> Tae-woo </PERSON>, who won the December election with 36 percent of the vote, was expected to win a majority in the 299-seat <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Assembly </ORGANIZATION> with less than half of the popular vote. As in December, a split in the opposition vote was expected to help the governing party. Each side has accused the other of fomenting violence, and opposition leaders say more trouble may follow if people feel Tuesday's elections are rigged. Police fired tear gas Monday at about 1,500 students who protested in two cities. Authorities reported 90 cases of election-related violence during he 18-day campaign, with more than 150 people detained and 77 formally charged. Scores have been injured, but no exact count was available. At least 20 injuries were reported Monday. Press reports said 145,000 national police were on full alert with 55,000 assigned to the 13,812 polling stations. <PERSON> Roh </PERSON>'s party says it provides the stability necessary for continued eonomic progress and the democratic reforms he has promised. The opposition, whose divisiveness cost it the advantage gained through widespread anti-government protests last summer, says victory by the <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> means one-party dictatorship. Opposition leaders also have attacked the governing party about an embezzlement scandal in which former President <PERSON> Chun </PERSON> <PERSON> Doo-hwan </PERSON>'s younger brother has been arrested A few dozen of the 224 single-member election districts are seen as opposition strongholds, but many others have one government candidate running against two rivals from the opposition. Spokesman for <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> say they hope to win about 125 districts, along with about 38 of the 75 seats to be awarded on the basis of a party's share of the vote nationwide. It held 160 of the 276 seats in the last <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Assembly </ORGANIZATION>, chosen in 1985. Under a new constitution that took effect in February, when <PERSON> Roh </PERSON> began his five-year term, the new assembly will serve for four years and has the power to investigate government actions. The president no longer can dissolve it. Opposition and government parties have traded charges of vote-buying and the South Korean press has reported widespread irregularities. <PERSON> Chai </PERSON> <PERSON> Mun-shik </PERSON>, chairman of the <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>, said in a statement Monday that candidate <PERSON> Kwon </PERSON> <PERSON> Joong-dong </PERSON> was expelled after prosecutors displayed 1,345 envelopes, each containing 20,000 won -LRB- $ 27 -RRB- and campaign leaflets for <PERSON> Kwon </PERSON>. <PERSON> Chai </PERSON> apologized to the nation for <PERSON> Kwon </PERSON>'s `` betrayal of party principles of fair elections.'' Supporters of the opposition said they found thousands of the envelopes Sunday night at a post office in <LOCATION> Andong </LOCATION>, south of <LOCATION> Seoul </LOCATION>. Prosecutors later ordered the arrests of two ruling party supporters in <LOCATION> Andong </LOCATION> on charges of trying to buy votes for <PERSON> Kwon </PERSON> with about 85 million won -LRB- $ 114,865 -RRB- found in 4,296 envelopes at a post office, the Korean news agency <ORGANIZATION> Yonhap </ORGANIZATION> reported. Police said they had detained 173 people in connection with non-violent violations of election law and formally charged 120. Actions involved include tearing down or pasting over election posters and producing allegedly slanderous campaign leaflets. Firebombs and rocks have been thrown at campaign rallies and political party offices. Supporters of rival candidates have fought in the streets over such things as the content of campaign leaflets and placement or removal of posters.
