<HEAD>Panama Gets New Cabinet</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: New grafs 1-13 UPDATE with banks to resume some suspended
services, new foreign minister's remarks. Picks up 9th graf pvs, In
Washington ...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By REID G. MILLER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PANAMA CITY, Panama (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Banking </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> said Monday that <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION>'s banks could immediately resume offering a dozen services that had been suspended following <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> actions directed against this nation's economy. The services include handling letters of credit, collecting outstanding loans and transferring funds within the country. The commission called resumption of the 12 services `` an important and decisive step in the gradual and ordered process'' toward normal banking operations. The nation's banks closed March 4 because there was not enough cash to cover withdrawals. Some banks reopened last week, but only to accept deposits. <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION>'s civilian chief executive, <PERSON> Manuel </PERSON> <PERSON> Solis </PERSON> <PERSON> Palma </PERSON>, met earlier Monday with new Cabinet members and other advisers in a renewed effort to find a way out of the deepening financial and political crisis. <PERSON> Solis </PERSON> <PERSON> Palma </PERSON> named seven new ministers to the 12-member Cabinet on Sunday night, three of them to sensitive posts in foreign and economic policy. He said the chief task would be to achieve full resumption of banking services. Several diplomats and other observers said privately the new ministers appeared to be technocrats without sharply defined political leanings. <PERSON> Solis </PERSON> <PERSON> Palma </PERSON>, considered to be a leftist, said he had no plans to interfere with private business or industry. He said he is willing to talk with opponents, but not if they continue demanding the resignation of Gen. <PERSON> Manuel </PERSON> <PERSON> Antonio </PERSON> <PERSON> Noriega </PERSON>, who commands the military and police and has the real power in <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION>. `` What we will not do is surrender before the start of battle,'' the acting president said. <PERSON> Noriega </PERSON> is under indictment in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> on drug trafficking charges, accusations which he denies. The <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration has been trying to oust him since since last summer, applying a series of sanctions that have paralyzed the economy. <PERSON> Jorge </PERSON> <PERSON> E. </PERSON> <PERSON> Ritter </PERSON>, <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION>'s new foreign minister, said Monday in an interview at the <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nations </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> that his top priorities are normalizing relations with the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and persuading it to lift its economic sanctions against <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Ritter </PERSON>, scheduled to return to <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION> on Tuesday, had served as <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> ambassador for the past 14 months. In <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, an opposition leader said a group of Panamanian dissidents is planning a military operation against <PERSON> Noriega </PERSON> by next week. Ambassador <PERSON> Juan </PERSON> <PERSON> B. </PERSON> <PERSON> Sosa </PERSON>, who has remained loyal to ousted President <PERSON> Eric </PERSON> <PERSON> Arturo </PERSON> <PERSON> Delvalle </PERSON>, told reporters the group is made up of very knowledgeable officers who have many friends in the Panamanian <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Forces </ORGANIZATION>, which <PERSON> Noriega </PERSON> commands. <PERSON> Sosa </PERSON> gave no details, but the group apparently includes high-ranking defectors who went to the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> soon after <PERSON> Noreiga </PERSON> deposed <PERSON> Delvalle </PERSON> on Feb. 26. <PERSON> Solis </PERSON> <PERSON> Palma </PERSON> said the first task of his new education minister would be to dismantle what he called the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rumors </ORGANIZATION>. The latest rumors had said his new appointees would be leftist ideologues. `` We are a capitalist group being attacked by other capitalists,'' <PERSON> Solis </PERSON> <PERSON> Palma </PERSON> told a news conference soon after introducing his new Cabinet members. He also rejected earlier reports in state-run newspapers that called his new team a `` war cabinet.'' The new ministers replace officials <PERSON> Solis </PERSON> <PERSON> Palma </PERSON> inherited when he replaced <PERSON> Delvalle </PERSON>. The National Assembly, dominated by <PERSON> Noriega </PERSON>'s supporters, ousted <PERSON> Delvalle </PERSON> a day after he tried to dismiss <PERSON> Noriega </PERSON> as commander of the Defense Forces <PERSON> Solis </PERSON> <PERSON> Palma </PERSON>'s title is minister in charge of the presidency.
