<HEAD>Billionaire Blames America's Decline On Business, Not Politicians</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHRISTINE DONNELLY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HONOLULU (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> billionaire <PERSON> H. </PERSON> <PERSON> Ross </PERSON> <PERSON> Perot </PERSON> on Monday said the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> had declined as a leader in world affairs and that business leaders, not politicians, are to blame. Since the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> economy depends on tax-paying workers, business leaders should work harder to create more jobs, <PERSON> Perot </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Perot </PERSON>, a 57-year-old businessman and philanthropist who in 1978 financed the rescue of two employees held hostage in <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION>, was keynote speaker at the <ORGANIZATION> Associated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION> Annual Luncheon held here Monday. The luncheon was held on the first day of the 102nd Annual Convention of the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Newspaper </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Publishers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION>. More than 2,000 people are attending the three-day convention. <PERSON> Perot </PERSON> said the country's decline began after World War II. `` We were complacent and arrogant'' after the war, he said. `` We gave it away at a time when we had an incredible edge. `` We've become a people who want to feel good now, at any cost, and let tomorrow take care of itself,'' he said. `` We and not the elected officials are the dwarfs and the wimps.'' <PERSON> Perot </PERSON> said other countries, especially in the <LOCATION> Asia-Pacific </LOCATION> region, are outpacing the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> in education, trade and technology. He said that before the federal government can cure the huge budget deficit, individual Americans must learn not to spend more than they earn. `` The greatest nation in the history of civilization has given up trying to live within its means,'' he said.
