<HEAD>Row Between Greece, Turkey Blocks EEC Meeting</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LUXEMBOURG (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A row over <LOCATION> Cyprus </LOCATION> on Monday between <LOCATION> Greek </LOCATION> and Turkish officials led to cancellation of a <ORGANIZATION> European </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Economic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Community </ORGANIZATION> meeting, according to diplomats. `` This is a very serious matter,'' said one diplomat after an announcement that the <ORGANIZATION> Turkey-EEC </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> meeting was called off. An <ORGANIZATION> EEC </ORGANIZATION> official, who like the diplomats spoke on condition of anonymity, said the <LOCATION> Turkish </LOCATION> delegation refused to take part in the meeting as a protest of the agenda's mentioning the Turkish occupation of <LOCATION> Cyprus </LOCATION>. He said the <LOCATION> Turkish </LOCATION> delegation agreed to discuss political cooperation with the Community over dinner, but would not attend the talks themselves. Foreign Minister <PERSON> Hans-Dietrich </PERSON> <PERSON> Genscher </PERSON> of <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION> failed to resolve the problem after more than three hours of closed-door negotiations and postponed the meeting indefinitely. <PERSON> Genscher </PERSON> spokesman <PERSON> Hans-Jurgen </PERSON> <PERSON> Chroborg </PERSON> said <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>, which holds the rotating EEC presidency until the end of June, hopes to reschedule the meeting before its term expires. Foreign Minister <PERSON> Mesut </PERSON> <PERSON> Yilmaz </PERSON>, the <LOCATION> Turkish </LOCATION> delegation chief, was angered over <LOCATION> Greece </LOCATION>'s insistence on including the Turkish occupation of northern <LOCATION> Cyprus </LOCATION> in the <ORGANIZATION> EEC </ORGANIZATION> statement adopted by the Community's foreign ministers earlier Monday. The statement said <LOCATION> Ankara </LOCATION>'s occupation of the east <LOCATION> Mediterranean </LOCATION> island has a `` bearing'' on the Community's relations with <LOCATION> Turkey </LOCATION>. The Community went into the meeting with a broad declaration `` taking note'' of <LOCATION> Turkey </LOCATION>'s desire to improve relations with the 12-nation Common Market. <LOCATION> Turkey </LOCATION> wanted the talks to help release a long-frozen EEC development credit of $ 748 million. It also wanted a discussion of the free movement of Turkish workers in the Community and the removal of restrictions on Turkish imports. <ORGANIZATION> EEC </ORGANIZATION> financial aid to <LOCATION> Turkey </LOCATION> was frozen since the military coup in <LOCATION> Turkey </LOCATION> in 1980. Despite a recent thaw in its relations with <LOCATION> Turkey </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Greece </LOCATION> said last week it would block the funding until Turkish troops were withdrawn from <LOCATION> Cyprus </LOCATION>. It also said it wants improved treatment of the Greek minority in <LOCATION> Turkey </LOCATION>. Turkish military forces invaded northern <LOCATION> Cyprus </LOCATION> in July 1974 and a Turkish federated state of <LOCATION> Cyprus </LOCATION> was set up after <LOCATION> Ankara </LOCATION> said the Turkish Cypriot minority there was threatened following a military coup in <LOCATION> Greece </LOCATION>. Greek Cypriots outnumber Turkish Cypriots on the island by more than four to one.
