<HEAD>Missing Baby Found; Woman Charged With Kidnapping</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAN GEHORSAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PHILADELPHIA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A 4-month-old baby taken from a hospital was found safe Monday, and a woman authorities said had impersonated a relative to gain access to the child was charged with kidnapping. LaShae Cherry, taken Saturday from <LOCATION> Children </LOCATION><LOCATION> 's </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hospital </LOCATION> <LOCATION> of </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Philadelphia </LOCATION>, was found at a house in north <LOCATION> Philadelphia </LOCATION> after several tipsters called the <ORGANIZATION> FBI </ORGANIZATION>. `` It's just like a miracle to me,'' the baby's mother, 18-year-old <PERSON> Faye </PERSON> <PERSON> Cherry </PERSON>, said at a news conference at the hospital. `` She started smiling and everything.'' <PERSON> Cherylle </PERSON> <PERSON> Staley </PERSON>, 21, was charged with kidnapping, criminal trespass, unlawful restraint, interference with custody of a child and recklessly endangering another person, police Capt. <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Deeds </PERSON> said. She was expected to be arraigned later Monday night or early Tuesday, Deeds said. A man who was at the home when the baby was found was not charged, police said. Authorities said Ms. <PERSON> Staley </PERSON> carried the baby out the hospital Saturday after she impersonated an aunt. The baby, dressed in new clothes, was recovered without incident. <ORGANIZATION> FBI </ORGANIZATION> assistant special agent <PERSON> Dick </PERSON> <PERSON> Ross </PERSON> said his office received several calls about a woman claiming to have had a baby, `` and this was found to be rather unbelievable -LRB- to callers -RRB- and this was reported to us.'' <PERSON> Ross </PERSON>, asked about a motive, said `` there was some feeling of having to produce a child.'' A doctor at the hospital said the baby was returned wearing clean clothes and apparently had been bathed recently. `` She received good care over the last 50 hours,'' said Dr. <PERSON> Leonard </PERSON> <PERSON> Friedland </PERSON>, pediatrician on duty in the hospital's emergency room when <PERSON> LaShae </PERSON> was brought in. LaShae sat quietly during the press conference, gurgling and sucking on her fist. `` As soon as she saw me she just laughed,'' Ms. <PERSON> Cherry </PERSON> said. She said she had become convinced Sunday night her baby had been sold by the woman who took her. LaShae had been at the hospital since April 18 for treatment of pneumonia and diarrhea, according to hospital officials. She was scheduled to be released Saturday.
