<HEAD>Super ``Aida'' For 15,000</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GRAHAM HEATHCOTE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 There wo n't be any elephants but there will be a cast of 600 performing for an arena seating 15,000 people in this summer's `` Aida'' extravaganza at Earl's Hall. It is the largest opera setting ever in <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>. The cavernous hall, also used for ice shows and pop concerts, covers 12 acres and was the largest reinforced concrete building in <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> when it was built in 1937. Its seating capacity is six times greater than the <ORGANIZATION> Royal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Opera </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> in Covent Garden, and ticket prices at $ 40 and $ 47.50 are about half the price of good seats at the opera house. Public fascination with <PERSON> Giuseppe </PERSON> <PERSON> Verdi </PERSON>'s opera, first performed in <LOCATION> Cairo </LOCATION> in 1871, abounds. `` The tickets are going so well that we have extended the run from six nights to seven,'' said <PERSON> Lilian </PERSON> <PERSON> Hochhauser </PERSON>, who with her husband, <PERSON> Victor </PERSON>, heads one of three groups of impresarios who got together to stage `` Aida'' at <PERSON> Earl </PERSON>'s Court near <LOCATION> Kensington </LOCATION> in west <LOCATION> London </LOCATION>. The triumphal procession in `` Aida'' has included elephants in some productions but animals were turned down for <PERSON> Earl </PERSON>'s Court. `` Elephants in <LOCATION> Egypt </LOCATION> are totally, historically inaccurate, and camels were not originally known there either,'' Mrs. <PERSON> Hochhauser </PERSON> said. `` Everybody wants animals but I think perhaps it's better not to start.'' Asked about a newspaper report that the impresarios expect a $ 2 million profit, she said, `` Nothing like that, and you can say I laughed hysterically.'' She also declined to say how much the production would cost. `` We do n't know what to expect because production costs have risen so enormously. This is unknown territory. There's never been an opera at <PERSON> Earl </PERSON>'s Court before and never one in <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION> on this scale,'' she said. `` I think there are thousands of people who are intrigued by opera and would like to hear one. But they are put off by the price and the lower-cost seats always sell out quickly. `` They feel an opera house is not their world, but they would feel more at home in a place like <PERSON> Earl </PERSON>'s Court,'' she said. Mrs. <PERSON> Hochhauser </PERSON> said the Royal Opera and its rival, the English National Opera, toyed over the years with the idea of going to <PERSON> Earl </PERSON>'s Court. `` But they never came up with a solution to the set problem _ they did n't have one to fit,'' she said. American mezzo-soprano <PERSON> Grace </PERSON> <PERSON> Bumbry </PERSON> will portray Aida on opening night and give one extra performance, while other international stars will rotate in the leading roles. The production is the idea of Italian director and designer <PERSON> Vittorio </PERSON> <PERSON> Rossi </PERSON>, who has put on similar shows in indoor stadiums in <LOCATION> Paris </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Zurich </LOCATION>. `` Aida,'' the grandest of grand operas, tells of the love of Radames, captain of the Pharaoh's guard, for Aida, a slave and daughter of the king of <LOCATION> Ethiopia </LOCATION> whom <PERSON> Radames </PERSON> has captured. Radames, tricked into betraying military secrets, is buried alive and <PERSON> Aida </PERSON> chooses to die with him. The tricky task of projecting the singer's voices to all parts of the hall is being solved by having the singers wear tiny radio microphones. The producers say the distances are so great that the mikes are unlikely to be visible. The <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> Symphony Orchestra will perform with 85 musicians conducted by <PERSON> Nello </PERSON> <PERSON> Santi </PERSON>. The <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Ballet </LOCATION> is also taking part as well as the Ambrosian Opera Chorus of 200. The production opens on Sunday June 26 and runs through Saturday July 2.
</TEXT>
