<FIRST>a i PM-LifeAbroad-Thailand Adv29   04-25 0831</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Life Abroad-Thailand, Adv 29,0854</SECOND>
<NOTE>$adv29</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Fri PMs April 29 or Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>LIFE ABROAD: Thailand _ Where White Elephants are National
Treasures</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDITOR'S NOTE </NOTE>
<TEXT>
 This is one of a series of periodic reports by <ORGANIZATION> Associated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION> correspondents on the way of life in other countries.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By DENIS D. GRAY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BANGKOK, Thailand (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A white elephant in <LOCATION> Thailand </LOCATION> is not anything you blithely unload. White elephants here are revered and pampered as national treasures. <LOCATION> Thailand </LOCATION> today is the home of the white elephant believed to have given rise years ago to the term `` white elephant'' of the other kind. But Thais do n't demean the beasts by calling them white elephants. They call them `` Auspiciously Significant Elephants.'' They are modern <LOCATION> Thailand </LOCATION>'s link to the days when kings rode elephants into battle and fought over the white ones. White elephants today reside in finely appointed stables, are assigned two caretakers each and daily consume up to 660 pounds of specially purchased greenery, garnished with papayas, bananas and other elephant delicacies. White elephants are by law offered to the king and the current monarch, <PERSON> Bhumibol </PERSON> <PERSON> Adulyadej </PERSON>, has 11 of them. They make themselves very much at home around his palace, strolling on manicured lawns, bathing in a lake and liberally stripping the royal foliage. White elephants, which are said to bestow good fortune on their owners, do n't come without expense. The herd does n't earn its keep, which includes of food bill equivalent to several thousand dollars a month. Hence the term `` white elephant'' as used elsewhere to mean a possession maintained at very high expense with very little in return. While the term in that sense is n't used in the Thai language, the English one may have originated from the practice of old Thai monarchs giving white elephants to nobles. Such gifts could hardly be refused and the creatures proceeded to eat their masters out of house and home. In former times _ the earliest records of their capture date to the 15th century _ white elephants bathed behind a screen to protect them from commoners' eyes. Kings of <LOCATION> Thailand </LOCATION> -LRB- <LOCATION> Siam </LOCATION> in those days -RRB- and <LOCATION> Burma </LOCATION> went to war over them. Beliefs, some still extant, grew up around them. Ailing children, it is said, can be cured by walking or crawling under their bellies. The hair from the tails of white elephants, incorporated into rings, can ward off evil. The fortunes of all elephants have since declined in <LOCATION> Thailand </LOCATION>. Massive deforestation has dramatically depleted the wild population to probably fewer than 2,000. Modern machines and roads have reduced elephants' usefulness in the logging industry and as beasts of burden. Domesticated elephants, which numbered nearly 13,500 in 1950, are down to fewer than 4,000 today. Roundups in the jungles, royal processions of caparisoned animals, the thundering charges of elephants in battle have been replaced by spectacles that some traditionalists regard as less than dignified. Today, elephants play soccer, take part in mock combat and lift their trunks on command in hotel reception areas for the amusement of tourists. Only a few outsiders are allowed into the stables of the white elephants at <LOCATION> Chitralada </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Villa </LOCATION>, where the animals, ranging in age from 10 to 59 years, are protected from undue stress, disease and any would-be human predators. Killing a white elephant is punishable by five years in prison. <PERSON> Phiphatanachatr </PERSON> <PERSON> Diskul </PERSON>, a veterinarian assigned to the white elephants' medical care, said the elephants get a blood test every six months and are given medicines and vitamins as needed. Initially, the keepers tried to sneak pills into bananas, sticky rice and other food but since the animals gingerly discarded them, a 4 -LCB- - inch syringe now is used To warrant such attention, an elephant must have 11 special characteristics including whitish eyes and a pinkish palette. White elephants, or albinos, are rarely if ever all white but rather mottled with off-whites and other skin tones other than the standard elephant gray. Once such an elephant is found, the word makes its way up through official channels to the Royal Household in <LOCATION> Bangkok </LOCATION>. An expert is dispatched and looks for the requisite characteristics. He also assesses the beast's personality, bearing and even whether it possesses a pleasant-sounding snore. If those tests are met, he proclaims the animal an `` Auspiciously Significant Elephant.'' At a later date the king presides over an elaborate induction ceremony, the roots of which lie deep in Hindu and <ORGANIZATION> Buddhist </ORGANIZATION> lore. <PERSON> Sawej </PERSON> <PERSON> Thanapradit </PERSON>, an 82-year-old expert who has worked with royal elephants most of his life, said the traditions and rituals surrounding white elephants once also existed in <LOCATION> Laos </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Burma </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Cambodia </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Sri </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Lanka </LOCATION>, formerly <ORGANIZATION> Ceylon </ORGANIZATION>. But political and social changes in those countries have turned royal white elephants into mere albinos. `` In <LOCATION> Thailand </LOCATION>, they will be with us a very long time,'' <PERSON> Sawej </PERSON> said, explaining that `` Auspiciously Significant Elephants'' are closely linked to the monarchy, which remains a vigorous institution.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv Fri PMs April 29</NOTE>
