<FIRST>a i PM-Panama-EkingitOut Adv02   04-25 0914</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Panama-Eking it Out, Adv 02,0943</SECOND>
<NOTE>$adv02</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Mon PMs May 2 or Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Panama Low on Supplies and Prospects for More are Dim</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHRIS ANGELO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PANAMA CITY, Panama (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 `` You can describe what is happening in the country like this,'' said the head of a major company as he drew a circle on a piece of paper. `` Have you ever seen a snake eating its tail?'' Trapped in the standoff between Gen. <PERSON> Manuel </PERSON> <PERSON> Antonio </PERSON> <PERSON> Noriega </PERSON> on one side and the local opposition and <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration on the other, Panamanians are using up what little <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION> has left, with dim prospects of getting more. `` The country is becoming paralyzed and now we are in the phase of eating up our inventories,'' said the Panamanian, who is the general manager of a major <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> company here. Like most businessmen here, he spoke only condition of anonymity because of the sensitive situation. `` There is going to be a total exhaustion of supplies on hand,'' he added. `` If we ca n't import raw materials, when the inventories run out we ca n't produce.'' Banks have been closed to the public by government order since March 4, because of cash shortages following months-long runs on accounts and a <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> freeze on Panamanian assets as part of the plan to force <PERSON> Noriega </PERSON> out as strongman. Without banks, the local economy runs on a cash-only basis. Even the most reliable customers have lost the credit they had with suppliers. Some Panamanian and foreign banks reopened April 18 but only to accept deposits. Except for some foods such as rice, an essential here, and a few manufactured goods, <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION> runs on imports. The situation became critical Feb. 26, the day <PERSON> Noriega </PERSON> engineered the ouster of President <PERSON> Eric </PERSON> <PERSON> Arturo </PERSON> <PERSON> Delvalle </PERSON> for issuing an order firing the general. <PERSON> Noriega </PERSON> had just been indicted in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> on drug trafficking charges. Hardly anyone seems to have escaped in the aftermath. _ Like everyone else, <PERSON> Harinas </PERSON> <PERSON> Panama </PERSON>, one of the country's three flour mills, ca n't buy wheat because its supplier wants cash for it General Manager <PERSON> Tirso </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Wolfschoon </PERSON> said the company is negotiating to get more wheat, but then there might not be any bags to put the flour in. He said his suppliers are having trouble getting materials for cloth and plastic bags. _ An association of insurance companies announced it ca n't pay claims and its clients ca n't pay premiums _ Construction is virtually halted Equipment stands idle at the concrete skeletons of twin 24-story condominium towers on prime real estate. _ <ORGANIZATION> Colgate </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Palmolive </ORGANIZATION>, a wholly owned branch of the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> company, is selling from its inventories of toothpaste, detergents and other personal care and cleaning products Like many others companies, it has given its employees vacations, but General Manager <PERSON> Carlos </PERSON> <PERSON> Rodriguez </PERSON> said that when worker get back from their vacations, the factory will use up its inventories. `` The main problem will be the massive unemployment this can generate,'' he said. _ For 10 years <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION> has been self-sufficient in rice, but growers say farmers are n't planting because of the lack of credit and uncertainty over whether they'll be able to get fertilizers and other chemicals Rice on hand normally would last through June or July, they say. But in the crisis, people are buying only essentials _ and rice is at the top of the list. _ Supermarkets are still well-stocked <PERSON> Nicolas </PERSON> <PERSON> Psychoyos </PERSON> of the Rey chain said sales are running at 40 percent of last year's. Some imported items, such as breakfast cereals, cooking oils and canned fruits, are running low, but local brands and all essentials are available. _ Activity in the cluster of white towers of the international banking center that grew up here in the 1970s is near a standstill According to one estimate, 50 to 70 of the 118 foreign banks have closed or are in the process of closing. Others say none have closed officially. Some Panamanian economists said they hold out hope that the center can revive, at least on some scale, but others say it is all but gone and that business is already moving to <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>'s <LOCATION> Cayman </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Islands </LOCATION> in the <LOCATION> Caribbean </LOCATION> south of <LOCATION> Cuba </LOCATION>. To survive, the Panamanian business instinct has come up with some creative answers. Some companies, like <ORGANIZATION> Colgate </ORGANIZATION>, have been paying employees with as much cash as they can muster, giving it to the lowest-scale workers. The rest receive coupons to buy food at supermarkets. Supermarkets and some other businesses are accepting the paychecks of government employees and in turn using them to pay utility bills. Supermarkets also are accepting checks of low denominations from suppliers' employees, then returning them for supplies. Some businesses are resorting to barter. Psychoyos of the Rey supermarket chain said he has exchanged food or canceled overdue accounts for windows, doors, reinforcing rods, wood, cinder block, trucks of fruit and `` just about anything that has value to it.'' `` We'll find someone who needs them and pay them with that,'' he said. A beer distributor in the provinces accepted food in payment, then used the food to pay its employees. Even if the situation is resolved soon, recovery will take years and depend on the influx of foreign aid, according to businessmen and economists. Some Panamanians now question the economic pressure the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> is using to force <PERSON> Noriega </PERSON> out and reduce the role of his <ORGANIZATION> Panama </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Forces </ORGANIZATION>. `` Right now, there's no winner in <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION>,'' said one. `` We're all losers.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv Mon PMs May 2</NOTE>
