<NOTE>For Release Thu AMs, April 28, and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Argentine Government Runs Pro-Democracy Ads to Thwart Military</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RANDALL HACKLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BUENOS AIRES, Argentina (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Concerned that some military men might still be restless in the barracks, <LOCATION> Argentina </LOCATION>'s civilian government is running television spots to promote democracy. `` Democracy comes from a Greek word meaning people's choice,'' the narrator says solemnly in one of them. The commercials follow revolts at three army camps last year and similar uprisings three months ago at six army garrisons by the cashiered rebel leader Lt. Col. <PERSON> Aldo </PERSON> <PERSON> Rico </PERSON>. The military, which has a history of intervention in government, turned government over to civilians in 1983 after ruling for seven years. President <PERSON> Raul </PERSON> <PERSON> Alfonsin </PERSON>'s <ORGANIZATION> Radical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Civic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Union </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> and the opposition <ORGANIZATION> Peronist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> have began debate on a law to amend the Constitution to strengthen civilian rule and reform the military to keep the armed forces out of politics. `` This country is tired of the continous agitations provoked by a small group that does not represent the general sentiment in the armed forces,'' said <PERSON> Antonio </PERSON> <PERSON> Cafiero </PERSON>, the governor of <LOCATION> Buenos </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Aires </LOCATION> province, chairman of the <ORGANIZATION> Peronist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>, and a leading presidential candidate. No civilian president in <LOCATION> Argentina </LOCATION> has completed a full term in 60 years. The military has toppled governments here six times since 1930, most recently when <PERSON> Isabel </PERSON> <PERSON> Peron </PERSON> was ousted in 1976 as the successor to her husband, President <PERSON> Juan </PERSON> <PERSON> D. </PERSON> <PERSON> Peron </PERSON>. <PERSON> Alfonsin </PERSON> has 20 months left in his six-year term. But recent events indicate domestic instability. Recent terrorist bombings in this capital and <LOCATION> Cordoba </LOCATION> wounded four people, including two federal policemen. One terrorist suspect was killed by police. Pro-Rico graffiti has spread from shantytowns outside <LOCATION> Buenos </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Aires </LOCATION> to downtown, near the seat of government. `` Rico is a patriot,'' `` Rico is God'' and `` Rico is freedom,'' the graffiti says. Rico is being held pending rebellion charges in the <LOCATION> Magdalena </LOCATION> military prison 62 miles south of <LOCATION> Buenos </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Aires </LOCATION>. The prison is where five former military leaders, including two military ex-presidents, also are held. The five leaders of the former military junta were convicted by the <PERSON> Alfonsin </PERSON> government for their roles in human rights abuses during <LOCATION> Argentina </LOCATION>'s `` dirty war,'' a campaign waged in the late 1970s by the military against alleged leftist subversion. At least 9,000 civilians vanished without a trace, according to a government panel, but human rights groups say the number of people abducted, tortured and ultimately `` disappeared'' is closer to 30,000. A year ago flashing TV spots saying `` Democracy or Dictatorship'' urged civilians to take to the streets to show support of the government during military uprisings April 15-21 in <LOCATION> Buenos </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Aires </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Cordoba </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Tucuman </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Alfonsin </PERSON> won the surrender of Rico at <LOCATION> Campo </LOCATION> <LOCATION> de </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Mayo </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Argentina </LOCATION>'s largest army base in suburban <LOCATION> Buenos </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Aires </LOCATION>, and told 400,000 people assembled in the central Plaza <PERSON> de </PERSON> <PERSON> Mayo </PERSON>, `` The house is in order and no blood was shed. When new rebel uprisings in January ended after 96 hours with <PERSON> Rico </PERSON>'s surrender again, <PERSON> Alfonsin </PERSON> said, `` We have again put our house in order.'' But in the past year, conditions have worsened on the economic and social fronts. <LOCATION> Argentina </LOCATION> had to renegotiate its $ 54.3 billion foreign debt, third-largest in <LOCATION> Latin </LOCATION> <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>, and inflation has run at a rate of 206 percent in the 12-month period. Workers are restive because their wages buy less and less, and <PERSON> Alfonsin </PERSON>'s party was routed in congressional and gubernatorial elections by the resurgent Peronists. Human rights groups such as the Mothers of the <LOCATION> Plaza </LOCATION> <LOCATION> de </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Mayo </LOCATION>, made up of relatives who lost loved ones in the `` dirty war,'' charged <PERSON> Alfonsin </PERSON> caved in to <PERSON> Rico </PERSON> and that he pushed a law through <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> that pardoned most officers accused of rights atrocities. Rico, meanwhile, has attracted support from rightist groups such as <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Alert </ORGANIZATION>, an organization that favors a return to military rule. Three army officers have gone underground since February, announcing they sided with <PERSON> Rico </PERSON> and planned to fight what they described as the `` Marxist enemy.'' <PERSON> Rico </PERSON> maintains the military should not be penalized for tactics he described as necessary in its 1970s war against subversion or be blamed for the embarrassing loss to <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION> in the 1982 Falklands War. While Rico has found support among younger, mid-level army officers, he is the butt of many local jokes, particularly about his surrendering after vowing to `` fight to the finish.'' Argentines say <PERSON> Rico </PERSON> has broken an unofficial record by surrendering three times in six years, first during the Falklands War, where he was a decorated commando, and twice at his own rebellions.
</TEXT>
