<HEAD>Japanese Citizens' Movements Protest Plans for U.S. Bases</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KAORI KITAI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ZUSHI, Japan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Citizens' groups in a <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION> suburb and a small Japanese island 115 miles out in the <LOCATION> Pacific </LOCATION> are protesting plans for <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> military housing and an airfield in their midst. The groups maintain the facililities will dvironments and disrupt their way of life. <LOCATION> Zushi </LOCATION>, a bedroom community 30 miles southwest of <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION>, has gone through four years of turmoil in local politics over the plan to build housing for <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> personnel on 200 acres of the <LOCATION> Ikego </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Forest </LOCATION>. estroy their en On <LOCATION> Miyake </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Island </LOCATION>, 115 miles from <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION> in the <LOCATION> Pacific </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Ocean </LOCATION>, 85 percent of the 4,300 residents have signed petitions against the construction of an airfield where <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> carrier pilots would practice night landings. In both cases the citizens' groups deny anti-American bias. They say they want only to protect their little bit of nature, a precious commodity in this crowded country, against encroachments brought about under the treaty that pledges the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> to defend <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>. `` We are only trying to check our central government going to far,'' said <PERSON> Akiko </PERSON> <PERSON> Motoyasu </PERSON> of the <ORGANIZATION> Save </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ikego </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Forest </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Group </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Zushi </LOCATION>. Professor <PERSON> Kazunari </PERSON> <PERSON> Minotani </PERSON>, a sociological researcher at <ORGANIZATION> Rissho </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION>, agrees. `` Iinment.''
