<FIRST>s a BC-APN--BlacksinCollege Adv08-2Takes   04-25 1083</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-APN--Blacks in College, Adv 08-2 Takes,1106</SECOND>
<NOTE>$adv08</NOTE>
<HEAD>AGENCIES AND RADIO OUT</HEAD>
<NOTE>For Release Sunday, May 8</NOTE>
<HEAD>From AP Newsfeatures</HEAD>
<NOTE>(APN SUNDAY ILLUSTRATIONS: Mailed print subscribers get 3 b&amp;w
photos. ColorFoto subscribers get 3 35mm slides.)</NOTE>
<TEXT>
 EDITOR'S NOTE _ Are minority students, especially blacks, getting a fair shake at college? While it's not like the old days of overt discrimination, recent incidents indicating recurring racism have prompted soul-searching at the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Wisconsin </ORGANIZATION> and other institutions. One thing is certain: The enrollment of blacks has been dropping and expressions of discontent have been rising.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By CHRISTOPHER CONNELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Education Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MADISON, Wis. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 From random insults on the street to graffiti in dorms to fistfights on fraternity row, <PERSON> black </PERSON> students say, part of their education at the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Wisconsin-Madison </ORGANIZATION> is learning how to deal with racism. <PERSON> Geneva </PERSON> <PERSON> Brown </PERSON>, 23, co-president of the <ORGANIZATION> Black </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Student </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Union </ORGANIZATION>, has received hate mail and heard herself called a `` spook'' and `` jungle bunny.'' `` This environment is hostile to blacks,'' she says. `` There is no reason for any black person to come here or stay here.'' <PERSON> Solomon </PERSON> <PERSON> Ashby </PERSON>, 21, who came to <LOCATION> Madison </LOCATION> on a football scholarship from <LOCATION> Portsmouth </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Va. </LOCATION>, says, `` It was a severe culture shock. I went from a community where everyone I saw was black to being a total minority.'' After five years, the senior says, `` I still find it very stressful. I'm in a zoology class of 500 where I am the only black student.'' There are 722 blacks among Madison's 43,368 students, or 1.66 percent. That is down from 906 seven years ago, when blacks comprised 2.3 percent of the students. It's among the smallest percentages of any major <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> university. Racial incidents have erupted into protests on other campuses, from the 1986 World Series dispute that spilled over into a racial brawl at the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Massachusetts-Amherst </ORGANIZATION> to protests at the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Michigan-Ann </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Arbor </ORGANIZATION> over racist jokes on a campus radio station to a furor over a fraternity sex show at the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Pennsylvania </ORGANIZATION>. At <ORGANIZATION> Pennsylvania </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION>, 89 activists, most of them black, were arrested in April for occupying a building in a protest over that institution's failure to achieve a court-ordered goal of 5 percent black enrollment. Some 2,424, or 3.6 percent, of <ORGANIZATION> Penn </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION>'s 67,278 students are black. <ORGANIZATION> Penn </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION>'s president, <PERSON> Bryce </PERSON> <PERSON> Jordan </PERSON>, later dropped the charges. The upsurge in racial incidents and strife, coupled with lagging black enrollments on many campuses, is prompting many colleges to mount new drives to achieve minority hiring and enrollment gains that have eluded them in the past. <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> H. </PERSON> <PERSON> Atwell </PERSON>, president of the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> on </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Education </ORGANIZATION>, says, `` We have hit the wall on minority participation and are loath to face the tough road ahead. Our own inner fatigue has been accentuated by an administration that has not seen equity issues as important.'' The council has enlisted former Presidents Carter and <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION> as co-chairman of a blue-ribbon commission that will issue a report this spring on problems that may lie ahead for the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> if more minorities do n't graduate from college. <PERSON> Kenneth </PERSON> <PERSON> Shaw </PERSON>, president of the 26-campus <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Wisconsin </ORGANIZATION> system, which has only 3,190 blacks among its 161,887 students, says, `` This is n't a Sunday school lesson we're talking about. We're approaching a situation by the year 2000 where a third of our young people going into the work force are going to be minorities. We ca n't afford for them to undereducated.'' The extent of educators' concern was evident at a recent videoconference on racism on campuses. The conference was organized by the <ORGANIZATION> Johnson </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Foundation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Governors </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> and seen by 11,000 people on 176 campuses. In panel discussions at the <ORGANIZATION> Wingspread </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Conference </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Racine </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Wis. </LOCATION>, and interviews on the <LOCATION> Madison </LOCATION> campus and elsewhere, experts agreed that today's racial problems are different from the outright legal discrimination that once kept black students from college campuses. <PERSON> Reginald </PERSON> <PERSON> Wilson </PERSON>, who directs the <ORGANIZATION> Office </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Minority </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Concerns </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> the </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> on </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Education </ORGANIZATION>, says much of the student protest arises from `` a wellspring of alienation'' fed by `` day-to-day kind of indignities'' inside and outside the classroom. He says that in student surveys 70 percent of minority students will say, ` We've got real problems,' while 70 percent of white students will say, ` This is a wonderful place.''' <PERSON> Raymond </PERSON> <PERSON> Mack </PERSON>, a <ORGANIZATION> Northwestern </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> sociologist, said, `` It is the casualness -LRB- of racism -RRB-, the fact that it is built into <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> society, that makes it such a continuing problem and so hard to deal with. It's the little flick, flick, flicks that hurt, not the one blow.'' While <PERSON> Atwell </PERSON> and others view Hispanic enrollment rates as `` abysmally low,'' it is the rate among blacks that has attracted the most attention. And it has been blacks who have been subjected to most widely noted incidents of racism on campuses. According to the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Education </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Education </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Statistics </ORGANIZATION>, <PERSON> black </PERSON> college enrollments fell almost 3 percent between 1980 and 1984, but increased slightly by 1986, the latest year for which the figures are available. The department says its survey indicated there were 1,081,000 blacks enrolled in fall 1986, down from the peak of 1,107,000 in 1980. But over the past decade the black share of enrollment has sagged from 9.4 percent to 8.6 percent. At the same time, <ORGANIZATION> Census </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bureau </ORGANIZATION> figures show, the percentage of black high school graduates ages 18 to 24 enrolled in college dropped from 33.5 percent in 1976 to 26.1 percent in 1985. Only 26.1 percent of the black high school graduates attended college, down from a peak of 33.5 percent in 1976, according to the <ORGANIZATION> Census </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bureau </ORGANIZATION>. `` The main problem of access is the kid who does n't have the stuff to go,'' says Education Secretary <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Bennett </PERSON>. Among students with similar academic achievements, `` black students are just as likely or more likely than white students to go to college.'' `` Most higher education institutions have been diligent about recruiting black students ...'' <PERSON> Bennett </PERSON> says. `` The most serious underlying barrier to greater <PERSON> black </PERSON> college enrollment is the need to enlarge the pool of black students who have had the right preparation.'' Black men, in particular, are passing up college. They were outnumbered by <PERSON> black </PERSON> <PERSON> female </PERSON> college students, 645,000 to 436,000, in 1986, the <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Education </ORGANIZATION> says. In 1985, 34,455 black women received bachelor's degrees, 3 percent more than in 1976. But the number of black male graduates, 23,018, was down 10 percent for that same period.
</TEXT>
