<HEAD>AGENCIES AND RADIO OUT</HEAD>
<NOTE>For Release Sunday, May 8</NOTE>
<HEAD>MADISON, Wis.: same period.</HEAD>
<TEXT>
 Overall black enrollment in the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Wisconsin </ORGANIZATION> system has slid 15 percent since 1980. Other states are wrestling with similar figures. In <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Jersey </LOCATION>'s nine state colleges and universities, black undergraduate enrollment dropped from 18,366 in 1980 to 14,237 in 1985. In <LOCATION> Rhode </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Island </LOCATION>, 1,975 blacks were enrolled in colleges and universities in 1986, down from 2,213 in 1980. <PERSON> Shaw </PERSON>, the president of the <LOCATION> Wisconsin </LOCATION> system, kicked up a storm last November by proposing free tuition for all minorities who maintained a C-plus average in core academic subjects in high school. The idea drew fire from many sides, including minority leaders at the <LOCATION> Madison </LOCATION> campus who feared it would arouse new enmity against blacks and other minority students. Some said C-plus students did n't deserve scholarships. In a revised `` Design for Diversity,'' <PERSON> Shaw </PERSON> has proposed doubling minority enrollments by 1993 in part with $ 1,700-a-year grants available to 500 disadvantaged <LOCATION> Wisconsin </LOCATION> residents _ not just minorities. <PERSON> Shaw </PERSON> also wants to raise minority faculty and staff hiring by 75 percent, and to groom 15 new minority Ph.D. s each year for teaching jobs in the system The total price tag over four years is nearly $ 17 million. <ORGANIZATION> Shaw </ORGANIZATION> builds on the so-called Madison Plan that new <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Wisconsin </ORGANIZATION> Chancellor <PERSON> Donna </PERSON> <PERSON> E. </PERSON> <PERSON> Shalala </PERSON> unveiled in February, six weeks after arriving in <LOCATION> Madison </LOCATION> and finding on her desk a thick pile of recommendations from a student-faculty Steering Committee on Minority Affairs. <PERSON> Shalala </PERSON>, a one-time <PERSON> Carter </PERSON> administration housing official, came to <LOCATION> Wisconsin </LOCATION> by way of the presidency of <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Hunter </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> College </ORGANIZATION>, where 60 percent of the 19,000 students are minorities. Her blueprint, fashioned after a frenetic round of meetings with faculty, student, staff and community leaders, calls for doubling freshman minority enrollment by 1993, hiring 70 new minority faculty over the next three years and 125 minority staff members. At <ORGANIZATION> Duke </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Durham </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.C. </LOCATION>, the <ORGANIZATION> Faculty </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Advisory </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION> reversed itself last month following faculty and student protests and required each of the institution's more than 50 departments to hire one more black faculty member by 1993. <ORGANIZATION> The </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Wisconsin </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> faculty </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> senate </ORGANIZATION> is being asked to approve an ethnic studies course requirement, and <PERSON> Shalala </PERSON>'s administration endorsed construction of a multicultural center for students _ although not one left solely in the hands of minority students, as activists had called for <PERSON> Shalala </PERSON> found $ 1.6 million in existing funds to launch the plan, and is asking the state legislature for $ 4.7 million more for its first three years. Some of the money will go into financial aid for the disadvantaged. Big debts have become a routine part of college life for many students in the past decade with the federal government shifting its emphasis from grants to loans. Many educators suspect that is a prime reason why the black share of college enrollment has dropped. They say the military is also recruiting a growing share of black high school graduates with its promise of both training and a paycheck. <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Wright </PERSON>, 23, minority affairs director for the <ORGANIZATION> Wisconsin </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Student </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION>, says, `` A lot of people just do n't feel like going out and taking out $ 20,000 in loans. That's what I've had to do.'' `` Then there's the Army: ` Be all you can be.' It's tempting,'' says <PERSON> Wright </PERSON>, a senior from <ORGANIZATION> Milwaukee </ORGANIZATION> who is one of 11 children. `` I know people who have college degrees who ca n't buy a job, and I know people who got jobs out of high school and are making money I dream of.'' Fellow senior <PERSON> Solomon </PERSON> <PERSON> Ashby </PERSON> says, `` A lot of people see this high level of education as superfluous. They'd much rather get into the job force right after high school. A lot of the trade skills are making much more money than people with a bachelor of arts degree.'' <PERSON> Ashby </PERSON> has worked summers in the shipyards back in <LOCATION> Portsmouth </LOCATION> as an $ 8-an-hour painter, and has seen buddies who chose not to return to college. `` The future may be somewhat limited,'' he says, but the jobs pay more than beginning teachers make. <PERSON> Charles </PERSON> <PERSON> Holley </PERSON>, 23, from <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION>, also a senior political science major and co-president of the <ORGANIZATION> Black </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Student </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Union </ORGANIZATION>, says, `` I do n't think Madison has a good image in terms of black students. Everybody who has friends who go to <LOCATION> Madison </LOCATION> knows there is nothing for you to do if you're black up here. There's no black music ... The social life is essentially null and void.'' <PERSON> Shalala </PERSON> says, `` What I want to do is make this place more like the real world, more multi-ethnic, more multicultural. There is a new generation of leaders, not only in higher education, but in this society. We have come up through the civil rights movement, through the peace movement and through the women's movement ... Twenty years ago, I was one of those demonstraters and I promised myself if I ever got into a position of power, I would be different in the way in which I led an institution. The 47-year-old <PERSON> Shalala </PERSON> says <PERSON> Madison </PERSON> will build its minority enrollment numbers `` the hard way,'' including finding transfer students and older students, and recruiting heavily in <LOCATION> Milwaukee </LOCATION> _ something it has not been doing. <LOCATION> Wisconsin </LOCATION>'s population is 3.8 percent black. `` I have to be real careful,'' <PERSON> Shalala </PERSON> says. `` I ca n't be so hungry for minorities that we bring in kids that really ca n't make it here ... We're not in the remedial business.'' She notes that on the same day the conference on campus racism was held at <LOCATION> Wingspread </LOCATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> was overriding President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>'s veto of the Civil Rights Restoration Act, which bars discrimination in federally subsidized institutitons `` That is very important for universities,'' she says. `` It holds us accountable for every department and every program.'' The success or failure of higher education's current drive to improve the racial climate and minority participation on campuses will also be affected by `` who's elected president -LRB- and -RRB- what tone is set,'' <PERSON> Shalala </PERSON> says. `` We're not going to make deep inroads until we change the way in which we run urban schools in this country.''
