<HEAD>Foreigners, Especially Turks, Bring Changes to West Germany</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By NESHA STARCEVIC</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>FRANKFURT, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 `` <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION> is n't a land of immigration,'' government officials like to say. But a massive influx of Turks and other foreigners has changed the face of this once insular nation. From dozens of kebab stands in big cities to young Turkish children playing in rural towns, the foreigners are making their presence felt. Nearly 1.5 million Turks live in <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>, the largest group among the 4.5 million foreigners in a country with a total population of 61.3 million. <LOCATION> Frankfurt </LOCATION> has a Turkish bazaar. Yugoslavs number about 590,000 and Italians are the third-largest with about 535,000. One of the Turks is <PERSON> Nedzhati </PERSON> <PERSON> Baris </PERSON>, who has acquired a small but successful business and an expensive home in the affluent town of <LOCATION> Koenigstein </LOCATION>, outside <LOCATION> Frankfurt </LOCATION>. `` My position here now is quite good,'' he said in German at his store. `` We are well known, since we've been here a long time. `` The only worry is bringing my mother for a visit from <LOCATION> Turkey </LOCATION>. We've been waiting eight months for a visa.'' The immigrant workers began arriving in the 1960s and 1970s and were called <PERSON> Gastarbeiter </PERSON>, German for guest workers, to signify what was to have been a temporary stay. Now, most of the Turks are still work on assembly lines or at menial jobs shunned by West Germans. Journalist <PERSON> Guenther </PERSON> <PERSON> Wallraff </PERSON>'s 1985 book on the exploitation of Turkish workers, `` Ganz Unten'' -LRB- Rock Bottom -RRB-, became a best-seller and stirred controversy and soul-searching among West Germans. Federal and state authorities are trying to reduce the number of foreigners in the country and make it more difficult for them to bring in family members. But opposition groups say <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>'s economy, one of the world's strongest, will need even more foreign workers in the future as the German birth rate continues to drop. Although most Turks hold low-paid jobs, some of them are successful businessmen. Turkish-owned travel agencies specializing in trips to their homeland are mushrooming across the country, cashing in on the West Germans' growing interest in <LOCATION> Turkey </LOCATION>. Turks, nevertheless, have been physically attacked by West German extremist groups, and they face other problems. `` According to all our studies, the Turks by far have the most difficult time integrating into the German society,'' said <PERSON> Hartmut </PERSON> <PERSON> Reichow </PERSON>, an expert in the federal office for foreigners in <LOCATION> Bonn </LOCATION>. `` This has to do with their background: They have a different religion -LRB- Islam -RRB- and come from a totally different culture,'' <PERSON> Reichow </PERSON> said in an interview. `` But the situation is much better now than it was in the late 1960s. Then, very few Turkish children went to school. Now, more and more and are getting even higher education and their prospects look much brighter.'' Two high schools in <LOCATION> Gelsenkirchen </LOCATION>, a <LOCATION> Ruhr </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Valley </LOCATION> industrial city, recently became the first in <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION> to offer the Turkish language as one of the subjects for the `` abitur,'' the examination that gives successful candidates a diploma roughly equal to a junior college degree in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. The schools, whose student bodies are about a quarter Turkish or Turkish-born, were the first to apply a long-existing law allowing a foreign language to be one of the subjects in the final exam. Turks are also making their mark on cultural life. The Turkish-born director <PERSON> Tevfik </PERSON> <PERSON> Baser </PERSON> scored a hit two years ago with his movie `` 40 Square Meters <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>,'' a moving story about a the wife of a Turkish worker forced by her husband never to leave their tiny apartment in <LOCATION> Hamburg </LOCATION>. The leading role was played by <PERSON> Ozay </PERSON> <PERSON> Fecht </PERSON>, who came to <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION> from <LOCATION> Istanbul </LOCATION> when she was 18 and became a critically acclaimed actress and jazz singer. Another Turk, <PERSON> Saliha </PERSON> <PERSON> Scheinhardt </PERSON>, who married a West German, advanced from a textile factory worker, waitress and air hostess to prize-winning author, writing mostly in German. But it is the service sector where Turks and other foreigners are beginning to play dominant roles. They run neighborhood ethnic restaurants and groceries, as well as tailor and shoe-repair shops. `` <LOCATION> Istanbul </LOCATION> Kebab,'' `` Balkan Grill,'' and `` Italian Pizza'' are found not only in large cities but also in many villages across <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>.
</TEXT>
