<NOTE>For Release Sunday, May 1, and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>FRANKFURT: across West Germany.</HEAD>
<TEXT>
 In <LOCATION> Koenigstein </LOCATION>, a half-hour's drive northwest of <LOCATION> Frankfurt </LOCATION>, grocer <PERSON> Baris </PERSON> explained that 15 years ago he traded his ice cream parlor at <LOCATION> Adana </LOCATION> in the southern <LOCATION> Turkey </LOCATION> for an uncertain future in <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>, The 38-year-old immigrant started out as a waiter, then became a factory worker and now owns the grocery store that doubles as a tailoring and alterations service in <LOCATION> Koenigstein </LOCATION>. Like most Turks, <PERSON> Baris </PERSON> has no immediate plans to return home. `` If the economic situation in <LOCATION> Turkey </LOCATION> improves, then maybe some day,'' he said. <PERSON> Baris </PERSON>' grocery store sells ornamented samovars and Turkish coffee pots, water pipes, dried eggplant, Bulgarian goat cheese, Greek olives, <LOCATION> Yugoslav </LOCATION> coffee, dozens of Turkish spices and mineral water, and even casette tapes of Turkish music. <PERSON> Baris </PERSON> said 90 percent of his customers in Koenigstein are West Germans. He opened his business five years ago and took a 250,000-mark -LRB- $ 148,000 -RRB- loan to buy a house. <PERSON> Baris </PERSON>, his wife and two Turks work in the store. All of <PERSON> Baris </PERSON>' four daughters were born in <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>. Two of them, aged 12 and 10, go to a German school. The two younger ones, 6 and 4 years old, go to a Roman Catholic-run kindergarten. In <LOCATION> Frankfurt </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Melek </PERSON> <PERSON> Kapicioglu </PERSON> followed a similar pattern. She came to <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION> 22 years ago, as a 19-year-old girl. After working on assembly lines for the electronics giant <ORGANIZATION> Siemens </ORGANIZATION>, she opened a tailor shop in downtown <LOCATION> Frankfurt </LOCATION> five years ago. `` I have been here long and I do n't really see how I can go back to <LOCATION> Istanbul </LOCATION> and work in my profession,'' she said. `` In <LOCATION> Turkey </LOCATION>, every woman knows how to sew.'' Both her grown-up children are back in <LOCATION> Turkey </LOCATION>. Ms. <PERSON> Kapicioglu </PERSON>, also speaking in German, said she would like <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION> to revise its law and extend business hours for stores. `` I work from 8 a.m. to 10 p.m. I can not serve customers legally after 6.30 p.m., but I have to work long. My store rent is 2,000 marks -LRB- $ 1,200 -RRB-.'' <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION> abounds with examples of Turkish and other foreign influences: _ In <LOCATION> Frankfurt </LOCATION>, kebab shops outnumber traditional sausage stands around the main train station _ <LOCATION> Newsstands </LOCATION> sell Turkish, <LOCATION> Yugoslav </LOCATION>, Italian, and Spanish papers Hurriyet, a Turkish daily, is printed in a <LOCATION> Frankfurt </LOCATION> suburb in 120,000 copies daily and distributed across the country. _ When floods hit many parts of <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION> recently, police vans cruised the streets, broadcasting warnings in both German and Turkish _ <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Berlin </LOCATION>'s <LOCATION> Kreuzberg </LOCATION> district, with a large <LOCATION> Turkish </LOCATION> population, has signs in German and Turkish to warn residents when they approach the <LOCATION> Berlin </LOCATION> Wall that they are leaving the American sector _ A cable television service in <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Berlin </LOCATION> offers Turkish programs <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>'s national television network has regular weekly news and cultural programs in Turkish, Italian, Serbo-Croat for the Yugoslavs, Spanish and Portuguese. _ The Turkish bazaar in downtown <LOCATION> Frankfurt </LOCATION> features coffee shops where patrons smoke water pipes, several restaurants, small stores and a mosque on the second floor <LOCATION> Frankfurt </LOCATION>'s Turks hope to build a large mosque with donations from believers.
</TEXT>
