<HEAD>Mexican Beer's U.S. Success Reflects Sound Planning At Home</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds, a companion story is BC-Mexican Beer-Carta, b0559</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES ANDERSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MEXICO CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Some beer fanciers have brushed off as a passing fancy the popularity of Corona Extra, the biggest-selling Mexican beer in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. Market experts questioned whether the light lager could compete in an import market traditionally dominated by darker and heavier European brews. Not so <PERSON> Valentin </PERSON> <PERSON> Diez </PERSON> <PERSON> of </PERSON> <PERSON> Cervecerias </PERSON> <PERSON> Modelo </PERSON>, the makers of <PERSON> Corona </PERSON>. Under his guidance as <PERSON> Modelo </PERSON>'s general sales director, <PERSON> Corona </PERSON> has vaulted into second place among imported beers in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, and the company is aiming to be No. 1. In the process, <PERSON> Grupo </PERSON> <PERSON> Modelo </PERSON>, the brewery's parent company, is exemplifying President <PERSON> Miguel </PERSON> de la <LOCATION> Madrid </LOCATION>'s controversial effort to wean Mexican industry off years of subsidies and trade protection to create an export-driven economy that can successfully compete abroad. `` We want to be a model for all Mexican businesses by giving prestige and credibility to Mexican products abroad,'' <PERSON> Diez </PERSON> said at his <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION> headquarters. A growing number of American beer drinkers are convinced. Americans consumed 25 million cases of Corona Extra last year, more than double the 1986 figure and 10 times above that just six years ago. <PERSON> Corona </PERSON> captured 18 percent of the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> import market in 1987, second only to <ORGANIZATION> Heineken </ORGANIZATION> of the <LOCATION> Netherlands </LOCATION> with 25 percent, according to <ORGANIZATION> Impact </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION>, a New York-based publication that monitors the beer industry. And with <PERSON> Corona </PERSON> now available in only 36 states, <PERSON> Grupo </PERSON> <PERSON> Modelo </PERSON> directors have reason to believe they'll achieve their goal. <PERSON> Diez </PERSON> cited strict quality control, strong advertising and sound marketing as reasons for <PERSON> Corona </PERSON>'s export success. But it has been sound financial planning at home that has steered Modelo through <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION>'s economic crisis. Tight credit, rising costs, slack consumer demand and crushing private debts have hurt many Mexican businesses, including <PERSON> Modelo </PERSON>'s chief competitor, <PERSON> Cuauhtemoc </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Monterrey </LOCATION> Modelo avoided these pitfalls by refusing to borrow to finance investment, when borrowing from foreign lenders was the rage in the late 1970s and early 1980s. The company continuously plowed its earnings back into the firm. `` Grupo Modelo's policy always has been to grow using its own resources. That means no debts,'' <PERSON> Diez </PERSON> said. `` We did it by reinvesting all of our dividends over the years to construct our own breweries, malt and glass producing firms, our own warehouses and distributors. `` Many at the time thought we were wrong. But this policy has allowed us to consolidate our leadership position in the Mexican beer industry.'' Modelo brands now account for nearly half the Mexican market and 60 percent of all Mexican beer exports, <PERSON> Diez </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Corona </PERSON> has been available in western <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> states since 1966. But sales growth was limited because a Puerto Rican brewery owned the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> rights to the familiar Corona blue-and-white crown trademark. <PERSON> Cervecerias </PERSON> <PERSON> Modelo </PERSON> was able to arrange a concurrent use agreement in 1983 and bought the trademark two years later. `` With the trademark question out of the way, this allowed us to launch ourselves into the market,'' <PERSON> Diez </PERSON> said. Not quite. Modelo's governing board insisted on introducing the lager into the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> market on a gradual basis rather than trying to flood it all at once. <PERSON> Corona </PERSON> showed up first in restaurants and bars before it appeared in liquor stores and supermarkets. The beer became identified with trendy establishments and ethnic cuisine. `` They do n't want to just open a market,'' said <PERSON> Roberto </PERSON> <PERSON> Viejo </PERSON>, a sales director at <LOCATION> Modelo </LOCATION>. `` They work it, service it. It is n't just, ` Hey, here's a new brand. No way.'' <PERSON> Corona </PERSON>'s popularity has benefited from a slick advertising campaign, with its `` Cross the Border'' message linking the lager to Mexican tourist attractions in magazines and on billboards. In <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Modelo </PERSON> has pushed its premium beer at sporting events. The beer's logo is found everywhere inside <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION>'s Social Security Park, home to the city's <ORGANIZATION> Red </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Devils </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Tigers </ORGANIZATION> professional baseball teams, and at boxing arenas The sports angle is being developed in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> as well. A promotional stint during the week of the <ORGANIZATION> NCAA </ORGANIZATION> college basketball championships featured six Corona bottles, two of them empty, and the slogan: `` On to the Final Four.'' A <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> decision to revoke trade preferences for Mexican beer in 1987 did n't hurt <PERSON> Corona </PERSON>'s sales growth. Instead, the company judged it a sign that the brew could successfully compete on equal terms with other American imports. So has President de la <LOCATION> Madrid </LOCATION>'s administration, which cited <ORGANIZATION> Cervecerias </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Modelo </ORGANIZATION> for export achievements. And Diez's colleagues in the <ORGANIZATION> Mexican </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Sales </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Marketing </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Executives </ORGANIZATION> designated him their distinguished executive of the year in 1987. Increased competitiveness means facing the prospect of more imported beers in <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION> as well. A trade agreement signed with the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> last year will allow many American beers in <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION> for the first time. Diez is confident <PERSON> Modelo </PERSON> will rise to the challenge. `` We welcome them, having plain confidence that the quality of our beers will allow us to freely compete with the best beers in the world,'' he said. With new markets opening up in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Jersey </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Alabama </LOCATION> and the <LOCATION> Carolinas </LOCATION> this year, Diez predicts Corona sales will jump an additional 15 percent. The company hopes its other leading export brands, <PERSON> Negra </PERSON> <PERSON> Modelo </PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION> Modelo </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Especial </ORGANIZATION> and <PERSON> Pacifico </PERSON>, also will catch on with American beer drinkers. <PERSON> Corona </PERSON> is making inroads in other countries. The lager was recently introduced in <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>, and after just one year it is the third-leading import by volume in <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION>. Distributors in <LOCATION> France </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Spain </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Belgium </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Australia </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION> have expressed interest in <LOCATION> Corona </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Diez </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Viejo </PERSON>, the sales director, dismissed some experts' opinion that <PERSON> Corona </PERSON> may already be falling out of the trendy import category in the American market. `` I would n't worry about it as long as they keep talking about it,'' he said. `` Corona is not in or out. It's a mainstream brand.'' <PERSON> Corona </PERSON> did fall into the list of `` outs'' for beers in <ORGANIZATION> BusinessWeek </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Magazine </ORGANIZATION>'s trends list for 1988. The brew that took its place in the `` in'' column: <LOCATION> Negra </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Modelo </LOCATION>.
</TEXT>
