<NOTE>$Adv00</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Anytime</NOTE>
<BYLINE>AP WEEKEND ENTERTAINMENT AND ARTS</BYLINE>
<HEAD>At the Movies: ``Sunset''</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BOB THOMAS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
 No one is better qualified than <PERSON> Blake </PERSON> <PERSON> Edwards </PERSON> to create a movie about the early days of <LOCATION> Hollywood </LOCATION>: He is a third-generation filmmaker; his grandfather was a silent film director; his father was an assistant director and production manager. His daughter, <PERSON> Jennifer </PERSON>, a promising actress, makes it four generations. The latest movie from the prolific <PERSON> Edwards </PERSON> -LRB- `` Breakfast at <ORGANIZATION> Tiffany </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION>,'' `` The Great Race,'' `` 10'' -RRB- is `` Sunset,'' an affectionate, funny, exhilarating glimpse at what <LOCATION> Hollywood </LOCATION> in the 1920s might have been _ `` give or take one or two lies,'' as one of the characters explains. Based on a book by <PERSON> Rod </PERSON> <PERSON> Amateau </PERSON>, <PERSON> Edwards </PERSON>' script contains a delicious idea: the teaming of <PERSON> Wyatt </PERSON> <PERSON> Earp </PERSON> and <PERSON> Tom </PERSON> <PERSON> Mix </PERSON> to solve a <LOCATION> Hollywood </LOCATION> murder case. The juxtaposition of an authentic Western hero and a gaudy star of horse operas makes a splendid metaphor. And <PERSON> Edwards </PERSON> adds another element from movie lore: the bootlegging Mafia. The plotting of `` Sunset'' becomes a bit convoluted for easy comprehension, and the heroics grow far-fetched. But the movie rolls along with <PERSON> Edwards </PERSON>' faultless pacing, and most of all, by the inspired casting of <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Garner </PERSON> and <PERSON> Bruce </PERSON> <PERSON> Willis </PERSON>. They are the slickest screen pairing since <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> Newman </PERSON> and <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Redford </PERSON>. The two mythic heroes are brought together when <PERSON> Earp </PERSON> comes to <LOCATION> Hollywood </LOCATION> as technical adviser for a movie in which he will be portrayed by Mix. After an early antagonism, the pa