 Say it is n't so. But it is. Home videos for babies. We're talking infants here, not children. Well, why not. After all, there are books for babies _ those soft, washable squishy things with big, bright drawings of animals and toys and virtually no words _ so why not videos? V.I.E.W. Video, an acronym for <ORGANIZATION> Video </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Entertainment </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> World </ORGANIZATION>, is releasing `` <LOCATION> Infantasia </LOCATION> _ A Musical Mobile for You and Baby'' just in time for Mother's Day. The 25-minute videocassette in VHS sells for $ 19.95 and features shapes, colors, animation and nursery rhymes a 5 or 6-month-old baby or older could enjoy. There's a happy blue bird chirping away with moving musical notes, and cute bunny rabbits cavorting on a sunny, verdant landscrape. There are 11 songs including `` Pop Goes the Weasel,'' `` <PERSON> Brahms </PERSON>' Lullaby'' and `` Three Blind Mice.'' `` I've tried to create a world of color, shape and song which would be both fun and learning for baby,'' said <PERSON> Dick </PERSON> <PERSON> Feldman </PERSON>, president of <ORGANIZATION> Network </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Enterprises </ORGANIZATION>, who designed `` Infantasia.'' Hi-Tops Video has a $ 14.95, 30-minute cassette for youngsters 5 and under called `` Babysongs,'' featuring such tunes as `` Do n't Wash My Blanket Today. From Pacific Arts Video for $ 19.95 is a 90-minute `` The Little Prince'' for kids 5-12. The Claymation animation is based on the St. Exupery book. Elsewhere in the home video world, <ORGANIZATION> Paramount </ORGANIZATION> will release `` 1900'' in June. The epic about the rise of fascism in <LOCATION> Italy </LOCATION> stars <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> De </PERSON> <PERSON> Niro </PERSON> and is directed by <PERSON> Bernardo </PERSON> <PERSON> Bertolucci </PERSON>, whose `` The Last Emperor'' recently won nine Academy Awards. <ORGANIZATION> Warner </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Home </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Video </ORGANIZATION> will release `` Nuts'' next month, starring Barbra Streisand and <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Dreyfuss </PERSON> in a courtroom drama. Videos reviewed this week: `` The Untouchables,'' `` Adventures in Babysitting'' and `` Hiding Out.'' `` The Untouchables'' -LRB- <ORGANIZATION> Paramount </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Home </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Video </ORGANIZATION>; VHS, $ 89.95 @ Beta, 29.95; Rated R -RRB- `` The Untouchables'' is much more than a stylish remake of the old television series, even though good guy G-men still bust <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION> ganglords during Prohibition. The <PERSON> Eliot </PERSON> <PERSON> Ness </PERSON> played by <PERSON> Kevin </PERSON> <PERSON> Costner </PERSON> is a teetotaler and loving father who compromises his killing principles as he conquers thugs who murder a 10-year-old girl with a bomb. He saves babies in runaway carriages with one hand and tosses gangsters from buildings with the other. The squeaky clean <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> <ORGANIZATION> Treasury </ORGANIZATION> agent frets when he shoots hoodlums, but he openly challenges mobsters and dutifully avenges the murder of his friends. He fights the mob with accountants and bullets, overcoming crooked cops and judges. The <PERSON> Al </PERSON> <PERSON> Capone </PERSON> played by <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> DeNiro </PERSON> appears too little in the 119-minute film, directed by <PERSON> Brian </PERSON> <PERSON> De </PERSON> <PERSON> Palma </PERSON> and written by <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Mamet </PERSON>. But the savage butchery of his criminal empire comes across. <PERSON> DeNiro </PERSON>'s <PERSON> Capone </PERSON> is a a boss who keeps his troops in line with bat-wielding brutality. He jokes with reporters, bribes the legal system and cries at the opera at the same time he's being told of a successful killing. <PERSON> Sean </PER