<HEAD>AP WEEKEND ENTERTAINMENT AND ARTS</HEAD>
<HEAD>In the Groove: Record Reviews</HEAD>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Gershwin </PERSON>: Rhapsody in <LOCATION> Blue </LOCATION>, Concerto in F _ <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Tritt </PERSON>, piano; The <LOCATION> Cincinnati </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Pops </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Orchestra </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Erich </PERSON> <PERSON> Kunzel </PERSON> conducting. The popularity of <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Gershwin </PERSON>'s `` Rhapsody in Blue'' owes a lot to the orchestration prepared by <PERSON> Ferde </PERSON> <PERSON> Grofe </PERSON> in 1942. But there was an earlier version, also <PERSON> Grofe </PERSON>'s work, for <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> Whiteman </PERSON>'s `` Experiment in Modern Music'' at the Aeolian Hall in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> in 1924 This was the version, and this was the concert, that established `` Rhapsody in Blue'' as an American standard. <PERSON> Whiteman </PERSON> commissioned <PERSON> Gershwin </PERSON> on the strength of the composer's Broadway successes, notably `` Swanee'' for <PERSON> Al </PERSON> <PERSON> Jolson </PERSON> in 1920 Setting to work just a month before the concert, <PERSON> Gershwin </PERSON> wrote a solo piano part and a second piano part which represented the orchestra. <PERSON> Grofe </PERSON> then helped in orchestrating the piece for eight violins, double bass, three woodwinds, two horns, two trombones, tuba, tympani, banjo, celeste, percussion and piano. It is this orchestration which the <LOCATION> Cincinnati </LOCATION> Pops Orchestra has recreated, using 24 players in the guise of the <ORGANIZATION> Cincinnati </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Jazz </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Orchestra </ORGANIZATION>. It's a beguiling performance. Despite the digital clarity, the small forces evoke the sound of old 78 rpm recordings and those make-believe ballrooms of the early days of radio. Delightful though it is, the recording also affirms the rightness of the more familiar 1942 version. In its final bars, `` Rhapsody'' begs for more oomph than two dozen players can muster. The Concerto in F, variations on `` I Got Rhythm'' and the `` Rialto Ripples'' rag, performed by the full pops orchestra, round out a very satisfying hour-plus compact disc. _ By <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Barr </PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION> Associated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION> Writer.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
 `` <PERSON> Pinker </PERSON> and Prouder Than Previous'' -LRB- <ORGANIZATION> Columbia </ORGANIZATION> -RRB- _ <PERSON> Nick </PERSON> <PERSON> Lowe </PERSON> <PERSON> Forgive </PERSON> <PERSON> Nick </PERSON> <PERSON> Lowe </PERSON> for feeling a little baffled about what the general public wants in its music stars. This veteran British rocker has done everything but jump through hoops in an attempt to break through during the past few years. He released two solid albums, including the exceptional `` Rose of <LOCATION> England </LOCATION>,'' after a string of inferior early 1980s records. He rerecorded one of his best songs, `` I Knew the Bride'' with <PERSON> Huey </PERSON> <PERSON> Lewis </PERSON> and the News. Still, no luck. The back cover of his new album, `` <PERSON> Pinker </PERSON> and Prouder Than Previous,'' shows <PERSON> Lowe </PERSON> standing against a brick wall, gazing wistfully at a street sign called `` Market Place.'' The relaxed tone of `` Pinker'' suggests <PERSON> Lowe </PERSON> has thrown up his hands and just decided to do what's comfortable. While the results are a few notches below his last two records, `` Pinker'' has its moments. <PERSON> Lowe </PERSON>'s a rock' n' roller, as he constantly tried to reassure fans who saw him on a solo acoustic tour last year, but he takes a few intriguing left turns at the outset of this record. `` You're My Wildest Dream'' is a roadhouse blues number backed by the Fabulous Thunderbirds, and `` Crying in My Sleep'' is a rare ballad. He cajoles two fine contributions from friends who happen to be sterling songwriters. `` Love Gets Strange'' is a <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Hiatt </PERSON> throwaway for which many songwriters would kill, and `` <ORGANIZATION> Black </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lincoln </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Continental </ORGANIZATION>,'' by <PERSON> Graham </PERSON> <PERSON> Parker </PERSON>, is a rollicking good time. Yet what's designed as this album's showcase is oddly disappointing. <PERSON> Lowe </PERSON> briefly reunites with former Rockpile partner <PERSON> Dave </PERSON> <PERSON> Edmunds </PERSON>, with whom he spent much of the 1980s feuding. But the reunion is only for one song, and instead of complementing the album, `` Lovers Jamboree'' stands uncomfortably apart. One hopes the slightly disjointed feel of this record does n't herald a return to <PERSON> Lowe </PERSON>'s early'80s sloppiness He's too much fun, even when not at his best, to lose heart over a lack of commercial success. _ By <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Bauder </PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION> Associated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION> Writer.
