<HEAD>Music Makers: A Former Doll Is Hot, Hot, Hot</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARY CAMPBELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Some rockers turn gray, still rocking. Not <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Johansen </PERSON>. The former <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> Doll got tired of rock and the road. So he put some brilliantine on his still-dark hair, worked it into a Little <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> pompadour, donned a tuxedo and became a jaded lounge lizard named <PERSON> Buster </PERSON> <PERSON> Poindexter </PERSON>. He became the toast of <LOCATION> Manhattan </LOCATION> with a slick deco act that best resembled a collaboration between P.G. <PERSON> Wodehouse </PERSON> and <PERSON> Noel </PERSON> <PERSON> Coward </PERSON>. And the songs he did were novelties and saloon tunes with witty anecdotes. He played at a club called Tramps with his five-piece Banshees of Blue, and moved to the Bottom Line with his 11-piece Banshees of Blue. Then he went national. `` Saturday Night Live'' snapped him up. He was interviewed on `` The Tonight Show Starring <PERSON> Johnny </PERSON> <PERSON> Carson </PERSON>,'' signed for `` Miami Vice'' and appeared in ads for Amaretto liqueur. His new album for RCA, `` <PERSON> Buster </PERSON> <PERSON> Poindexter </PERSON>,'' has been on best-selling charts for months. `` Hot Hot Hot,'' a tune he once heard on a <LOCATION> Caribbean </LOCATION> vacation sung by a calypso king named Arrow, was the first single. His newest single, also borrowed, is `` Oh Me Oh My,'' which was recorded in 1925 by the <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Orleans </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Owls </ORGANIZATION>. And <PERSON> Buster </PERSON> <PERSON> Poindexter </PERSON> is playing dates in much nicer rooms than <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Johansen </PERSON> ever did. `` I like places where your feet do n't stick to the floor,'' he said. `` Until I had the album, there was no going out as <PERSON> Buster </PERSON> <PERSON> Poindexter </PERSON>. People would n't come. You can have the greatest show on <LOCATION> Earth </LOCATION> but if they have n't heard of you they're not going to come out and see you.'' The 38-year-old <PERSON> Johansen </PERSON> explained the reasons for his new persona: `` I'd been doing a straight rock' n' roll show for many years and I got tired of it. I think I outgrew it. I wanted to do something a little more sophisticated and something I could entertain people of all ages with, instead of just kids. `` As solo performer <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Johansen </PERSON> -LRB- after the 1973-75 <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> Dolls heyday -RRB-, a lot of things I would say were going over the audience's heads. Now I'm in a situation where I can be funny. It is very satisfying. `` Every year you're singing rock you get older but the kids stay the same age. <PERSON> Buster </PERSON> is suitable entertainment for all ages. People who like rock like <PERSON> Buster </PERSON>.'' He chose the `` obscurities from days gone by'' for the album. `` The reason I started doing <PERSON> Buster </PERSON> <PERSON> Poindexter </PERSON> was, I wanted to sing all these songs I've cataloged in my head. ... It was n't like I seriously expected to do this. `` I did n't stop doing the other thing and start doing this. I started Monday nights at Tramps. I said I was <PERSON> Buster </PERSON> <PERSON> Poindexter </PERSON> so they would n't come expecting to see <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Johansen </PERSON>'s schtick. For six months maybe I was singing as both. It was a natural progression. Now guys on the street go, ` Yo, <PERSON> Buster </PERSON>.''' <PERSON> Johansen </PERSON> is married to portrait photographer <PERSON> Kate </PERSON> <PERSON> Simon </PERSON>. He started in show business in the campy, gay theater troupe, <PERSON> Charles </PERSON> <PERSON> Ludlum </PERSON>'s Ridiculous Theater, and moved on to become lead singer in a campy, male rock group, the <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Dolls </ORGANIZATION>, who wore high heels and makeup. `` I guess I was a precocious kid,'' he said in an interview. `` Most of the people in my family sing, dance, are always in plays. I was the least inclined in that direction. I'm the one who took it up as a profession. Now my mother comes to my shows all the time with her friends.'' His Norwegian father, who died three years ago, was a light opera singer who became an insurance salesman when he and his Irish wife had the first of their six children. `` We always went to see Broadway shows when we were kids,'' <PERSON> Johansen </PERSON> said. `` I liked them all.'' At home on <LOCATION> Staten </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Island </LOCATION>, <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Johansen </PERSON>'s street name was <PERSON> Buster </PERSON>. `` I was the one in the gang who read books,'' he says. `` They called me <PERSON> Poindexter </PERSON>. Some people have that wanderlust both physically and intellectually. I had a band in high school, the Blue Banshees. I wanted to revive that name, for whatever reason I'm not sure.'' After high school, he worked for people who owned a store. One of them was in the late <PERSON> Charles </PERSON> <PERSON> Ludlum </PERSON>'s theater company. `` I just kind of fell into it. <PERSON> Charles </PERSON> <PERSON> Ludlum </PERSON> was a brilliant man, very generous with his information. I learned a lot. It was like an apprenticeship. I was a lion in one play, a saint in one. I was an extra, really. `` Then I started up the New York Dolls. At that time rock was very blue jeans and flannel shirts. We wanted to bring a sense of flamboyance, fantasy and fun to it. The way we dressed scared the homophobes -LRB- people afraid of homosexuals -RRB-. `` We got involved with each other because we looked like that. ... I do n't think we thought what we were doing was particularly outrageous. I think it translated that way. We made two albums for Mercury, released many times _ the best of, very best of, complete works of. `` It has been said the <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> Dolls were the beginning of punk. I do n't agree. I think it was classic rock' n' roll we played. I wrote lyrics that were teen angst with a sense of humor.'' <PERSON> Johansen </PERSON> said the <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Dolls </ORGANIZATION> broke up because they got tired of each other. `` We were very volatile. We'd have an argument; that would be it. Most people would say, ` We still have this viable gig.' Not us. We were amateur, I guess. `` In retrospect, it was a project that was completed. I do n't want to go around looking like that forever I see grown men still wearing their mother's clothes. I say, ` There but for the grace, go I.''' After the breakup, <PERSON> Johansen </PERSON> and another band member made money touring <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> _ <PERSON> Johansen </PERSON> now calls them the Dollettes. Then he wrote songs and made six solo albums for Epic, continually touring the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> for eight years. `` I love to sing,'' he says. `` It's the schlep that kills me.''
