<HEAD>AP WEEKEND ENTERTAINMENT AND ARTS</HEAD>
<HEAD>Books and Authors: On Foot Through the Rain Forest</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE JAHN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Eric </PERSON> <PERSON> Hansen </PERSON> has vivid memories of the split second it took to make the decision: turn his back on civilization and return to the <LOCATION> Borneo </LOCATION> jungle he had just spent five months crossing on foot. Six years after his marathon trip, other memories continue to haunt <PERSON> Hansen </PERSON>, who relates his experiences in his new book, `` Stranger in the Forest _ On Foot Across <LOCATION> Borneo </LOCATION>'' -LRB- <ORGANIZATION> Houghton </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mifflin </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, $ 17.95 -RRB-. He recalls his brush with death with former headhunters convinced he was an evil spirit, and his fantasies about cross-country skiing while trudging through the hot, leech and insect-infested rain forest. Departing from <LOCATION> Kuching </LOCATION> in the west in May 1982, <PERSON> Hansen </PERSON> made a 2,500-mile journey through uncharted rain forest to <LOCATION> Tanjungselor </LOCATION> in the east and back, carrying only a bed sheet, a change of clothes and barter goods. He had the company of guides for much of the time, but also traveled alone. He emerged a changed man, a spear-wielding hunter and a gatherer whose Western sense of time had washed away. `` After spending five months in the jungle, I was n't fully aware of how much I had changed,'' <PERSON> Hansen </PERSON> said. `` Then I went back two more months, and I had changed even more.'' In <LOCATION> Singapore </LOCATION>, his first real exposure to civilization afterwards, `` there was all this traffic and the pollution ... and I was acutely aware of the fact that there were no trees at all. And I felt much more uncomfortable coming back into Western society than I had going into the jungle.'' Civilization lost its terrors within about two months for the author. But long-term changes remain to this day. `` I'm much more patient, much more resilient. ... It's very much developed my self-confidence,'' he said in a recent interview. The <LOCATION> Borneo </LOCATION> journey was not the first adventure for the 40-year-old <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION> native, who has traveled to <LOCATION> Nepal </LOCATION> and northern <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION>. He also has worked as a goldsmith, a buffalo catcher and as a barber for <PERSON> Mother </PERSON> <PERSON> Teresa </PERSON>'s home for the destitute in <LOCATION> Calcutta </LOCATION>. Like his other experiences, <PERSON> Hansen </PERSON> said that the decision to embark on a rain forest odyssey was compulsive. `` I think a lot of us fantasized about a place we want to go or a situation we would like to be in and most of us are quite happy to keep it on that fantasy level,'' he said. `` I thought about going to <LOCATION> Borneo </LOCATION> for five or six years and it became an overwhelming desire on my part.'' <PERSON> Hansen </PERSON>'s 278-page book is at its most fascinating when it juxtaposes civilization against the rain forest and its creatures _ the author among them. Among such vignettes is an episode describing the aftermath of a wild boar hunt with parangs _ heavy knives: `` Squatting on my haunches, I could feel the fat running down my forearms and dripping from my elbows. I was totally absorbed in the meal when I heard a vaguely familiar droning sound growing louder and louder. `` I looked up through a gap in the jungle canopy and saw, for perhaps five seconds, a commercial airliner. `` I imagined myself sitting on the plane. ... Far below, at the edge of a small clearing, almost hidden from sight, I could see myself seated by a campfire with two brown-skinned jungle men, speaking an unknown language. Nearby lay the steaming carcass of a wild boar. `` From that perspective I suddenly realized what an astonishing situation I was in: submerged in a sea of giant trees, hunting wild animals, a bloodied parang at my waist _ the stuff of pure fantasy six months earlier.'' <PERSON> Hansen </PERSON>'s encounter with American missionaries and his decision to retrace his steps is perhaps the keystone episode and clearly explains the triteness of `` civilization'' to a man grown accustomed to harsher realities. `` <PERSON> Ian </PERSON> and <PERSON> Julie </PERSON> were perched nervously on the edge of their seats staring at me, perhaps waiting for me to disappear. I looked at the Christian paintings, calendars and framed scriptural quotes that covered the walls. I had been in the jungle too long to make any sense of them. `` All these symbols seemed trite and out of place. And their puppy. That sweet-smelling freshly shampooed, little bundle of white fluff would have been torn to pieces in thirty seconds by the village hunting dogs.'' <PERSON> Hansen </PERSON> chuckled as he thought back to that time. `` They had this little bungalow beside the jungle and inside the house was a perfect time capsule,'' he said. `` Everything about it was ridiculous, from the soap to the rugs, to the cookies in a jar. I was convinced that it had been brought by helicopter and just dropped there.'' In the book, he presents the forest and its inhabitants at their most frightening on his return trip, when he ignored the locals' advice and embarks alone during `` the season of fear,'' the former time for headhunting, when evil spirits lurk <PERSON> Hansen </PERSON> was mistaken for a `` bali saleng'' _ half man, half spirit who kills for blood and who can not be killed. `` What I did not know was that the description of ` bali saleng' changed regularly,'' he writes `` At the time ... the description was ` a tall, white-skinned man with brownish hair who walks by himself in the jungle.''' His book describes several close calls with frightened natives, including one hair-raising encounter where he was stripped and cross-examined for hours, until he laboriously convinced his interrogators to let him free. <PERSON> Hansen </PERSON> said his journey left him none the worse for wear and that he is looking forward to his next project _ an extended tour of rugged <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Yemen </LOCATION>. The slightly built, balding adventurer laughed heartily when told that he did not seem physically rugged enough for such experiences. `` I think there's a myth, fed by movies and television that it's the hairy-chested, gun-slinging, whip-wielding individual that ... conquers the mountain, or the river, or the woman or whatever,'' he said `` In fact, I've never seen anyone in real life like that get very far ... because they're the first ones to get sick, or complain or freak out when something happens. `` When they ca n't scream or pay somebody off, they give up.''
