<HEAD>SPECIAL EDITION</HEAD>
<HEAD>TRAVEL: With Highway 1-Nepenthe</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By THOMAS MURPHY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BIG SUR, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 On a bluff with a sweeping view of the Big Sur coast, 808 feet above the <LOCATION> Pacific </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Ocean </LOCATION>, sits a restaurant that serves something more with its burgers than a side of fries. <ORGANIZATION> Nepenthe </ORGANIZATION> has been a popular eatery on Highway 1 since the late 1940s, not just with the 1.5 million motorists who pass by annually, but with many of the writers, artists and thinkers who have given Big Sur its unique reputation as the birthplace of the human potential movement. The restaurant, designed by <PERSON> Rowan </PERSON> <PERSON> Maiden </PERSON>, a <PERSON> Frank </PERSON> <PERSON> Lloyd </PERSON> <PERSON> Wright </PERSON> disciple, makes the most of its view with a dining room surrounded by picture windows and a wrap-around, bi-level patio. Inside and out, there are giant fireplaces to ward off the chill of the notorious coastal fog. The food, ranging from quiche and burgers to steaks and red snapper, is good and not unreasonably priced by Big Sur standards. But it's the history and people of <LOCATION> Nepenthe </LOCATION> that really makes the place special. The restaurant, named for a mythical Egyptian drug that induced forgetfulness and eased sorrow, sits beside a log cabin built by the equestrian <ORGANIZATION> Trails </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Club </ORGANIZATION> in 1925. The cabin was purchased by <LOCATION> Orson </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Welles </LOCATION> in the 1940s, reportedly as a gift for <PERSON> Rita </PERSON> <PERSON> Hayworth </PERSON>. But she never lived there and the property was sold again to <PERSON> Bill </PERSON> and <PERSON> Lolly </PERSON> <PERSON> Fassett </PERSON> in 1947. Today, <ORGANIZATION> Nepenthe </ORGANIZATION> is managed by their grandson, <PERSON> Kirk </PERSON> <PERSON> Fassett </PERSON>. Granddaughter <PERSON> Erin </PERSON> <PERSON> Fassett </PERSON> supervises the dining room and lives in the rustic cabin. Born and raised in Big Sur during the 1960s, they had a good view of social changes here, and of the changes in people who gave up the straight life somewhere else to seek an alternative lifestyle on the <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> coast. `` In Big Sur, there is really only one industry, the entertainment industry _ restaurants and inns,'' notes <PERSON> Erin </PERSON>. `` So people who wanted to live here, unless they were independently wealthy or self-employed, ended up working in restaurants. `` I know people who have Ph.D. s or were doctors and did n't want to be doctors anymore _ people who dropped out of a different life and were working here And that's still true ... These people have gone through a real rebirth in a way, a rejuvenation. They get excited about life again,'' she said. `` Every night, somebody comes through and says ` I came here 10 years ago and I was never able to forget it.' It's really kind of a haunting community. You do n't forget it very easily.''
