<HEAD>SPECIAL EDITION</HEAD>
<HEAD>TRAVEL: I-95</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhotos NY700, NY713</HEAD>
<HEAD>(EDITORS: For suggested side-by-side use with b1117, Highway 1)</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 When Gov. <PERSON> Bob </PERSON> <PERSON> Martinez </PERSON> drove a 1929 <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Model </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> AA </ORGANIZATION> truck to open the final 33-mile stretch of Interstate 95 last Dec. 19, it marked the end of a superhighway project that began snaking its way from <LOCATION> Miami </LOCATION> to <LOCATION> Maine </LOCATION> 32 years ago. The idea for the road was born in the 1940s as a way to speed up troop movement, when needed, while aiding the burgeoning <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Coast </LOCATION> population. It was included in a national interstate network outlined in 1956 in the Federal Aid Highway Act signed into law by President <PERSON> Dwight </PERSON> <PERSON> D. </PERSON> <PERSON> Eisenhower </PERSON>. Ambitious plans called for the entire network, 90 percent funded by the federal government, to be carrying traffic by 1972. It was designed as an unbroken freeway, but its 1,866 miles are interrupted in central <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Jersey </LOCATION>, where there is a short gap near <LOCATION> Trenton </LOCATION>. The interstate picks up a few miles later, where it shares the <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Jersey </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Turnpike </ORGANIZATION>. Plans for completing I-95 in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Jersey </LOCATION> were scuttled in 1983. I-95 now runs through all or parts of 15 Eastern states and the <LOCATION> District </LOCATION> <LOCATION> of </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Columbia </LOCATION>, from <LOCATION> Miami </LOCATION> to <PERSON> Houlton </PERSON>, <LOCATION> Maine </LOCATION>. In parts of the heavily-traveled <ORGANIZATION> Northeast </ORGANIZATION>, I-95 often becomes a traffic nightmare. <PERSON> Howard </PERSON> <PERSON> T. </PERSON> <PERSON> Owens </PERSON>, a state senator from <LOCATION> Bridgeport </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Conn. </LOCATION>, and chairman of the <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Assembly </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Transportation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION>, describes the situation on <ORGANIZATION> Interstate </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> 95 </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Connecticut </LOCATION> as `` absolutely horrendous.'' `` It's gridlock from 6:30 a.m. to after 8:30. A ride from <LOCATION> Bridgeport </LOCATION> to <LOCATION> Stamford </LOCATION> that should take 25 minutes takes more than one hour, and if every aspect of mass transportation was used by the year 2000, we'd still have hopeless gridlock,'' <PERSON> Owens </PERSON> said. Work on the $ 222 million final leg in <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION> began in <LOCATION> Jacksonville </LOCATION> in February 1985 with money appropriated by <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> three years before. The last link runs from northeastern <LOCATION> Palm </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Beach </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION> into <LOCATION> Martin </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION>, loops west across the <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Turnpike </LOCATION> and then meanders back toward the coast to connect with what used to be a dead-end stretch of the highway in <LOCATION> St. </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Lucie </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION>. During several years of construction, the then-incomplete portion of I-95 became a favorite runway for drug smugglers. `` It became the longest runway in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> for drug smuggling planes,'' <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> D. </PERSON> <PERSON> Holt </PERSON>, the sheriff of <LOCATION> Martin </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION>, said when the link was opened in December. In <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION>, Interstate 95 offers easy access to all of the <LOCATION> Atlantic </LOCATION> beaches and is little more than an hour away from <ORGANIZATION> Disney </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> World </ORGANIZATION>, <LOCATION> Sea </LOCATION> <LOCATION> World </LOCATION> and many other <LOCATION> Central </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION> attractions. `` I did n't know whether I'd live long enough to see it complete or not,'' said <PERSON> Bill </PERSON> <PERSON> Fowler </PERSON>, of the state <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Transportation </ORGANIZATION>, who helped oversee work on the `` missing link.'' Some officials say completion of the section between <LOCATION> Palm </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Beach </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> St. </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Lucie </LOCATION> counties in southeastern <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION> will open the <ORGANIZATION> Treasure </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Coast </ORGANIZATION> to commuter traffic from as far away as <LOCATION> Miami </LOCATION>. `` You figure a two-hour commute to <LOCATION> Miami </LOCATION> really is n't any worse than what some people do to get from one end of <LOCATION> Miami </LOCATION> to the other, or <LOCATION> Fort </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Lauderdale </LOCATION>,'' said <LOCATION> Martin </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION> Commissioner <PERSON> Maggy </PERSON> <PERSON> Hurchalla </PERSON>. But <PERSON> Lance </PERSON> <PERSON> deHaven-Smith </PERSON>, associate director of the <ORGANIZATION> Florida </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Atlantic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University-Florida </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Joint </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> the </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Study </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Environmental </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Urban </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Problems </ORGANIZATION>, sees it as one more step in `` the <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angelization </LOCATION> of <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION>.''
