<FIRST>a a BC-SPE--Travel:WithI-95-Houlton     04-25 0491</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-SPE--Travel: With I-95-Houlton,0502</SECOND>
<HEAD>BC-SPECIAL EDITION</HEAD>
<HEAD>TRAVEL: With I-95-Houlton</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By EVA PARZIALE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HOULTON, Maine (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Interstate 95, the 1,866-mile corridor that takes truckers, snowbirds and salesmen from <LOCATION> Maine </LOCATION> to <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION>, begins at the Canadian border in this far north potato town. Before reaching <LOCATION> Bangor </LOCATION>, the nearest big city, I-95 winds through miles of potato farms, brushes the <LOCATION> Haynesville </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Woods </LOCATION> _ made famous by <PERSON> Dick </PERSON> <PERSON> Curless </PERSON>' country and western hit, `` Tombstone Every Mile'' _ then passes through a strand of white birches before cutting through the brooding Argyle peat bog. Remote and isolated, the only access to points south before the opening of the two-lane highway in 1966 were state Routes 2 and 2A _ hilly, winding, treacherous roads, particularly in winter. Then the trip to <LOCATION> Bangor </LOCATION> could take up to four hours, and had to be a well-planned event. `` We would go only a couple times a year,'' recalls <PERSON> Lois </PERSON> <PERSON> Ward </PERSON>, 62, who has lived her entire life in this <LOCATION> Aroostook </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION> shiretown of 6,750. `` We'd leave early in the morning, do our shopping, have dinner and it was probably 10 o'clock at night before we were home. It was an all day thing, but it was grand fun.'' Today, the interstate is a four-lane highway and the speed limit 65 mph, which has cut the driving time to <LOCATION> Bangor </LOCATION> in half. `` It was a godsend as far as getting to the southern part of the state,'' lifelong area resident, <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Anderson </PERSON>, 50, said of the highway. `` The interstate ca n't be equalled in my opinion, anywhere.'' The opening of the interstate has increased traffic into the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> from <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION>. When I-95 first opened _ two miles from the <LOCATION> Maine-New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Brunswick </LOCATION> border _ 4,900 people a month entered the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. By 1987, 273,000 people and 5,000 trucks a month were streaming into the country, according to <PERSON> Marc </PERSON> <PERSON> Russell </PERSON>, <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Immigration and <ORGANIZATION> Naturalization </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> supervisor at the border checkpoint. The interstate, which cost $ 140 million to build from <LOCATION> Bangor </LOCATION> to <PERSON> Houlton </PERSON>, also created a new business district, forcing motels, restaurants and stores from downtown <PERSON> Houlton </PERSON> or Route 2A to close or move near the highway to accommodate the re-routed traffic. Some believe business has increased in <LOCATION> Houlton </LOCATION>, where the economy is based on the potato industry and the lumber trade. `` There seems to be more activity in <LOCATION> Houlton </LOCATION> than there has been in prior years,'' said <PERSON> Anderson </PERSON>, an insurance and real estate agent. `` Maybe that's just a gut feeling, but there seems to be more construction. I think development around an interstate seems to snowball.'' While the road has made access to southern <LOCATION> Maine </LOCATION> easier, life in <LOCATION> Houlton </LOCATION>, as one resident says, has n't changed much. `` It's just a long way from the rest of the world,'' Mrs. <PERSON> Ward </PERSON> said. `` Even though you can get to <LOCATION> Bangor </LOCATION> in just under two hours, you still have a long way to go if you want to go to <LOCATION> Boston </LOCATION>.''
