<FIRST>a a BC-SPE--Travel:OlympicCity     04-25 0755</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-SPE--Travel: Olympic City,0774</SECOND>
<HEAD>SPECIAL EDITION</HEAD>
<HEAD>TRAVEL: Olympic City</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhotos NY708, NY709</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BARRY RENFREW</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Once called the Hermit Kingdom, <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION> is preparing to entertain the world at the 1988 Olympic Games and show just how much things have changed. The country, which for centuries tried to seal itself off from the world, has been transformed in recent years into one of <LOCATION> Asia </LOCATION>'s most modern and fastest-growing nations Staging the Olympics is the crowning glory of <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION>'s economic rise. <LOCATION> Seoul </LOCATION>, a sprawling city of 10 million people, has been preparing for years to host the Games and ensure that everything is right when the Olympic spotlight turns on <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION> beginning Sept. 17. The city of high-rise buildings, broad avenues and meticulous neatness is dotted with Olympic flags and banners for the Games. The five interlocked circles, symbol of the Olympic movement, is stamped on everything from milk cartons and television logos to carriages in the <LOCATION> Seoul </LOCATION> subway system. `` The No. 1 games. The No. 1 people,'' proclaim the subway signs on every carriage door. Counters ticking off the days to the start of the games stand outside all government offices and police stations, in every subway station and in many shops and businesses. Some buildings even have little counters in the elevators. Newspapers are filled with articles on the Olympics, <LOCATION> Seoul </LOCATION> taxi drivers are taking courses in English and other foreign languages, homeowners are being urged to provide accommodation for tourists, and hotels and new shops are under construction all over <LOCATION> Seoul </LOCATION>. The sprawling Olympic Park in the south of <LOCATION> Seoul </LOCATION>, with its giant stadiums, tracks and pools, is ready for the Games. Workers scurry around the immaculate complex every day, polishing the stadiums and trimming lawns and trees. But visitors hoping to attend the Olympic Games had better already have firm hotel and airline reservations. Accommodation is likely to be scarce with more than 200,000 visitors expected. Visitors who want to get the real flavor of <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION> should get off the main streeets and take a walk through the sidestreets and alleys that are usually just one block over. Street life in <LOCATION> Seoul </LOCATION> is colorful and entertaining. Little shops offer brightly colored quilts and basketwork, antique dealers sell old pottery and elaborate Korean chests. Stall holders are everywhere selling fruit, vegetables and flowers. Sidewalk vendors or little makeshift restraurants offer onion pancakes, rice noodles in red pepper sauce and jam and almond paste cakes, roast chestnuts and dried squid. Koreans like to socialize over food and drink and <LOCATION> Seoul </LOCATION> is covered with thousands of restaurants, beer halls, tea rooms, snack counters and sidewalk vendors serving a vast range of dishes. Korean food offers distinctive spicy dishes such as pulgogi, a barbecued beef that is cooked at your table, and kalbi or barbecued beef ribs. Kimchi, fiery pickled cabbage that is the most famous dish in Korean cuisine, accompanies just about every meal. Another pleasure are the many small and inexpensive noodle and rice restaurants where a steaming bowl of fish or beef soup can be had with noodles or rice for $ 2 or $ 3. Many visitors enjoy sampling both local brews and Korean society by visiting Korean beerhalls, where local beers and a potent sorghum liquor called soju are served. Koreans love to sing and strangers and friends join in everything from country and western hits to haunting Korean love melodies. <LOCATION> Seoul </LOCATION> has much to offer shoppers, with bargains in clothes, luggage, shoes and leather goods, porcelain, Oriental prints, fabric, and inexpensive jewelery. Several fur companies offer bargain fur coats that shoppers pick up at the airport on their way out. The city is covered with shops, department stores, arcades and markets. Many visitors head for the <LOCATION> Itaewon </LOCATION> <LOCATION> District </LOCATION>, where English is widely spoken. More colorful are the vast open air markets at <LOCATION> Tongdaemun </LOCATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Namdaemun </ORGANIZATION> where vendors sell everything from sneakers and bolts of brilliantly colored silk to live carp and turtles for dinner. Foreign visitors invariably say language is the biggest problem they encounter. English and other foreign languages are not widely spoken. But Koreans will happily assist guests and smiles, nods and hand gestures are often sufficient. One problem confronting Olympic visitors will be very strict security that could make getting around difficult at times during the Games. The government, concerned about possible terrorist threats from rival communist <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION>, will deploy tens of thousands of troops and police to ensure the safety of the Games and the visitors.
</TEXT>
