<FIRST>a a BC-SPE--Travel:Nepal     04-25 0708</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-SPE--Travel: Nepal,0728</SECOND>
<HEAD>BC-SPECIAL EDITION</HEAD>
<HEAD>TRAVEL: Nepal</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By G.G. LaBELLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>POKHARA, Nepal (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Men and women with heavy loads on their backs trudge the roads of <LOCATION> Pokhara </LOCATION>. Some are trekkers _ Americans, Europeans, Australians _ going up into the mountains Others are <PERSON> Gurung </PERSON> tribesmen coming down with loads of cloth or grain. <LOCATION> Pokhara </LOCATION>, 124 miles west of <LOCATION> Katmandu </LOCATION>, owes its existence to the majestic sweep of half a dozen Himalayan peaks to the north. It calls itself `` Gateway to <PERSON> Annapurna </PERSON>,'' after the tallest at 26,504 feet. It is crowded with young tourists chattering about treks and older ones waiting hopefully for frequent clouds and mist to part for a glimpse of the snowy peaks. It was not always so. In fact, says retired British Col. J.O.M. <PERSON> Roberts </PERSON>, <LOCATION> Pokhara </LOCATION> was once one of the world's most isolated places. `` Anything you can see here, cut it down. It did n't exist,'' <PERSON> Roberts </PERSON> said, recalling his initial visit as one of the first Westerners into the <LOCATION> Pokhara </LOCATION> valley in 1950. <LOCATION> Nepal </LOCATION> was closed to tourists until 1951, and the ony way to <LOCATION> Pokhara </LOCATION> was to walk. French climber <PERSON> Maurice </PERSON> <PERSON> Herzog </PERSON>, the first European to conquer a major Himalayan peak, bypassed the place en route to his conquest of Annapurna I on June 3, 1950. <PERSON> Roberts </PERSON> said that on his second visit in 1957, he saw only an airstrip and a tree. Even the oxcart, ubiquitous in south <LOCATION> Asia </LOCATION>, did not arrive in <LOCATION> Pokhara </LOCATION> until 1961, brought in by aircraft. Today, where only rocky paths existed, a string of villages makes up the town of <LOCATION> Pokhara </LOCATION>. Corrugated tin shops, thatch shacks and concrete-block houses have sprung up willy-nilly. About 70,000 people live in the area. Many are <PERSON> Gurungs </PERSON> or Mayars who came down from the hills to settle after seeing the outside world in the famed Gurkha regiments in which <PERSON> Roberts </PERSON> also served. D.B. <PERSON> Thapa </PERSON> of the government tourist office said 70,000 visitors also come to <LOCATION> Pokhara </LOCATION> each year. But natives and foreigners rarely collide, since tribesmen do their business in the <LOCATION> Mahendra </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Pul </LOCATION> area north of the airport, and Westerners hang out near <LOCATION> Lake </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Phewa </LOCATION> to the west. At the native bazaar, most signs are in Nepali script, though the <ORGANIZATION> Shakva </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Tailors </ORGANIZATION> advertises `` Satisfaction Is Our Garent.'' A search for books in English turns up only `` Basic Chemistry'' and similar texts. The lakeside, by contrast, is a bibliophile's dream: 16 bookstores can be found in a 15-minute walk, with titles in a half-dozen languages traded or sold by wandering readers. At one shop, the Bible in German shares a shelf with `` I'll Take Manhattan'' by <PERSON> Judith </PERSON> <PERSON> Krantz </PERSON>, <PERSON> Tolstoy </PERSON>'s `` War and Peace,'' and `` Annapurna, Premier 8,000,'' <PERSON> Herzog </PERSON>'s tale of his conquest. Nearby are books on mountains and mysticism, along with Batik versions of the Tantric erotic art carved on <LOCATION> Nepal </LOCATION>'s Hindu temples. The rest of the lakeside is a similar international jumble: the <ORGANIZATION> Amica </ORGANIZATION> German Hair Composer, Axis Steaks and Pizza, the Monsoon Restaurant _ Japanese food, and Tranquility Lodge offering `` harmony, peace and good energy.'' `` You can get a room in <LOCATION> Pokhara </LOCATION> from 15 rupees to 1,500 rupees,'' _ 70 cents to $ 70 dollars _ said <PERSON> Ranga </PERSON> <PERSON> Nath </PERSON> <PERSON> Timilshina </PERSON>, 19, who was hawking the <PERSON> Amrit </PERSON> <PERSON> Hotel </PERSON>, four rooms each with bath added to his family's lakeside home. A friend, 22-year-old <PERSON> Madabah </PERSON> <PERSON> Prasad </PERSON> <PERSON> Neupane </PERSON>, leaned on his bicycle and mused about changes since <LOCATION> Pokhara </LOCATION>'s hotel boom began in the late 1960s. `` People here used to be farmers. Now they find the hotel business is an easy way to get money,'' he said. <PERSON> Roberts </PERSON> grumbles about the `` concrete mess'' of today's <LOCATION> Pokhara </LOCATION>, but his trekking service here makes him part of the place. He even has a role in one supposed legend of the ersatz town. One guidebook relates how an expedition that <PERSON> Roberts </PERSON> led in 1957 to climb 22,958-foot <PERSON> Macha </PERSON> <PERSON> Pucchare </PERSON> _ Fishtail Peak, the nearest to the town _ turned back because <LOCATION> Sherpa </LOCATION> guides feared the wrath of the `` mountain goddess.'' Not so, said <PERSON> Roberts </PERSON>. The Sherpas had no superstitions, and it was two British climbers who were forced to quit about 150 feet from the top. `` We were beaten by the mountain,'' he said. `` It's still not been climbed,'' he added. `` It's nice to have something untouched.''
</TEXT>
