<HEAD>SPECIAL EDITION</HEAD>
<HEAD>TRAVEL: Conner Prairie</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY703</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LESLIE H. DREYFOUS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NOBLESVILLE, Ind. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Conner </PERSON> <PERSON> Prairie </PERSON>, one of the nation's most authentic 19th-century villages, is adding something new: a state-of-the-art, $ 10.5 million museum center The museum center will open May 7 with a two-day celebration. <LOCATION> Conner </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Prairie </LOCATION>, six miles north of <LOCATION> Indianapolis </LOCATION>, depicts the lives, times, attitudes and values of <LOCATION> Indiana </LOCATION>'s first settlers. It stretches over 250 acres and attracts 200,000 visitors annually. `` You're in your own historical novel or personal <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Wayne </PERSON> movie,'' said <PERSON> Frank </PERSON> <PERSON> Werner </PERSON>, who supervises the museum's documentation `` People who know nothing of the 1830s come out here and suddenly find themselves wrapped up in the history. We awaken people to the realities _ good and bad.'' The museum center will house a permanent gallery, temporary exhibition hall, audio-visual program, restaurant, 100-seat theater, library, classrooms and administrative offices. `` The center has been designed as a complement to the village,'' museum smokeswoman <PERSON> Brenda </PERSON> <PERSON> Myers </PERSON> says. `` It's a modern visitor's center meant to augment what's outside The village is real, so why imitate?'' Open since 1974, <PERSON> Conner </PERSON> <PERSON> Prairie </PERSON> features `` citizens'' interpreting everyday events from a 19th-century perspective. Visitors are encouraged to participate in hands-on activities as they circulate among the town's 30 authentic buildings. `` Kids can poke around and play here and that does n't happen at most historic sites,'' <PERSON> Myers </PERSON> said. `` There are so many generic living history museums and ` no touch' places out there. That's what we want to avoid. `` We encourage active participation because we want visitors to get not only a sense of how people lived, but how they felt. How better to learn history?'' <PERSON> Werner </PERSON> said family members of all ages enjoy chatting with the more than 100 history interpreters at Conner Prairie and joining them in weaving, making soap, cooking, working with wood and playing pioneer games. `` You ca n't describe what the interpreters do as acting,'' said <PERSON> Werner </PERSON>, who also participates in the role-playing. `` It goes beyond acting. You're recreating social, political, cultural and emotional circumstances.'' He also underlined the museum's success in educating visitors _ in some cases _ despite themselves. `` People expect the typical history museum where everything is ` over there' and roped off,'' <PERSON> Werner </PERSON> said. `` But here, no one's lecturing you People's hesitancy breaks down and they become a part of the village. We impart factual knowledge without their knowing it.'' Evening concerts on the prairie, candlelight walks and hearthside suppers are among the special programs scheduled year-round at the museum. Families can also relive the pioneer experience by reserving a rustic cabin on the prairie or by attending horse races, weddings, funerals and political debates in the village. `` We generally have funerals in the fall, because that was the cholera season. We aim to make visitors feel and understand that these are real people, not just historic figures,'' <PERSON> Myers </PERSON> said. `` Everything here has to be tried and true and confirmed by at least three sources.'' International pharmaceutical heir <PERSON> Eli </PERSON> <PERSON> Lilly </PERSON> originally purchased the property in 1934. With his wife, he restored the original <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Conner </PERSON> home, decorating it with period antiques before donating it and the surrounding farmland to <ORGANIZATION> Earlham </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> College </ORGANIZATION> in 1964. <PERSON> Conner </PERSON>, a frontiersman, trader and statesman, was instrumental in developing central <LOCATION> Indiana </LOCATION> during the early 19th century.
</TEXT>
