<HEAD>TRAVEL: With Conner Prairie-Historic</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
 For travelers with a special interest in American history, in rediscovering American roots, there are numerous book guides to the past. Among them is the lavish Reader's Digest `` <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>'s Historic Places,'' published this spring -LRB- $ 26.95 -RRB-. It is an oversized travel guide and reference book to 500 locations throughout the country, including historic battlefields from <LOCATION> Gettysburg </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Pa. </LOCATION>, to the <LOCATION> Alamo </LOCATION>; mansions like the <LOCATION> Wentworth-Coolidge </LOCATION> mansion in <LOCATION> Portsmouth </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.H. </LOCATION>, and <PERSON> Beauvoir </PERSON>, the spacious cottage in <LOCATION> Biloxi </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Miss. </LOCATION>, where <PERSON> Jefferson </PERSON> <PERSON> Davis </PERSON> lived the last 12 years of his life; and monuments from the national capital's <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> Monument to <LOCATION> Iowa </LOCATION>'s Effigy Mounds, the Hopewell Indian burial sculptures. The well-illustrated book has travel-planning details, such as when places are open and how much they charge, as well as background text on the sites, listed according to regions. Another travel book focusing on <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>'s history is `` Experiencing <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>'s Past,'' a paperback guide to restored, re-created and reconstructed museum villages -LRB- <ORGANIZATION> Wiley </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION>, 1986, $ 12.95 -RRB-. Authors <PERSON> Gerald </PERSON> and <PERSON> Patricia </PERSON> <PERSON> Gurek </PERSON> list some 40 places from <LOCATION> Old </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Sturbridge </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Village </LOCATION> in <LOCATION> Sturbridge </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Mass. </LOCATION>, a re-created <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> England </LOCATION> town of the 1830s, to the <LOCATION> Greenfield </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Village </LOCATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Henry </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Museum </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Dearborn </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Mich. </LOCATION>, an indoor-outdoor museum dedicated to the automobile. However, the book deals only with places beteween the <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Coast </LOCATION> and the <LOCATION> Midwest </LOCATION>.
