<HEAD>SPECIAL EDITION</HEAD>
<HEAD>TRAVEL: Asheville</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
 `` Dixieland was a big cheaply constructed frame house of 18 or 20 drafty high-ceilinged rooms: it had a rambling, unplanned gabular appearance.'' In <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON> <PERSON> Wolfe </PERSON>'s autobiographical first novel, ` Look Homeward, <PERSON> Angel </PERSON>,'' `` Dixieland'' was the fictional name for the place called <ORGANIZATION> Old </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Kentucky </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Home </ORGANIZATION>, a boarding house run by his mother in his birthplace of <LOCATION> Asheville </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.C. </LOCATION> <PERSON> Wolfe </PERSON> moved into the boarding house when he was about 6 years old. `` The construction was after her own plans,'' <PERSON> Wolfe </PERSON> wrote of the house, `` and of the cheapest material: it never lost the smell of raw wood, cheap varnish and flimsy rough plastering.'' <PERSON> Wolfe </PERSON>'s mother, <PERSON> Julia </PERSON> -LRB- the <PERSON> Eliza </PERSON> of `` Look Homeward, Angel'' -RRB- bought the house in 1906 for $ 6,500. She renovated it, added rooms and a sun porch and rented to traveling salesmen, vaudeville performers, school teachers, and others. Her business cards advertised, `` Large Lawns, No Sick People, Rates Reasonable.'' <PERSON> Wolfe </PERSON>'s father, <PERSON> W.O. </PERSON>, refused to become a part of the enterprise and stayed at the old family home on <LOCATION> Woodfin </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Street </LOCATION>, now a YMCA. The boarders provided <PERSON> Wolfe </PERSON> with much material for his novels. `` Look Homeward, Angel'' shocked <LOCATION> Asheville </LOCATION> residents of the time, who objected to the unvarnished, thinly-disguised portraits of those in <PERSON> Wolfe </PERSON>'s fictional town of `` <LOCATION> Altamont </LOCATION>.'' The book was banned from the local <LOCATION> Asheville </LOCATION> library. But today, there's renewed interest in <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON> <PERSON> Wolfe </PERSON> _ the 1988 Pulitzer Prize for biography went to <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Herbert </PERSON> <PERSON> Donald </PERSON> for `` Look Homeward: A Life of <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON> <PERSON> Wolfe </PERSON>'' _ and <LOCATION> Asheville </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.C. </LOCATION>, is saying you can go home again. The 28-room boarding house at 48 Spruce St. -LRB- Spring St. in <PERSON> Wolfe </PERSON>'s novel -RRB- is now a literary shrine, open to the public, with formal tours -LRB- $ 1 admission -RRB-. A `` Living History'' attraction is featured this May 14-15, with role players at the house wearing period costumes of 1916, the year <PERSON> Wolfe </PERSON> left <LOCATION> Asheville </LOCATION> to attend the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> North </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Carolina </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Chapel </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hill </LOCATION>. `` We try very hard to present the house and its inhabitants exactly as they were back then,'' says <PERSON> Steve </PERSON> <PERSON> Hill </PERSON>, site manager of the Wolfe Memorial. `` The costumes of the people playing the role of boarders are specially made to assure their authenticity. `` Once visitors enter the home, they will think they have taken a trip back in time to 1916. Even the music we play is from that time period.'' The house reflects the early 1900s with furnishings and many personal effects intact. An upstairs bedroom contains <PERSON> Wolfe </PERSON>'s belongings from his <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> apartment, including clothing, a writing table and typewriter -LRB- which he never used, preferring to write in longhand -RRB- <PERSON> Wolfe </PERSON>, also the author of `` Of Time and the River'' and `` You Ca n't Go Home Again,'' among others, died in 1938. The 50th anniversary of his death will be marked with a special program at the home in September. In October, there will be an open house to commemorate his birthday. Another tourist site in the area is the <ORGANIZATION> Biltmore </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION>, the <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> W. </PERSON> <PERSON> Vanderbilt </PERSON> mansion built in <LOCATION> Asheville </LOCATION> in 1885 by architect <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Morris </PERSON> <PERSON> Hunt </PERSON> and landscape designer <PERSON> Frederick </PERSON> <PERSON> Law </PERSON> <PERSON> Olmsted </PERSON>. Touted as `` the largest, grandest residential estate ever built in <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>,'' the Renaissance-style chateau has 250 rooms and 17 acres of gardens. Built as <ORGANIZATION> Vanderbilt </ORGANIZATION>'s dream house in the mountains outside of <LOCATION> Asheville </LOCATION>, it originally encompassed 125,000 acres. After <ORGANIZATION> Vanderbilt </ORGANIZATION>'s death in 1914, part of the estate was deeded to the federal government to form the nucleus of the <ORGANIZATION> Pisgah </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Forest </ORGANIZATION>, part sold for a section of the <LOCATION> Blue </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Ridge </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Parkway </LOCATION> and part incorporated into the residential town of <LOCATION> Biltmore </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Forest </LOCATION>. The house museum is open for tours and now includes the Biltmore Winery. <LOCATION> Asheville </LOCATION> is the largest city in western <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Carolina </LOCATION>, bounded by the <LOCATION> Blue </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Ridge </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Mountains </LOCATION> to the east, and the <LOCATION> Great </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Smoky </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Mountains </LOCATION> <LOCATION> National </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Park </LOCATION> about 50 miles to the west along the border with <LOCATION> Tennessee </LOCATION>.
