<FIRST>a a BC-SPE--Travel:Disabled     04-25 0559</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-SPE--Travel: Disabled,0573</SECOND>
<HEAD>SPECIAL EDITION</HEAD>
<HEAD>TRAVEL: Disabled</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By H. JOSEF HEBERT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Groups that represent the handicapped are eagerly awaiting a <ORGANIZATION> Transportation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> regulation _ expected within a few months _ that they hope will clarify their rights aboard commercial airliners. People who must use wheelchairs or are blind have complained for years that they are being discriminated against and often embarrassed when they travel by air. The battle lines between the handicapped and the airline industry have at times been tense. According to the National Federation of the Blind, there have been more than 20 blind people arrested and taken from aircraft because of disputes over seating or other issues. `` What the blind want most is simple, straightforward, uncomplicated and reasonable. We want to be left alone to buy our tickets and fly in peace,'' <PERSON> Marc </PERSON> <PERSON> Mauer </PERSON>, president of the federation, told a government panel last September. The new regulations are expected to provide broad guidelines to the airlines on how they should accommodate the handicapped and also provide specific requirements. `` Once we get these regulations in draft form a lot of people will finally know what their rights are and the airlines will know what their obligations are. Things will be a lot clearer,'' says <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Capozzi </PERSON>, an official of the Paralyzed Veterans of <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>. The regulations stem from the Air Carrier Access Act, enacted by <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> in 1986 to specifically guarantee the rights of the handicapped to have access to air travel without discrimination. <PERSON> Capozzi </PERSON>, who uses a wheelchair, said issues still to be resolved include: _ The question of where handicapped passengers should be allowed to sit. Federal regulations include no seating restrictions, although many airlines have policies that direct handicapped to be seated in certain sections of a plane. _ Should airlines be allowed to set a limit on the number of handicapped people to allow on a single flight? Airlines want to restrict such passengers to no more than the number of emergency exits on an aircraft. _ Should a handicapped traveler be required to be accompanied by an attendant? Advocacy groups for the handicapped argue that should be up to the traveler involved. The seating issue is among the most controversial. The airlines want the government to specifically exclude handicapped passengers from certain seats, such as the row next to an emergency exit. But groups representing the handicapped scoff at suggestions that a blind person might be a liability in such a location. They also say that if there is a restriction it should be limited to the door adjacent to the exit and not an entire row. Some airlines require the handicapped to be seated in specific seats in an aircraft. Recently, a blind passenger aboard a <ORGANIZATION> Midway </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airlines </ORGANIZATION> jet was arrested when she refused to move from the smoking section at the rear of the plane to the first row close to an exit door. <PERSON> Capozzi </PERSON> said that the incident was an example of another problem facing the handicapped. `` They -LRB- the airlines -RRB- treat the disabled persn as a homogenized group. You need to look at the individual differences,'' he says. Travelers who are confined to wheelchairs, for example, like the first row of an airplane because of the easy access, but to a blind person that same requirement may not be irrelevant, he suggests.
</TEXT>
