 <PERSON> Shamu </PERSON>, <PERSON> Namu </PERSON> and <PERSON> Kandu </PERSON> are readying a killer of a sea show that organizers hope will fishtail with the <LOCATION> Alamo </LOCATION> and the city's <LOCATION> River </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Walk </LOCATION>. While the killer whales swim around in a 7 million gallon tank, gardeners are putting the final landscaping touches on Sea World of <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION>, a $ 140 million, 250-acre facility billed as the nation's largest marine theme park The park's `` Big Splash'' opening is set for May 28, but workers, animals and trainers are already performing in rehearsals for visitors. Sea World, 13 miles northwest of downtown <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Antonio </LOCATION>, will be open year-round. It is expected to employ 2,000 people during its peak summer season, generate a $ 25 million annual payroll and attract 3 million visitors bearing another $ 300 million yearly for the park's and <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION>' economies. City and tourist industry officials have looked at <LOCATION> Sea </LOCATION> <LOCATION> World </LOCATION> as a magnet for tourists to help the state diversify from its dependency on petroleum, but <ORGANIZATION> Sea </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> World </ORGANIZATION> chairman <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Becker </PERSON> warns against expecting too much too soon. `` I've cautioned a few people that we'll do the very best that we can, but not to rest on their laurels and expect us to be the end-all and the answer to all of their business problems,'' he said. Visitors can expect to see the park's star, <PERSON> Shamu </PERSON>, a two-ton killer whale that was among the fish and animals brought in from three other Sea World parks around the country. <PERSON> Shamu </PERSON> will perform in a 4,500-seat stadium. At other, smaller stadiums, dolphins, seals, sea lions, walruses and other animals will show their stuff, too. Skiers will perform acr