<FIRST>a a BC-SPE--Travel:Soho     04-25 0658</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-SPE--Travel: Soho,0676</SECOND>
<HEAD>BC-SPECIAL EDITION</HEAD>
<HEAD>TRAVEL: Soho</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LESLIE SHEPHERD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> Soho </LOCATION>, the <LOCATION> Bohemian </LOCATION> neighborhood famed for its smorgasbord of restaurants and expensive, tourist-oriented topless bars, is cleaning up its naughty image. Families are moving back to the once seedy half-mile square area of central <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> that was originally settled by immigrants and refugees. Trendy restaurants, wine bars and media companies are moving next door to generations-old firms of tailors, silversmiths and clockmakers, reclaiming the classic Georgian buildings from what was collectively known as `` the vice.'' Part of <LOCATION> Soho </LOCATION> has become the capital's <LOCATION> Chinatown </LOCATION>, with <PERSON> Gerard </PERSON> <PERSON> Street </PERSON> converted into a busy mall lined with <LOCATION> Chinese </LOCATION> restaurants, supermarkets, bookstores and pay phones with pagoda-style roofs. The impetus for change came from <LOCATION> Soho </LOCATION>'s residents who were tired of gazing out their windows at pulsating pink neon signs boasting `` Girls, Girls, Girls,'' and of having to slink past peep shows, pornographic cinemas, lingerie shops and topless bars every time they took their children to school or shopped for groceries. `` The local community realized that it was them or us,'' explained <PERSON> Bryan </PERSON> <PERSON> Burrough </PERSON>, chairman of the <ORGANIZATION> Soho </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Society </ORGANIZATION>. `` And we wanted to make sure it was us.'' <PERSON> Soho </PERSON> became synonymous with sleaze during World War II when <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> soldiers swarmed to its clubs and pubs. But <PERSON> Burrough </PERSON> said <LOCATION> Soho </LOCATION> did n't hit rock bottom until the mid-1970s. `` Prior to the mid-1960s, ` the vice' was represented in the main by prostitutes who were fairly unnoticeable,'' he said. `` In the 1970s it became sex cinemas, topless encounter bars, all sorts of things totally outside the provisions of the law. So ordinary, legitimate businesses were being pushed out.'' The 1,000-member <ORGANIZATION> Soho </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Society </ORGANIZATION> was founded in 1972 as a community group, and one of first accomplishments was to have <ORGANIZATION> Soho </ORGANIZATION> declared a conservation area, meaning nothing can be demolished without permission from the Westminster borough council. Westminster then passed tougher laws to regulate the flesh trade. The borough set aside just 10 licenses for sex shops, and a spokeswoman says only five were actually issued, all to book and video stores. <PERSON> Burrough </PERSON> said about 20 more sex shops still operate illegally, compared with a decade ago when 185 Soho buildings were devoted to the sex industry. He said 18 such buildings were on Greek Street alone, but now its four short blocks are home to 18 restaurants, three pubs, two sandwich bars, a patisserie, and only one sex shop. <LOCATION> Soho </LOCATION>, in the heart of <LOCATION> London </LOCATION>'s <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> End </LOCATION> <LOCATION> theater </LOCATION> <LOCATION> district </LOCATION>, is bounded by <LOCATION> Oxford </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Street </LOCATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Regent </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Street </ORGANIZATION>, <LOCATION> Charing </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Cross </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Road </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Leicester </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Square </LOCATION>. The name is thought to come from the ancient hare-hunting cry, `` So-Ho.'' The area's cosmopolitan flavor dates back to its first immigrants, French Protestants known as Huguenots who arrived in the late 1600s. Germans and Italians, many of them cooks and waiters, arrived in the 1860s and 1870s, followed by Polish and Russian Jews, many of them tailors, in the 1890s. Joining the melting pot were families from almost every other European country as well as <LOCATION> British </LOCATION> colonies past and present, Indians and <LOCATION> Hong </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Kong </LOCATION> Chinese. In the 1960s a favorite <LOCATION> Soho </LOCATION> haunt was Carnaby Street, with its swinging fashion shops stocked with bellbottoms, go-go boots, miniskirts and fishnet stockings. Today, <LOCATION> Soho </LOCATION>'s nooks and crannies are still packed with old established family businesses. Here the Savile Row tailors have their workshops, and gold lace is handmade for Buckingham Palace's livery Sprinkled among them are dozens of new film production and distribution offices, film laboratories, advertising agencies and other support services for <LOCATION> London </LOCATION>'s TV and cinema industry. Street for street, <LOCATION> Soho </LOCATION> is said to have more restaurants than any other part of <LOCATION> London </LOCATION>, ranging from Japanese sushi bars to a 1950s-style chrome and formica diner. Gourmets and gourmands can wallow in a cheese shop offering 200 varieties including car-tire-sized wheels of Swiss emmenthal. A coffee shop sells 25 types of fresh, aromatic beans, and barbecued ducks hang in Chinese markets.
</TEXT>
