<BYLINE>By PRUDENCE HELLER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Take the train: That's the message of railroads all over <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>. Their lures include rail passes and reduced rates, tours sponsored by the railroads or by companies using rail transportation, and ride-a-bit, drive-a-bit arrangements covering trains and cars. Railroads have taken into account that a person may not want to ride the rails continuously, day after day, and yet wants full money's worth from his pass. So some offer passes that are good for perhaps nine days of train travel within a 21-day period or 16 days within a month, or other combinations. Eurail's Flexipass and the French Railpass fall into this category. The Flexipass is one of Eurail's four types of passes, all first class and covering 16 countries from <LOCATION> Austria </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Greece </LOCATION> to <LOCATION> Portugal </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Ireland </LOCATION>, but not <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>. For that, one would want the first class or economy class BritRail pass. Eurail, BritRail and the <LOCATION> France </LOCATION> Railpass all must be purchased outside the countries concerned. Travelers seeking to concentrate on a given region might look into the Scandinavian Rail Pass, covering <LOCATION> Denmark </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Finland </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Norway </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Sweden </LOCATION> and sold in the Scandinavian countries, or the <ORGANIZATION> Benelux </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Tourrail </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Pass </ORGANIZATION>, covering <LOCATION> Belgium </LOCATION>, the <LOCATION> Netherlands </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Luxembourg </LOCATION> and sold only in those countries. The <ORGANIZATION> European </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Travel </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> also lists more than a dozen countries that have their own passes. They include <LOCATION> Italy </LOCATION> -LRB- B.T.L.C. Pass -RRB-, <LOCATION> Ireland </LOCATION> -LRB- Rambler -RRB-, <LOCATION> Austria </LOCATION> -LRB- Austrian Network Pass -RRB-, and <LOCATION> Switzerland </LOCATION> -LRB- Swiss Holiday Card -RRB-. A number of countries also offer discounts of up to 50 percent for senior citizens or sell half-fare cards entitling a traveler to half-fare on all train travel for a given period. On this side of the <LOCATION> Atlantic </LOCATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Amtrak </ORGANIZATION> has its All Aboard <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> fares, enabling people to take the train to any destination within one region of the country for a set roundtrip price, within two regions for a bit more and across the entire country for still another set price. One intermediate stop is allowed each way. <ORGANIZATION> Amtrak </ORGANIZATION> also offers a $ 7 Return Fare under which the purchaser of a one-way ticket in many cases can get the return trip for only $ 7. On regular <ORGANIZATION> Amtrak </ORGANIZATION> fares, seniors get a discount. <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION>'s railroad system, Via, has a Canrailpass and a Youthrailpass, which can be purchased in <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION>, and senior citizens get one-third off regular fares. In <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>, there are first-class and ordinary rail passes _ and a new undersea tunnel, more than 33 miles, linking the main island of <LOCATION> Honshu </LOCATION> with Hokkaido to the north. In many countries, passes also carry such perks as cut-rate entry to places of interest or free travel on city buses or subways. This is just a glimpse along the tracks. Railroads urge travelers to consider all the options before they make a choice. Sometimes a senior discount, for instance, or a one-time payment for half-fare privileges might be a bigger bargain than a pass. Many Americans, unused to trains, may feel lost without a car. The railroads have the answer: a car waiting at the station. Explore the countryside, return the car, and board the train again for the next destination _ and the next car. Eurail users can even leave the car involved in another country in some cases. For travelers who do n't want to lift a finger, there are tours by rail: <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION>'s famed Copper Canyon with its 37 bridges and 86 tunnels; <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION> coast-to-coast; a nostalgic trip on the <ORGANIZATION> Orient </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Express </ORGANIZATION> from <LOCATION> Istanbul </LOCATION> to <LOCATION> Zurich </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Switzerland </LOCATION>. You name it. The less ambitious can take one-day excursions _ from <LOCATION> Paris </LOCATION> to the chateau country, or <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> to Bath, Stonehenge and <PERSON> Salisbury </PERSON>, for instance. Tours take care of luggage, hotels, many meals, sightseeing and escorts to tell one what it's all about and leap the language barrier.
