<BYLINE>By BRUCE HANDLER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>RIO DE JANEIRO, Brazil (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Ripoffs and muggings of foreign tourists are giving Rio an image problem, and the government _ discreetly _ is trying to persuaded `` gringos'' to skip this famous city and visit other parts of vast <LOCATION> Brazil </LOCATION>. `` There's only one trouble spot for tourists in <LOCATION> Brazil </LOCATION>, and that's <LOCATION> Rio </LOCATION> <LOCATION> de </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Janeiro </LOCATION>,'' <PERSON> Joao </PERSON> <PERSON> Doria </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON>, president of <ORGANIZATION> Embratur </ORGANIZATION>, the federal government tourist board, told The <ORGANIZATION> AP </ORGANIZATION>. Police figures are imprecise, but almost every day Rio newspapers carry stories of Americans, Europeans and even Latins from the Spanish-speaking part of <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> complaining of 1,000 percent jackups of taxi fares, thefts of cameras and wallets from beaches and hotel rooms, and even outright stickups, sometimes by armed robbers. A federal government poster at <LOCATION> Rio </LOCATION>'s international airport shows a doll-like figure wearing shorts and a flowery shirt, with a camera around its neck. Written below in big letters is: `` Respeite o Turista,'' or `` Respect the Tourist'' in <LOCATION> Portuguese </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Brazil </LOCATION>'s language <ORGANIZATION> Embratur </ORGANIZATION>'s official line is that <PERSON> Rio </PERSON> is still a great place. But meanwhile, the agency is trying to make it easier for foreigners to visit other parts of the country. Many foreigners do n't realize that <LOCATION> Brazil </LOCATION> is bigger in area than the 48 contiguous <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, and tropical beach cities such as <LOCATION> Recife </LOCATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Natal </ORGANIZATION> at the country's northeastern tip and the <LOCATION> Amazon </LOCATION> jungle gateway of Manaus are thousands of miles closer to the Northern Hemisphere than <PERSON> Rio </PERSON> is. <LOCATION> Brazil </LOCATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Varig </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airlines </ORGANIZATION> has a daily nonstop run from <LOCATION> Miami </LOCATION> to <LOCATION> Rio </LOCATION>. But one extra flight on that route stops weekly in <LOCATION> Manaus </LOCATION>, where <ORGANIZATION> Embratur </ORGANIZATION> has begun a program of `` ecological tourism'' aimed at the appreciation for and preservation of the remarkable flora and fauna along the tributaries of the <LOCATION> Amazon </LOCATION> <LOCATION> River </LOCATION>. <ORGANIZATION> Varig </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> France </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Portugal </ORGANIZATION> now include <LOCATION> Recife </LOCATION>, with its miles of palm-fringed, balmy beaches and precious Portuguese colonial architecture, on some of their European flights. `` We want to increase airline competition to Brazilian entry points that are not now generally well known,'' <PERSON> Doria </PERSON> said. `` The goal is to reduce air fares and attract more visitors.'' Despite its climate, scenery, music and cheap currency, <LOCATION> Brazil </LOCATION> attracts just 1 percent of world tourism. And of the 2 million annual visitors, most come from neighboring <LOCATION> Argentina </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Uruguay </LOCATION>, with the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> in third place, followed by <LOCATION> Italy </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>. `` Because <LOCATION> Brazil </LOCATION> is a poor country, surrounded by poor countries, in the far-off <LOCATION> Southern </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hemisphere </LOCATION>, it will never compete with places such as <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Spain </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Italy </LOCATION> for international tourism,'' <PERSON> Doria </PERSON> said. `` But we do think realistically we can get our share up to 3 percent.'' But <LOCATION> Brazil </LOCATION>'s own typical Latin bureaucracy often gets in the way of tourism objectives. The <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION>, which determines international airline routes, has been reluctant to promote unrestricted air competition. `` The ministry has been, let us say, conservative in this area, but still we are making progress,'' <PERSON> Doria </PERSON> said. `` Five years ago, no charter flights were permitted in <LOCATION> Brazil </LOCATION>. Today we have them every week from <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>.'' <LOCATION> Brazil </LOCATION>'s Foreign Relations Ministry often makes foreign tourists obtain a visa before they can come to brazil. The standard is reciprocity: If a foreign country requires a visa for Brazilians, then citizens of that country must get a visa for <LOCATION> Brazil </LOCATION>. `` Sometimes what sounds right diplomatically does n't make sense economically,'' <PERSON> Doria </PERSON> said of the visa policy. `` Take the case of <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION>, which recently instituted visas for <LOCATION> Brazil </LOCATION>, because some Brazilian tourists were caught working there illegally. So now Canadians need visas to visit <LOCATION> Brazil </LOCATION>. But I ca n't imagine many Canadians seeking to work illegally in <LOCATION> Brazil </LOCATION>.'' `` Our own government's countermeasures was not in our country's best interests, financially speaking,'' <PERSON> Doria </PERSON> said
