<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
 `` Wednesday 3 June 1863. `` Cloudy weather dominated the skies along the <LOCATION> Rappahannock </LOCATION> <LOCATION> River </LOCATION> at <LOCATION> Fredericksburg </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Va </LOCATION>. It rained somewhat in the morning.'' It was on that day that the <LOCATION> Gettysburg </LOCATION> campaign of the Civil War began with the <ORGANIZATION> Confederate </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Northern </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Virginia </ORGANIZATION> starting its march toward <LOCATION> Pennsylvania </LOCATION>, as Gen. <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> E. </PERSON> <PERSON> Lee </PERSON> `` commenced to draw the army from the vicinity of <LOCATION> Fredericksburg </LOCATION>.'' <PERSON> Lee </PERSON> realized some of his army's deficiencies, yet wrote to his wife: `` I trust that a kind Providence will watch over us, and notwithstanding our weakness and sins will yet give us a name and place among the nations of the earth.'' The excerpts are from a <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Park </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> daybook of the campaign, part of the national commemoration of the 125th anniversary of the key battle at the <LOCATION> Gettysburg </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Pa. </LOCATION>, National Military Park. The commemoration begins Memorial Day, May 30. A `` Living History Encampment'' starts June 18 on a farm outside <LOCATION> Gettysburg </LOCATION>, when more than 1,000 re-enactors will organize an encampment and simulate the battle, firing blanks from original and authentic-looking Civil War guns and cannons. It will culminate in three days in July with a re-creation of the conflict that became the `` high water mark of the Confederacy.'' On July 1, 1863, the <ORGANIZATION> Confederate </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Northern </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Virgina </ORGANIZATION> pushed the <ORGANIZATION> Union </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> the </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Potomac </ORGANIZATION> from its positions north and west of the town to its final defense line, to sites like <LOCATION> Little </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Round </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Top </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Cemetery </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hill </LOCATION>, Devil's <PERSON> Den </PERSON>, <PERSON> Culp </PERSON>'s <PERSON> Hill </PERSON>, <PERSON> Spangler </PERSON>'s Spring. Col. <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Pickett </PERSON>'s charge, a frontal assault on July 3, sent 12,000 Confederate soldiers toward the Union line. Less than 4,000 returned. On July 4, <PERSON> Lee </PERSON>'s army withdrew, never to return to the North. Some 160,000 soldiers took part in that battle 125 years ago; there were some 50,000 casualties. A few months later, a national cemetery was dedicated at the <LOCATION> Gettysburg </LOCATION> battlefield. President <PERSON> Lincoln </PERSON> gave a brief speech. On Nov. 19 this year, the now-famous <LOCATION> Gettysburg </LOCATION> Address will be re-enacted with an actor portraying <PERSON> Lincoln </PERSON> leading the procession from the original railroad station to the National Cemetery. <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> Chief Justice <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Rehnquist </PERSON> is scheduled to re-read the address.
