<HEAD>Comcast, Tele-Communications Acquiring Storer Cable Properties</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BILL MENEZES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A proposal by two of the nation's biggest cable television concerns to pay about $ 1.55 billion for the cable systems of the former <ORGANIZATION> Storer </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Communications </ORGANIZATION> follows a bigger consortium's abortive proposal to buy the properties at a higher price. <ORGANIZATION> Comcast </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Tele-Communications </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> announced Sunday they had a definitive agreement to acquire <ORGANIZATION> SCI </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Holdings </ORGANIZATION>, the company formed when <PERSON> Storer </PERSON> was taken private by the investment firm <ORGANIZATION> Kohlberg </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> , </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Kravis </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; <PERSON> Roberts </PERSON> in a $ 2.5 billion leveraged buyout in 1985. SCI last year sold its six television stations for about $ 1.4 billion, leaving it with cable television systems serving about 1.48 million subscribers in 12 states in the East and <LOCATION> South </LOCATION>. The acquisition is subject to regulatory approval and other conditions. <ORGANIZATION> Comcast </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Tele-Communications </ORGANIZATION> both members of the consortium that proposed and later dropped a plan to acquire SCI for about $ 2.9 billion earlier this year. <ORGANIZATION> SCI </ORGANIZATION> said in December it had gotten a letter of intent for the acquisition by the consortium, which included <ORGANIZATION> Comcast </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Television </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Communications </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, which is owned by <ORGANIZATION> Time </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, and <ORGANIZATION> Taft </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cable </ORGANIZATI