RGANIZATION> posted a net loss of $ 9.4 million in its 1987 fiscal year, compared with a 1986 profit of $ 1 million, or 3 cents a share, due to the costs of financing several acquisitions and to accounting factors. Revenue rose to $ 309.2 million from $ 130.8 million. <ORGANIZATION> Tele-Communications </ORGANIZATION> owns or controls cable systems serving about six million subscribers, according to industry estimates. It also owns a 52 percent stake in the operations of the newly merged <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Artists </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Entertainment </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, which has interests in cable television and movie theaters. <ORGANIZATION> Tele-Communications </ORGANIZATION> posted a profit of $ 5.6 million, or 4 cents a share, in its 1987 fiscal year, down from $ 72.3 million, or 48 cents a share, the previous year. Its revenue rose to $ 1.7 billion from $ 645.7 million. The company blamed the earnings decline on the costs of financing its acquisition of <ORGANIZATION> Heritage </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Communications </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> and costs related to its investment in <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Artists </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Entertainment </ORGANIZATION>. The profit figures included one-time gains of $ 42.4 million in 1987 and $ 165 million in 1986 from asset sales, and a charge of $ 22.5 million in 1986 from settlement of litigation.
