<HEAD>Textile Maker Accepts $1.2 Billion Takeover Proposal</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: New throughout to UPDATE with morning stock price, details;
no pickup.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Textile giant <ORGANIZATION> J.P. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stevens </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, target of a protracted takeover battle, has accepted a $ 1.2 billion cash offer from two buyers after initially rejecting the deal, the companies involved said today. The $ 68.50-a-share deal will split up the 175-year-old fabric maker, one of the nation's largest textile producers and an important employer in the southeastern <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. The major buyer is rival textile producer <ORGANIZATION> West </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Point </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Pepperell </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, which will keep most of <PERSON> Stevens </PERSON>' sheet and towel operations but sell some to another textile producer, <ORGANIZATION> Bibb </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> of <LOCATION> Macon </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ga. </LOCATION>, to satisfy previously announced federal antitrust concerns. <ORGANIZATION> Odyssey </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Partners </ORGANIZATION>, a Wall Street investment firm that had been vying with <LOCATION> Pepperell </LOCATION> to buy <PERSON> Stevens </PERSON>, will get the company's other operations, including its carpet and industrial fabrics plants, for about $ 530 million. <LOCATION> Pepperell </LOCATION> and <PERSON> Odyssey </PERSON> arranged the purchase with <PERSON> Stevens </PERSON> after an initial $ 1.2 billion offer was rejected, partly because of the target company's concerns about the tentative nature of Odyssey's financing The terms were revised over the weekend to <PERSON> Stevens </PERSON>' satisfaction, and the deal was accepted In early trading on the <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stock </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION>, <PERSON> Stevens </PERSON> rose 25 cents to $ 67.75 a share. <LOCATION> Pepperell </LOCATION> has made its bids in conjunction with the <ORGANIZATION> NTC </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Group </ORGANIZATION>, parent of <PERSON> Bibb </PERSON>. Under terms of the agreement with <PERSON> Stevens </PERSON>, the <LOCATION> Pepperell </LOCATION> group will acquire the entire company for $ 68.50 a share under a tender offer that will expire at midnight EDT May 6, unless extended. Odyssey will then purchase its portion of the the <PERSON> Stevens </PERSON> assets from <LOCATION> Pepperell </LOCATION>. But if <LOCATION> Pepperell </LOCATION> can not complete its end of the deal, <ORGANIZATION> Odyssey </ORGANIZATION> has agreed to purchase <PERSON> Stevens </PERSON>, subject to financing. Odyssey's outstanding $ 68.50-a-share tender offer has been extended to May 20. <LOCATION> Pepperell </LOCATION>'s interest in <PERSON> Stevens </PERSON> has centered exclusively on the company's sheet and towel operations, which include manufacturing facilities as well as designer brand names. Those operations account for 60 percent of <PERSON> Stevens </PERSON>' annual sales, which amounted to $ 1.61 billion last year. Among the top brand names in <PERSON> Stevens </PERSON>' towel and sheet arsenal are <PERSON> Ralph </PERSON> <PERSON> Lauren </PERSON>, <PERSON> Laura </PERSON> <PERSON> Ashley </PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION> Gloria </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Vanderbilt </ORGANIZATION>, <PERSON> Perry </PERSON> <PERSON> Ellis </PERSON>, <PERSON> Pierre </PERSON> <PERSON> Cardin </PERSON> and <PERSON> Givenchy </PERSON>, among others. <LOCATION> Pepperell </LOCATION>'s brands include Arrow, Martex, <PERSON> Lady </PERSON> <PERSON> Pepperell </PERSON> and <PERSON> Burberry </PERSON>. Headquartered in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Stevens </PERSON> employs more than 23,000 people. The takeover maneuvering for the company began earlier this year when management offered to buy it for $ 765 million. <LOCATION> Pepperell </LOCATION> and Odyssey went three rounds in a heated bidding contest before announcing last week that they would work together to draft a joint buyout proposal.
