<HEAD>Firestone Loses Tire Supply Deal with GM</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 10 grafs to UPDATE with shareholders voting to
accept buyout offer by Bridgestone; picks up 8th graf pvs bg'ng,
Firestone's statement ...; Adds byline.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By DAVID DISHNEAU</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Shareholders of Firestone Tire and <ORGANIZATION> Rubber </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> have voted overwhelmingly in favor of the $ 2.6 billion buyout by <ORGANIZATION> Bridgestone </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> of <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>, Firestone Chairman <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Nevin </PERSON> said today. The Japanese tiremaker's $ 80-a-share offer was supported by 99.3 percent of the 58 percent of shareholders who voted on the question, said <PERSON> Nevin </PERSON>, who announced the outcome at a special shareholders' meeting this morning. <ORGANIZATION> Bridgestone </ORGANIZATION>'s tender offer expires Tuesday, and the acquisition could become effective Wednesday, <PERSON> Nevin </PERSON> said. Approval of the <ORGANIZATION> Bridgestone </ORGANIZATION> offer comes on the heels of <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Motors </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>'s announcement that it would drop <PERSON> Firestone </PERSON> as a tire supplier for its vehicles. <PERSON> Nevin </PERSON> would not speculate on why <ORGANIZATION> GM </ORGANIZATION> made the decision. `` To a Japanese company, the long term is considerably more important. We'll look at this as anything one has to deal with in the business world and decide what path the company has to take in the future,'' said <ORGANIZATION> Bridgestone </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> Dennis </PERSON> <PERSON> Allen </PERSON>. <ORGANIZATION> GM </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Crellin </PERSON> said the automaker's action was part of `` our rationalization study,'' which is a periodic review of capacity and future needs of suppliers. <PERSON> Crellin </PERSON> declined to discuss how long the phaseout of Firestone tires would take or discuss the amount of business <ORGANIZATION> GM </ORGANIZATION> does with its suppliers. `` We've got four other tire suppliers: General Tire, <ORGANIZATION> Goodyear </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Michelin </ORGANIZATION> and Uniroyal-Goodrich,'' <PERSON> Crellin </PERSON> said. `` There are no plans to look for another supplier at this time. We will be informing the other four tire suppliers of the availability of increased business.'' <PERSON> Nevin </PERSON> said in a statement issued Saturday that he was `` surprised and disappointed'' by <ORGANIZATION> GM </ORGANIZATION>'s move but said <PERSON> Firestone </PERSON> is confident it will find other markets for its tires without hurting profits. <PERSON> Firestone </PERSON>'s statement offered no reason for <ORGANIZATION> GM </ORGANIZATION>'s action, but the company said it was `` advised by <ORGANIZATION> Bridgestone </ORGANIZATION> that the action will have no effect'' on the $ 80-a-share buyout offer. <PERSON> Firestone </PERSON> said the phase-out would occur over two years. Estimates in the trade publication Modern Tire Dealer show that <ORGANIZATION> GM </ORGANIZATION> buys about 34 percent of its tires from <ORGANIZATION> Uniroyal-Goodrich </ORGANIZATION>, making it <ORGANIZATION> GM </ORGANIZATION>'s largest tire supplier. <ORGANIZATION> Goodyear </ORGANIZATION> is second at 22.5 percent, <PERSON> Firestone </PERSON> third with 20 percent, General Tire fourth at 17.5 percent and <ORGANIZATION> Michelin </ORGANIZATION> fifth at 4.5 percent. Firestone moved its corporate headquarters in November from <LOCATION> Akron </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ohio </LOCATION>, to <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION>. It operates four <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> plants with 1,400 employees at its main plant in <LOCATION> Akron </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Firestone </PERSON> agreed to be acquired in March by <ORGANIZATION> Bridgestone </ORGANIZATION>, after an unsolicited takeover bid by <LOCATION> Italy </LOCATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Pirelli </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> SpA </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Kimball </PERSON> <PERSON> Firestone </PERSON>, a <ORGANIZATION> Firestone </ORG