<HEAD>SEC Delays Enactment Of Mutual Fund Rule</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Securities </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> said Monday it was delaying by two months the effective date of a rule designed to make it easier for investors to shop for mutual funds. The commission said mutual funds can wait until July 1 before they must calculate yield in a standardized way so that consumers can readily compare the track records of competing funds. When the commission decided on the new rule in January, it set May 1 as the effective date. However, the <ORGANIZATION> Investment </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Company </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION>, a trade group for mutual funds, said its members needed more time to adjust their computer and accounting systems. The <ORGANIZATION> SEC </ORGANIZATION>, in response, has decided to allow funds to advertise their yield using the old methods of calculation through the end of June. However, the funds will have to disclose in the ads that the yield is not computed according to <ORGANIZATION> SEC </ORGANIZATION> standards. Shares in mutual funds are offered by investment companies that collect money from investors to buy stocks, bonds, commodities, options and other investment products.
