<HEAD>Steel Output Fell 0.9 Percent in Week</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Steel production fell to 1.970 million tons in the week ended April 23, a decrease of 0.9 percent from the previous week's 1.987 million tons, the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Iron </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Steel </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION> reported Monday. The industry's production amounted to 91.9 percent of capacity during the week, compared with 92.7 percent in the previous week. Estimated figures for the year to date showed production at 31.607 million net tons, an increase of 28.5 percent from the 24.595 million net tons in the previous year. The steel operations of <ORGANIZATION> USX </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, the nation's largest steel producer, were shut down by a strike during the first month of 1987. Production so far this year used 90.4 percent of capacity, compared with 70.8 percent a year earlier. Net tonnage by district for the week ended April 23: <LOCATION> Northeast </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Coast </LOCATION>, 294,000; <LOCATION> Pittsburgh </LOCATION>, 198,000; <LOCATION> Youngstown </LOCATION>, 131,000; <LOCATION> Lake </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Erie </LOCATION>, 151,000; <LOCATION> Detroit </LOCATION>, 169,000; <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION>, 497,000; <LOCATION> Midwest </LOCATION>, 203,000; Southern, 225,000; and Western, 102,000.
