<HEAD>Exxon, Mobil, Other Companies Report Strong Quarterly Earnings</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN C. GIVEN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Major <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> oil companies, led by top-ranking <ORGANIZATION> Exxon </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> and second-largest <ORGANIZATION> Mobil </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, reported strong improvements in their first-quarter earnings Monday, many citing sharp gains in refining and marketing, as well as chemicals. <ORGANIZATION> Amoco </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Occidental </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Petroleum </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Unocal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> also reported hefty increases. <ORGANIZATION> Exxon </ORGANIZATION> said its earnings were up 36 percent to $ 1.46 billion, or $ 1.06 per share, compared with $ 1.07 billion, or 75 cents per share, in the 1987 first quarter. Sales totaled $ 22.0 billion vs. $ 19.4 billion a year earlier, it said. <ORGANIZATION> Mobil </ORGANIZATION> said its quarterly profit doubled to $ 505 million, or $ 1.23 per share, compared with $ 252 million, or 62 cents per share in the 1987 period. Revenue from continuing operations totaled $ 13.8 billion vs. $ 11.7 billion in the first three months of last year. Both companies are based in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>. Among the others: _ <ORGANIZATION> Amoco </ORGANIZATION>, of <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION>, said its earnings leaped 80.4 percent, to $ 469 million, or $ 1.82 per share, vs. 1987 first-quarter earnings of $ 260 million, or $ 1.02 per share Sales totaled $ 5.8 billion in the first three months, compared with $ 5.2 billion in the 1987 period, the nation's fifth-largest petroleum company said. _ <ORGANIZATION> Occidental </ORGANIZATION>, ranked seventh, said its earnings increased by 16.5 percent to $ 113 million, or 52 cents per share, compared with $ 97 million, or 50 cents per share, a year earlier Both periods included extraordinary gains, however. The Los Angeles-based company said its sales totaled $ 4.48 billion in the three months, compared with $ 4.16 billion in the 1987 first quarter. _ <ORGANIZATION> Unocal </ORGANIZATION> said its earnings nearly tripled, but were also affected by special items The company, ranked 13th-largest, is also headquartered in <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION>. <ORGANIZATION> Unocal </ORGANIZATION>'s quarterly earnings totaled $ 178.4 million, or $ 1.53 per share, on $ 2.3 billion of revenue, vs. $ 60.7 billion, or 52 cents per share, on sales of $ 2.06 billion in the same period of 1987. Included in those results were a $ 456 million one-time gain due to an accounting change related to income taxes. This was partially offset by an post-tax charge of $ 322 million for a writedown of certain company assets, the company said. `` Excess supplies and weak winter demand associated with warmer-than-normal weather caused crude prices to move sharply lower during the quarter. Crude prices in last year's first quarter were higher and relatively stable,'' observed <ORGANIZATION> Exxon </ORGANIZATION> Chairman L.G. <PERSON> Rawl </PERSON>. The sharply lower crude prices, together with much stronger margins for petroleum products and record chemical earnings were `` fundamentally responsible'' for <ORGANIZATION> Exxon </ORGANIZATION>'s overall earnings improvement, he added. `` The quarterly comparison was helped by sale of property abroad and lower incentive compensation costs in 1988, but the effect of these benefits was largely offset by the absence of 1987 foreign exchange gains and tax credits associated with foreign operations,'' <PERSON> Rawl </PERSON> said. <ORGANIZATION> Mobil </ORGANIZATION> Chairman <PERSON> Allen </PERSON> <PERSON> E. </PERSON> <PERSON> Murray </PERSON> said the company's quarterly performance was the best since 1981, with the most important improvements occurring in its domestic refining and marketing segment and chemicals, which posted its `` best quarter ever.'' The latest report did not reflect the impact of <ORGANIZATION> Mobil </ORGANIZATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Montgomery </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ward </ORGANIZATION> unit, which was sold on March 7 <ORGANIZATION> Mobil </ORGANIZATION> said the retailer made $ 19 million in profits, compared with $ 8 million in the first quarter of 1987. Those profits and proceeds from the sale will be posted in the second quarter, the company said. <ORGANIZATION> Amoco </ORGANIZATION> Chairman <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> M. </PERSON> <PERSON> Morrow </PERSON> attributed the company's performance to substantial strengthening of refined product margins, compared with the same period last year, along with continued record earnings by its chemicals division In <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Occidental </ORGANIZATION> Chairman <PERSON> Armand </PERSON> <PERSON> Hammer </PERSON> said chemical operations more than tripled during the quarter. The company said its 1988 results included an after-tax gain of $ 53 million, primarily from the sale of a 25 percent interest in its <LOCATION> Colombia </LOCATION> oil holdings, as well as extraordinary gains of $ 2 million, primarily from capital loss carryforwards. Its 1987 first-quarter results included a post-tax gain of $ 103 million from the sale of certain chemical operations plus $ 24 million in capital loss carryforwards. <PERSON> Fred </PERSON> <PERSON> L. </PERSON> <PERSON> Hartley </PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION> Unocal </ORGANIZATION>'s chairman, said the main negative factors affecting quarterly performance were higher dry hole costs and exploratory expense and lower geothermal earnings and domestic crude prices. These were offset somewhat by higher natural gas production in <LOCATION> Thailand </LOCATION> and higher refining and marketing profits, he added. The writedowns included <ORGANIZATION> Unocal </ORGANIZATION>'s remaining investment in a shale oil project, about half its investment in mining and processing facilities in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Pennsylvania </LOCATION> and 40 percent of its investment in certain coking facilities at its <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION> refinery.
