<FIRST>u f AM-Dollar-Gold     04-25 0585</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Dollar-Gold,0604</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Mixed, Gold Slightly Lower</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICK GLADSTONE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The dollar ended mixed in light trading Monday, reflecting dealer reluctance to speculate prior to potentially market-moving developments later this week. Gold prices fell marginally after rising in <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> and falling in <LOCATION> Asia </LOCATION>. <ORGANIZATION> Republic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> quoted bullion at $ 447.50 a troy ounce as of 4 p.m. EDT, compared with $ 449.50 late Friday. Money dealers attributed the dollar's mixed behavior partly to uncertainty about the impact of a government report on first-quarter <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> economic growth due out Tuesday. They also said the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION>'s impending vote on a major trade bill, along with questions about the outcome of a planned <ORGANIZATION> OPEC </ORGANIZATION> meeting with non-cartel oil exporters, injected uncertainty into foreign exchange trading. `` There's not much to say today,'' said <PERSON> Christianne </PERSON> <PERSON> Mandell </PERSON>, a trading analyst at the <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> branch of <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Barclay </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> PLC </ORGANIZATION>. `` It was quiet because there's anticipation about events that are happening later. Until those things come out, there wo n't be information to trade on.'' Traders said the <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION>'s report on the gross national product would be a tricky number to interpret. Estimates range between 1.5 percent and 3 percent, but it will be the underlying components of that figure that influence the dollar's value For example, if first-quarter GNP is high, that could boost the dollar provided that the growth was caused by strength in exports, thereby helping reduce the trade deficit. But if the growth was caused by strong consumer demand for foreign goods, that suggests higher imports, a widening trade deficit and a further decline in the dollar. On the other hand, a substantially lower GNP could boost the dollar because it implies a slowdown in imports. But it also could hurt the dollar by relieving pressure for higher domestic interest rates, traders said. `` It's really a Catch-22 situation,'' said <PERSON> Alberto </PERSON> <PERSON> Soria </PERSON>, foreign exchange manager at the <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> branch of <ORGANIZATION> Swiss </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp </ORGANIZATION>. In <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION>, where trading ends before <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>'s business day begins, the dollar rose 0.35 yen to a closing 125.00 yen. In <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> it retreated to 124.60 yen, and in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> it traded at 124.73 yen, down from 124.91 yen late Friday. The British pound fell in <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> to $ 1.8730, cheaper than the $ 1.8880 reached Friday, largely because of weekend remarks by <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>'s Chancellor of the Exchequer <PERSON> Nigel </PERSON> <PERSON> Lawson </PERSON> that sterling should n't rise further. In <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> the pound fetched $ 1.8736, cheaper than $ 1.8840 quoted Friday. Other late dollar rates in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> compared with levels late Friday: 1.6753 West German marks, down from 1.6758; 1.3873 Swiss francs, up from 1.3849; 1.2317 Canadian dollars, down from 1.2324; 5.6862 French francs, up from 5.6845; and 1,244.75 Italian lire, up from 1,244.50. Late dollar rates in <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> compared with late Friday: 1.6765 West German marks, up from 1.6730; 1.3860 Swiss francs, up from 1.3840; 5.6915 French francs, up from 5.6865; 1.8790 Dutch guilders, up from 1.8770; and 1.2309 Canadian dollars, down from 1.2324; 1,245.50 lire, up from 1,244.50. On the Commodity Exchange in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>, gold for current delivery fetched $ 448.90 an ounce, down $ 2. Gold closed in <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> at $ 449.50 a troy ounce, up from $ 449 Friday. In <LOCATION> Zurich </LOCATION> the late bid price was $ 450 vs. $ 449, and in <LOCATION> Hong </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Kong </LOCATION> it was $ 451.13 vs. $ 451.58. On the Comex, silver for current delivery fetched $ 6.355, off 5 cents. Silver was quoted in <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> late Monday at a bid price of $ 6.42 a troy ounce, down from $ 6.46 Friday.
