N> <ORGANIZATION> Exporting </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Countries </ORGANIZATION> and non-OPEC oil-producing countries, which could lead to an inflationary agreement to limit oil production. Gold settled $ 2 to $ 2.30 lower with June at $ 450.10 a troy ounce; silver was 5 cents lower across the board with May at $ 6.365 a troy ounce. Nervousness about Tuesday's oil meeting also overshadowed the energy futures market at the <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mercantile </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION>, where prices finished mixed. West Texas Intermediate crude oil settled 10 cents to 12 cents higher with June at $ 18.40 a barrel; heating oil was .04 cent to .61 cent higher with May at 51.21 cents a gallon; unleaded gasoline was .24 cent lower to .65 cent higher with May at 52.05 cents a gallon. Grain and soybean futures settled mostly lower on the <ORGANIZATION> Chicago </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trade </ORGANIZATION> despite indications early in the session that demand for soybean products was stronger than anticipated. The soybean complex had led the grain markets higher in early trading after the <ORGANIZATION> Census </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bureau </ORGANIZATION> reported lower-than-expected stocks of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> soybean meal at the end of March. Corn futures weakened on poor export sales. The wheat market succumbed to continuing fears about dryness in the spring wheat growing region of the <LOCATION> northern </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Plains </LOCATION>, said <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Loewy </PERSON>, senior grain and oilseed analyst for <ORGANIZATION> Prudential-Bache </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Securities </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>. Wheat settled 2 -RCB- cents to 3 -RCB- cents lower with May at $ 