<HEAD>Soviet Economy Ailing, New Figures Show</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 3 grafs to CORRECT percent to percentage points in
second graf, CORRECTS 3rd graf to show income increased 4 percent
over first quarter, sted in first quarter; picks up 4th graf pvs,
The first ... A version moving on general news wires.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By ANDREW KATELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 From shoes to machines, the Soviet economy had trouble meeting the country's needs in the first three months of this year, the government said Monday in a sobering report on <PERSON> Mikhail </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>'s reforms. Perhaps the most telling admission in the lengthy report was that national income, the overall barometer of the country's economic health, fell 2.6 percentage points short of the planned level National income went up 4 percent over the first quarter of 1987, whereas the plan called for an increase of 6.6 percent. The same shortfall was reported in labor productivity. The first quarter of 1987, to which the new figures are being compared, was marred by overall poor performance. `` Now it's important for everything designated not to remain only on paper,'' the <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ministers </ORGANIZATION>, the government's Cabinet, said Monday in reviewing the economic report The council stressed that many of the economy's bottlenecks were hurting the country's 285.2 million people. `` The shortcomings noted in the work of a series of industries and complexes became serious brakes in the buildup of production and increase in people's well-being,'' the council said, according to the news agency <ORGANIZATION> Tass </ORGANIZATION>. The report covered a period in which a new system was introduced in the Soviet economy. As of Jan. 1, more than 76,000 state-run factories and farms responsible for 60 percent of the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>'s production were required to depend on themselves for the revenue they need to operate. That is one of the key elements of <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>'s economic reforms, aimed at giving local managers more responsibility and flexibility. The Communist Party chief wants to limit central authorities to overall planning of the economy and allow local managers to exercise direct control over production plans and quotas. The media said the reforms were not to blame for the shortcomings noted in the report. Industries and farms operating under the new requirements `` are performing better than those working in the old way,'' <ORGANIZATION> Radio </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Moscow </ORGANIZATION> said. Industrial production increased 5 percent over the first quarter of 1987, exceeding the 4.5 percent target set in state plans, <ORGANIZATION> Radio </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Moscow </ORGANIZATION> quoted <PERSON> Nikolai </PERSON> <PERSON> Belov </PERSON>, deputy head of the <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> on </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Statistics </ORGANIZATION>, as saying. Energy production, transportation equipment, computers and medical equipment all grew strongly, the statistics said. But one-third of the machine-building industry, a key sector in <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>'s drive for greater efficiency, did not complete its orders, the Council of Ministers noted. Among the specific problems cited in the report, splashed over two pages of the government newspaper <ORGANIZATION> Izvestia </ORGANIZATION>, were shortcomings in consumer products. It sais 87,000 radio receivers, 44,000 washing machines and 44,000 vacuum cleaners called for in state plans were not produced. Clothing and shoes were either in short supply or were left unpurchased because they were old-fashioned or of poor quality. In agriculture, meat, vegetable and dairy production failed to satisfy people's needs, and in some areas bread quality and assortment was poor, the report said. Of the 15 Soviet republics, <LOCATION> Armenia </LOCATION> had the worst record from January to March for fulfillment of industrial contract obligations. Armenian factories completed just 98.5 percent of their orders, compared to a high of 99.9 percent for <LOCATION> Byelorussia </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Latvia </LOCATION>. The report also criticized <LOCATION> Armenia </LOCATION> for not raising workers salaries, improving household services or building schools, hospitals and cultural centers. During much of February, many of <LOCATION> Armenia </LOCATION>'s factories, schools and businesses were closed in a strike prompted by an ethnic dispute. The report was released as <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> intelligence agencies released in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> an assessment saying that <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>'s reforms ran into serious obstacles in 1987. A joint report by the <ORGANIZATION> Central </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Intelligence </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agency </ORGANIZATION> and the <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Intelligence </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agency </ORGANIZATION> said the Soviet gross national product increased only 0.5 percent in 1987, compared with a 3.9 percent increase the previous year. It said the poor performance in 1987 was due to poor weather that hurt farm production and resistance to change in the Soviet bureaucracy. National income, the barometer the Soviets use, is a measurement of economic activity that differs from gross national product because it does not consider the value of some services.
</TEXT>
