<HEAD>Senate in Last-Ditch Scramble for Trade Bill Votes</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 3rd graf pvs, bgng: ``The bill ...'' to UDPATE with vote
now scheduled for Tuesday or Wednesday.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MIKE ROBINSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Senators traded last-minute sales pitches Monday as they fought for votes on a sweeping trade bill advancing in defiance of presidential veto threats. `` You let this bill go down the tubes and I'll tell you where the champagne corks will be popping _ they'll be popping in <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> and they'll be popping in <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>,'' said <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Finance </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> Chairman <PERSON> Lloyd </PERSON> <PERSON> Bentsen </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-Texas </LOCATION>. The bill, scheduled for a <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> vote on Tuesday or Wednesday, was expected to pass with votes to spare and the major question remaining was whether it would get enough support to override a veto. `` It's close,'' <PERSON> Bentsen </PERSON> told reporters. Democrats were expected to back the measure overwhelmingly while Republicans were divided. The administration and its supporters said a veto would not finish off the issue for the year and that there still would be time to pass a stripped-down version that deleted the most controversial provisions. `` I know this is an election year and the majority party may be looking for a campaign issue rather than a trade bill, but I am confident the <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> could pass a better bill if this one is rejected,'' said Sen. <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> T. </PERSON> <PERSON> Stafford </PERSON>, D-Vt. The <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> passed the 1,000-page measure on Thursday 312-107, more than enough support to override President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>'s threatened veto. Over the last month, the administration has focused most of its criticism on a provision that would require all but the smallest employers to provide 60-day notice of plant closings and large-scale layoffs. A number of business groups have campaigned against the measure, saying it would dry up capital for investment, frighten off customers and cause other problems for management. Basic provisions of the bill would overhaul the system under which the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> imposes import curbs in retaliation for international trade violations and other unfair practices. Among other things, it would make retaliation mandatory for violations except in certain cases, such as national security. It also would transfer from the president to the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> trade representative the authority to determine whether retaliation was in order and, if so, what kind of sanctions to impose. Other central features would streamline the machinery under which the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> imposes import quotas and tariffs to aid American industries that are threatened by surges in foreign competition. The measure contains scores of other features ranging from billions of dollars in agricultural subsidies to repeal of the windfall profits tax on earnings of oil companies.
