<HEAD>Judge Tentatively Approves Settlement With Home State Accountant</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CINCINNATI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A state judge tentatively approved on Monday a proposed $ 5.5 million settlement of <LOCATION> Ohio </LOCATION>'s lawsuit against <ORGANIZATION> Arthur </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Andersen </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, accounting firm for the collapsed <ORGANIZATION> Home </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Savings </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION>. Judge <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Niehaus </PERSON> of <ORGANIZATION> Hamilton </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> County </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Common </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Pleas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> said he would accept objections to the proposed settlement and make a final ruling on May 6. The state blamed the firm for negligence in auditing Home State's books, which <LOCATION> Ohio </LOCATION> officials said contributed to the March 1985 collapse of the Cincinnati-based thrift. <PERSON> Arthur </PERSON> <PERSON> Andersen </PERSON> denied the state's allegations and admitted no wrongdoing in reaching the settlement. The settlement was reached April 15, after the case already had gone to trial in the <LOCATION> Ohio </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Court </LOCATION> of Claims in <LOCATION> Columbus </LOCATION>. The case is before <PERSON> Niehaus </PERSON> because he has jurisdiction over the state's liquidation of Home State The case is one of numerous civil suits the state filed in its efforts to recover costs of guaranteeing all the deposits of Home State after its collapsed. Home State was closed for three months until another company bought and reopened it in June 1985, allowing depositors to get their money back. Home State collapsed three days after the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Securities </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATIO