<HEAD>Goodyear Reports Stronger Core Earnings</HEAD>
<DATELINE>AKRON, Ohio (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Goodyear </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Tire </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; <ORGANIZATION> Rubber </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> reported Monday that its first quarter profit from continuing operations rose by 14.2 percent from the previous year, due largely to the company's focus on its core tire business <ORGANIZATION> Goodyear </ORGANIZATION> posted net income of $ 95.3 million, or $ 1.67 per share, all from continuing operations, during the quarter ended March 31. That compared with a profit of $ 284.2 million, or $ 3.99 per share, a year earlier, which included $ 200.8 million from discontinued operations. Sales during the quarter rose to $ 2.6 billion from $ 2.3 billion in first quarter 1987. <ORGANIZATION> Goodyear </ORGANIZATION> last year sold its <ORGANIZATION> Goodyear </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Aerospace </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Motor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Wheel </ORGANIZATION> and Celeron Oil and Gas operations, plus other assets. The company sold those assets under a major restructuring following an unsuccessful hostile takeover attempt by the international businessman Sir <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Goldsmith </PERSON>. <ORGANIZATION> Goodyear </ORGANIZATION> Chairman <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> E. </PERSON> <PERSON> Mercer </PERSON> said the latest quarterly results reflected increased global demand for the company's tire products. <ORGANIZATION> Goodyear </ORGANIZATION> also reported sales growth in its other businesses, including chemicals, film, industrial hoses, conveyor belts and power transmission products.
