<HEAD>Trade Bill's Fate Debated Before Publishers</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 7th graf ``The other...'' to CORRECT name to Makoto,
sted Macota.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By CHRISTINE DONNELLY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HONOLULU (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 An omnibus trade bill that President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> has promised to veto could be revised easily to his liking with its major provisions intact, the chairman of the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trade </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> said Monday. `` I think you're a bit premature in calling in the undertaker,'' <PERSON> Susan </PERSON> <PERSON> Liebeler </PERSON> told fellow panalists discussing the bill. The issue was raised at the 102nd annual convention of the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Newspaper </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Publishers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> here. The trade bill passed the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> by 312-107 last week and is to be voted on by the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> this week. <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> objects to a provision requiring most manufacturers to give 60 days notice of plant closings and major layoffs. <PERSON> Liebeler </PERSON> said she thought that <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> would veto the bill and that, in a revised version, the notification provision would be dropped and the bill approved. `` You may in fact see a trade bill the administration will sign,'' she said. The other panalists were <PERSON> Makoto </PERSON> <PERSON> Kuroda </PERSON>, vice minister for international affairs in <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trade </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Industry </ORGANIZATION>; <PERSON> Pat </PERSON> <PERSON> Choate </PERSON>, vice president for policy at <ORGANIZATION> TRW </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>; and <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> H. </PERSON> <PERSON> Davidson </PERSON>, an associate professor at the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Southern </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> California </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> School </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Business </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION>. The Japanese government has urged <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> to veto the bill, which would punish <ORGANIZATION> Toshiba </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> for a subsidiary's sale of sensitive equipment to the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> and give the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> trade representative more power to deal with complaints of unfair trade practices by foreign countries. The panalists were divided on the bill, with <PERSON> Kuroda </PERSON> voicing opposition and <PERSON> Choate </PERSON> and <PERSON> Davidson </PERSON> supporting it. The flip side of the trade issue, <PERSON> Choate </PERSON> said, was foreign investment in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, an issue he said the federal government was ill-equipped to handle because it did not keep an accurate count of money invested by foreigners. `` How can we have a good policy without good information?'' <PERSON> Choate </PERSON> asked. <PERSON> Kuroda </PERSON> said <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>'s investment in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> would help revitalize the economy's of both countries and provide for technological transfer. The discussion, called `` International Trade: Is Protectionism Dead?'', was moderated by <PERSON> Karen </PERSON> <PERSON> Elliot </PERSON> <PERSON> House </PERSON>, foreign editor of the Wall Street Journal. The panel was the first group discussion in the three-day convention, which began Monday. More than 2,000 people, including about 1,500 publishers who represent 90 percent of the daily newspaper circulation in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, are attending.
